<DOCNO> AP880714-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     07-14 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Driving Down Meat Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a couple of bumper corn crops and
relatively low feed prices, livestock producers thought they saw
some daylight ahead, but the dark may be closing in again, an
Agriculture Department report shows.
   The drought and sizzling heat of May and June have already
squeezed livestock producers and could hurt them further if
conditions persist much longer, the department's Economic Research
Service said Wednesday.
   ``Rising costs brought on by drought are affecting livestock and
poultry producers' returns,'' the agency said in a new outlook
summary. ``Also, poor pasture and range conditions are reducing
forage supplies for cattle and lamb producers.''
   The report added, ``If the drought continues, hog and cattle
slaughter may be boosted, adding to already record red meat and
poultry supplies.''
   Market prices of cattle dropped in June, following record high
levels during the spring, and likely resulted, in part, from large
meat supplies, the report said.
   ``Feeder cattle prices weakened in response to lower fed cattle
prices and rising feed costs,'' it said. ``While lower feeder
cattle prices reduce returns to cow-calf producers, the more
immediate problem is poor pasture and water conditions.''
   Although hay cut from land idled under federal programs has
helped, there will be more pressure to reduce the cattle inventory
if pastures continue to deteriorate, the report said.
   Total production of red meat and poultry in 1988 is expected to
rise 3 percent to a record 59.9 billion pounds, but all the gain
will be from pork, lamb and mutton, and poultry.
   Beef production this year was forecast at 22.9 billion pounds,
down 2 percent from last year.
   Pork output, at 15.6 billion pounds, would be up 9 percent from
1987. Lamb and mutton was shown at 326 million pounds, up 6
percent. Veal, however, is expected to decline 5 percent from last
year to 397 million pounds.
   Federally inspected poultry production this year was forecast at
20.6 billion pounds, led by a 4 percent increase in broiler output
to nearly 16.2 billion pounds. Turkey production was forecast at
3.89 billion pounds, up 4 percent from 1987.
   Economists said market prices of Choice-grade steers at Omaha,
Neb., may average $65 to $69 per 100 pounds of liveweight in the
third quarter, down from $72.81 in the second. In the fourth
quarter, steer prices may average $68 to $71 per hundredweight.
   Hog prices at the major markets were forecast at $43 to $47 per
100 pounds in the third quarter and $37 to $43 in the fourth,
compared with $45.90 in the second quarter.
   ``Rising poultry prices have more than offset higher feed
costs,'' the report said. ``Wholesale broiler prices are expected
to average 51 to 54 cents per pound (over all of this year), up
from 47 cents in 1987.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
150,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery this year under a
long-term supply agreement between the two countries, says the
Agriculture Department.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 150,000 tons of
corn would be about 5.9 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.70 per bushel at the
farm level, meaning that the sale reported Wednesday could have a
farm value of around $16 million.
   The corn is part of the grain the Soviet Union is committed to
buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls
for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of U.S. grain.
The pact expires Sept. 30.
   According to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to
include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The
Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as
wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two
tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain
equivalent.
   With the latest purchases, the Soviets now have bought 5.04
million tons of corn, plus more than 9 million tons of wheat;
830,700 tons of soybeans, and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers in counties not hit by drought may
harvest hay under various Agriculture Department acreage and
conservation programs if they donate it to those in
drought-stricken areas.
   Previously, hay could be taken only from idled program land in
counties approved for emergency haying or grazing due to drought.
There are nearly 2,000 of those designated counties in 37 states.
   A producer who wishes to donate hay should contact the local
office of the department's Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service for harvesting permission, Agriculture
Secretary Richard E. Lyng said Wednesday.
   The farmer than must donate the hay through a designated state
agency engaged in drought relief efforts.
</TEXT>
