<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CouncilWars     07-14 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Council Wars,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opponents of Mayor Purged from Committee Posts in Raucous Council
Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer consolidated his power with a
shakeup of committee chairmanships Wednesday night during a raucous
City Council meeting at which an opponent said Sawyer ``declared
war in the black community.''
   With Sawyer's blessing, his allies stripped his top political
rival in the black community, Alderman Timothy Evans, of
chairmanship of the Finance Committee, and dumped at least three
other black aldermen out of key posts.
   The reorganization was adopted on a vote of 26-17, with Sawyer,
who is black, relying on votes from white aldermen.
   Opponents of the mayor, most of them black, said the realignment
would add fuel to Evans' probable mayoral run in 1989.
   Only 15 months ago, black aldermen were united when the late
Mayor Harold Washington, the city's first black mayor, was
re-elected. But since Washington's death last November, and
Sawyer's elevation from alderman to acting mayor, black political
figures have divided their allegiance between Sawyer and Evans.
   ``Mr. Mayor, I think you've made a terrible mistake,'' said
Alderman Danny Davis, a black who lost chairmanship of the Zoning
Committee. ``It looks like everything we fought for, that Harold
Washington died for, is being turned back.
   ``What we have seen is an evil, sinister plot,'' added Davis,
himself mentioned as a possible mayoral candidate. ``It's a dark
day in the City of Chicago. I guess you and your colleagues have
declared war in the black community.''
   But Alderman Michael Sheahan, a white Sawyer supporter, said the
mayor was trying for a ``real balanced reorganization.''
   If Sawyer did not reorganize, Sheahan said, ``that's
surrendering.''
   Sawyer said he had to act ``to move the city ahead.''
   ``We have an agenda to move, a city to run,'' he said. ``They
have another agenda and it's not mine.''
   As part of the council committee reshuffling, Alderman Larry
Bloom, a white opponent of Sawyer who has his own mayoral
ambitions, lost chairmanship of the Budget Committee to Alderman
Lemuel Austin, a Sawyer supporter.
   The Housing Committee, formerly chaired by Sawyer opponent
Alderman Dorothy Tillman, was turned over to Alderman Sheneather
Butler.
   The meeting was punctuated by protests from the gallery as
various aldermen rose to defend or criticize the committee
reassignments. At one point, near the end of the meeting, police
officers rushed to the floor to break up a near-fight between Ms.
Tillman and Alderman Marlene Carter.
   Many of the audience members shouted, ``Go home, Uncle Tom!'' to
some of the black aldermen who defended the purge.
   A special election is scheduled next April to fill the final two
years of Washington's four-year term. Sawyer has said he will run,
and Evans has all but declared his own candidacy.
</TEXT>
