<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0028EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LibertyScholarships     07-14 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberty Scholarships,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Leaders Agree On Plan To Guarantee College For Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BELLAFIORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Needy New York state students will begin
getting a guaranteed free public college education beginning in
1991 under a program agreed to Wednesday by Gov. Mario Cuomo and
legislative leaders.
   Under the Liberty Scholarship program, students entering a New
York college in fall 1991 whose families have a gross adjusted
income of $18,000 or less would be given a scholarship worth the
difference between other grants they receive and their full college
costs including such things as books and transportation.
   The value of the scholarship would be geared to the average
tuition costs at State University of New York schools, but would be
available for students who chose to go instead to private colleges
in New York.
   That means that if a student was eligible for a $4,000 Liberty
Scholarship and decided to go to a private college where the annual
costs were $15,000, the student would still only get a $4,000
scholarship.
   ``We believe this is the most comprehensive and first program of
its kind in the United States,'' said Cuomo press secretary Gary
Fryer.
   When first proposed by Cuomo earlier this year, the Liberty
Scholarship idea was questioned by some legislators who said their
middle-class constituents might not look kindly on it. Cuomo said
that those who opposed it were being ``selfish.''
   The program is expected to be approved by the Legislature before
it ends it regular session, possibly as early as the end of this
week.
   The Liberty Scholarships, a key Cuomo initiative this year,
would be available at a reduced level for students from families
with annual incomes up to $26,000. Fryer said about 94,000
scholarships would be awarded when the program is fully implemented.
</TEXT>
