<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-14 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How do you keep 45 gallons of ice cream
in a 167-foot-long banana split from melting on a sunny Arkansas
afternoon?
   You arm 167 hungry Cub Scouts with plastic spoons.
   The lengthy dessert is a tradition at the annual Boy Scout
Jamboree. Day camp director Kay Morris has forgotten the first year
of the long split, but remembers the length.
   ``We started with 50 feet and have increased it every year,''
she said. ``We try to break our old record each year.''
   Camp staffers created the split Wednesday along a foil-covered
gutter using 45 gallons of ice cream, three three gallons of
chocolate syrup, two gallons of cherries, 15 cans of whipped cream
and a case of bananas.
   Because of the number of staffers involved, the concoction's
creation took only 10 minutes. Its consumption took the Cubs a
little longer.
   ``I'm eating like a pig,'' said 6-year-old John Starks of Fort
Smith, his face covered and his hair matted with ice cream and
chocolate sauce. He explained that after losing his spoon in the
giant treat, he bent over the ice cream and used his mouth. Moments
later, he spotted his spoon and plunged his hand in to retrieve it.
   A hose squad from the Fort Chaffee Fire Department eased the
cleanup.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood has gone to the dogs _ and so
has Glamour.
   Glamour magazine, that is. Its search for the ugliest dog in the
land led to a 53-pound bulldog named Dewey.
   His owners, Ellen and Bob Durfee, think their pooch is a peach.
   ``His looks are his personality,'' Ms. Durfee said.
   But they won't turn down the $50 prize that goes along with the
honor Glamour bestowed on Dewey.
   The dog was the unanimous choice of the magazine's Ugly Dog
Competition judges, beating out canines decked out in sunglasses
and bikinis.
   ``It was his face,'' executive editor Rona Cherry said Tuesday.
``You look at it and say `Oh my, that's an ugly dog.'''
   Dewey's mug graces the August issue of Glamour, which goes on
sale this week.
   The Durfees breed and show 3-year-old Dewey, who lives with them
and two other bulldogs, Winston and Lady.
   Dewey can only do one trick, Ms. Durfee said. He can sit while
wearing a hat.
   ``That's only after his nap, though,'' she said.
   Even if he's been proclaimed the ugliest dog in the nation, Ms.
Durfee says everyone doesn't find him unattractive.
   ``He's going to be a daddy any day now,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The toilet tissue crisis is over at the
historic Canton courthouse, thanks to the delivery of five cases of
fluffy white tissue, which ended a much-discussed drought of the
restroom item.
   ``We're smiling a lot more around here now,'' said Chancery
Clerk Billy Cooper, who last week dug into his own pocket to buy
tissue for paper-depleted restrooms.
   The county's supply of toilet tissue dried up last week because
the product was temporarily out-of-stock at the Jackson firm that
holds the state-approved contract for two-ply toilet tissue.
   ``It got so bad for paper we pulled out last year's tax rolls,''
Tax Assessor Gerald Barber said in jest.
   Madison County supervisors applauded word that relief was at
hand. ``I know everybody feels better around here now,'' said
superviors' President J.S. ``Brother'' Harris.
</TEXT>
