<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Family'sLoss     07-14 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family's Loss,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Russian Roulette Death Another Chapter in Family's Tragic History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who lost five children in an
apartment fire 25 years ago is now mourning with the death of their
17-ear-old son _ shot in what police said was a game of Russian
roulette.
   ``We're trying to get through this and we're praying to the good
Lord, but it's pretty tough,'' said Bessie Milton, whose
17-year-old son Edward died after being shot in the eye.
   ``We lost five children in a fire in Chicago in 1963 and the
Lord blessed me with five more children,'' Mrs. Milton, 46, said
Wednesday. ``Now I've lost my baby. Hopefully, the good Lord will
pull me through again.''
   The teen-ager's shooting death Saturday is the latest tragedy to
scar a family all too familiar with death.
   L.D. and Bessie Milton were in the process of buying a house in
1963 when a boiler in their South Side apartment building exploded.
   The couple had left their five small children in the care of a
neighbor who lived upstairs from their basement apartment. The
Milton children _ four girls and a boy _ all died in the resulting
blaze.
   The Miltons, who have been married 29 years, rebuilt their
family with four boys and a girl, and moved to Peoria in 1974 where
Milton works as a musician. They live in public housing in Peoria's
poor south side.
   ``My oldest would have been 29 years old now and my baby was
17,'' Mrs. Milton said. ``I had a nervous breakdown two years after
the fire, but I turned my life around. I hope I can get through
this.''
   Mrs. Milton is angry at the youth accused of shooting her
promising son. ``My son was outgoing _ he would do anything for
anyone,'' she said.
   ``He worked at a restaurant, owned his own car and was going to
graduate from Manual High School next year. He was a good student
and he talked about going to college. He was even in the ROTC. He
was a good boy and was never any trouble.''
   David L. Gaines, 17, was charged with first-degree murder and
remained in jail on $100,000 bond Wednesday. Police say he shot
Edward Milton in the right eye early Saturday in a game of Russian
roulette that involved at least four youths.
   In Russian roulette, a revolver's cylinder is loaded with one
cartridge, the cylinder spun and the trigger pulled.
   Prosecutors said Gaines pointed the gun at the heads of two
other youths and pulled the trigger, but the weapon didn't fire
until it was Milton's turn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
