<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Interior-MoneyBill     07-14 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interior-Money Bill,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves $10 Billion Spending Bill Despite Veto Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate approval of a $10 billion spending bill
for the Interior Department is being greeted with the threat of a
presidential veto because of what the White House budget office
says is excessive spending.
   The 92-4 vote, however, was far more than the two-thirds tally
needed to override a veto. The Senate bill exceeds Reagan's budget
request by $1.2 billion, and would boost current spending by $747.6
million.
   The measure now goes to a House-Senate conference committee,
which will reconcile differences with a $9.69 billion version of
the bill approved by the House on June 29 for fiscal 1989, which
begins Oct. 1.
   James Miller, director of the Office of Management and Budget,
sent word he will recommend that President Reagan veto the bill
unless his objections are resolved.
   Miller complained of excessive spending under the Senate bill
for $526 million worth of energy conservation grants, land
acquisition, construction projects and Indian health facilities.
   Miller also protested the measure's proposed one-year moratorium
on sale of oil and gas leases off the coasts of northern California
and Massachusetts and resumption of such a ban off the Florida Gulf
Coast.
   The chamber also approved an amendment by Sen. Bennett Johnston,
D-La., eliminating a provision that would have accelerated by six
months, to Aug. 1, 1989, a Southern California lease sale involving
7 million acres of shoreline.
   Environmentalists had opposed that provision because of the
Senate Appropriations Committee's declaration that environmental
impact statements prepared for previous lease sales in the area
should be considered sufficient for this sale.
   The Senate voted to provide $525 million to support a Reagan
commitment to Canada to combat acid rain by developing technology
to reduce polluting emissions from coal burning.
   Miller had complained that the House backtracked on a
congressional commitment made last year by voting to slash the $525
million for clean coal research in fiscal 1989 to only $100 million.
   The House bill would provide additional sums of $225 million in
1990 and $200 million in the following year. The Senate deleted all
clean coal money for those later two years.
   Miller urged Congress to approve Reagan's request for $600
million each in 1990 and 1991 for clean coal projects before a
compromise bill is sent to the White House.
   The Senate deleted a House provision, strongly opposed by the
administration, that would require that at least 50 percent of
labor and materials used for offshore oil or gas rigs be made in
the United States.
   Both measures include $333.5 million to buy and transport oil to
fill the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, but the Senate bill sets
$91.5 million of the money aside as an advance appropriation for
fiscal 1990.
</TEXT>
