<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Cities Take Different Approach to Handle Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cities hosting the Democratic and Republican
national conventions are taking different approaches towards paying
for the expensive extravaganzas.
   Despite some charges of disorganization, Atlanta officials say
they're on their way to paying for the Democratic affair with help
from a $9 million check from the national party and a special tax
for motel and hotel rooms in the area through July 1990.
   The total tab for the Democratic National Convention next week
is expected to be $24 million, with the Georgia legislature and
some local banks expected to help raise funds for any shortfall in
payments.
   ``We have a nice cushion built in, in what we need to borrow and
what our interest revenues are going to be,'' said Bobby Kahn,
president of the Atlanta '88 organization set up to handle the
event.
   New Orleans, site of the Republican Convention on Aug. 15-18,
has struggled to come up with the funds to pay for security
measures, 5,000 upholstered chairs and the lighting and sound
systems for the Superdome.
   Fund-raising chief Ron Jones says he is banking on the fact
that, ``This has always been a town that gets its big hits late.''
   Mayor Sidney Barthelemy formed a second fund-raising committee
after complaints by the Greater New Orleans Convention Fund that
the first committee wasn't getting a fair share from big companies.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis and Beryl Ann Bentsen Campaign Together For First</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Time
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beryl Ann Bentsen used her first appearance on
