<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChildForSale     07-14 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child For Sale,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Given Probation for Trying to Sell Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who tried to sell his daughter to
her uncle for $100,000 was sentenced to three years probation and
312 hours of community service in a plea bargain.
   Joseph Waltman, who had pleaded guilty to endangering the
welfare of a child in the plea agreement, was given probation
Wednesday because it was his first offense, said Bergen County
Superior Court Judge James Madden. He could have received a
five-year prison term.
   ``I am not condoning what this young man did,'' Madden said.
``However, there are mitigating circumstances ... extreme
mitigating circumstances.''
   Waltman, 24, of Alloway Township was arrested outside Giants
Stadium in East Rutherford in March 1987, when he attempted to sell
daughter Rachel, now 6 years old, to her uncle, Gary Stern. Police,
tipped off by Stern, were waiting for Waltman in the New York City
suburb.
   Waltman's attorney, James Patuto, said his client was a victim
of pressures brought on him in a battle over Rachel's custody with
other family members.
   The sentence was criticized by Stern and his wife, Deborah, of
Sunrise, Fla., who adopted the child in May after a custody battle.
   ``It's a very dark day,'' Gary Stern said. ``You have to pray
that if you can hold out long enough justice will prevail. Today,
it didn't.''
   The custody fight involving the Sterns, Rachel's maternal
grandparents and her former stepmother followed Waltman's arrest.
   A New Jersey judge awarded full custody to the Sterns last
December, but gave the grandparents and the former stepmother
visitation rights.
   The Sterns complied with the order, sending Rachel to New Jersey
twice for visits with her relatives.
   But after a Florida judge approved the adoption in May, Gary
Stern cut off visitation, claiming Rachel was now his daughter and
that it was inappropriate for a child so young to be traveling back
and forth.
   Stern's attorney, Harry Gulkin, said a child psychologist found
that the visitation was causing Rachel to become confused about her
identity and her family.
   Last month, a Bridgeton judge found the Sterns in contempt of
court for adopting Rachel in Florida and interrupting the visits.
   Rachel, who enters first grade this fall, has been bounced from
one family to another since her teen-age mother died after a truck
slammed into her car in October 1984.
   She was awarded $2.9 million last year in a personal injury
lawsuit against the company that owned the truck. The payments do
not begin until she turns 18.
</TEXT>
