<HEAD>Sills Talk-Show Pilot To Be Taped This Summer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City Opera director Beverly Sills has
agreed to produce a TV pilot for her own daily, one-hour variety
program that would go on the air in September 1989.
   Miss Sills, who announced in May her plans to retire as general
director of the once-struggling opera company on Jan. 1, said at
the time that she was considering accepting a TV talk-show offer.
   ``At this point in my career, I am only willing to do things
that I can have fun with,'' said Miss Sills, 59, on Wednesday.
``This sounds like a lot of fun.''
   The Brooklyn-born coloratura soprano joined the company in 1955
and was its biggest star until 1980, when she retired from singing.
   Plans for the television show call for it to be taped before an
audience in New York. The format will include a band with
entertainers and other celebrities joining Miss Sills, who will
have a different co-host each week.
   Miss Sills agreed to the pilot program this week with G.T.G.
East, part of a joint venture between Grant Tinker and the Gannett
Co. G.T.G. East plans to assemble the pilot this summer and begin
selling the show to local stations this fall.
