<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-USBases 1stLd-Writethru a0482 07-14 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-US Bases, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0891</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Over US Bases More Complex Than Cash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To ADD explanation of importance of U.S. bases, INSERTS new
11th graf, `Clark Air ... Persian Gulf.' Picks up 11th graf pvs,
`Mrs. Aquino ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artful diplomacy may well resolve a
current impasse over strategic U.S. military bases in the
Philippines, but the issue is likely to haunt the
allies-turned-wary partners' relations for some time.
   The stumbling block now is money: Should the U.S. boost the
compensation it currently pays Manila to maintain its massive naval
and air installations in this Southeast Asian nation?
   Washington says the current $180 million a year is probably
enough. Manila wants much more.
   But the underlying problems are far more complex than cash. They
include growing Filipino nationalism and American global interests,
local politicking here and nearly a century of intimate but not
always happy relations.
   Recent polls indicate that if a general vote were taken now, the
bases would stay beyond the 1991 expiration of a 41-year-old treaty
under which they were established. Many Filipinos, perhaps most,
still appear to harbor pro-American feelings.
   During this week's visit to Manila by Secretary of State George
P. Shultz, the lines of Filipinos outside the U.S. Embassy seeking
visas far outnumbered nearby anti-American demonstrators wielding
placards reading, ``Go to hell, not here.''
   But the onerous legacy of deposed President Ferdinand E. Marcos
and the still rocky democracy under President Corazon Aquino have
created many problems related to the bases that have yet to be
thrashed out.
   Mrs. Aquino was swept into power in February 1986 in a
civilian-military uprising that sent Marcos into exile in Hawaii.
   The uncertainties include a potent communist insurgency and a
volatile political arena that has included the spectacle of several
failed coup attempts by military factions.
   Beyond the island nation, there are questions of whether the
Soviet Union and China will continue beefing up their military
forces in the region and how much pressure non-communist Southeast
Asian neighbors will exert on the Philippines to keep the U.S.
military presence.
   Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore, a partner of the
Philippines in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, has said
the bases are ``crucial for a balance of forces in the Western
Pacific.''
   Clark Air Base and Subic Naval Base are the largest U.S.
military installations outside the United States. Subic is
especially crucial because it serves as the major repair and supply
facility for U.S. forces in the Pacific and Indian Oceans as well
as the Persian Gulf.
   Mrs. Aquino herself is a question mark, having maintained a
steadfast silence over whether she wants the bases to remain. ``I
am keeping my options open,'' she keeps saying.
   Staying or not staying also depends on how both sides muster
their propaganda and play their diplomatic cards.
   The protracted and still ongoing review of the agreement,
something called for every five years, is probably a foretaste of
things to come through 1991.
   In negotiations beginning in April, the Philippine side asked
for significantly more compensation; some suggested $1.2 billion
and more. There was talk of terminating the agreement.
   Shultz called the sums ``staggering'' and said the U.S. might
have to move the bases elsewhere. Haggling continued.
   During Shultz's visit, both sides said they hoped the review
could be completed by the end of this month. A compromise appeared
to be in the making.
   But still pending is the issue of whether the Philippines will
pass into law a bill banning all nuclear weapons from the country,
something Washington strongly opposes.
   And if the review negotiations and outcome leave too sour a
taste in American mouths, Washington might be reluctant to provide
large sums for a major, multilateral plan to rehabilitate the
tottering Philippine economy.
   Meanwhile, anti-American protests have become a feature of
Manila life, and the rhetoric as well as legitimate debate have
heated up. The bases issue has sparked political posturing and
deeply rooted feelings about the United States and the country's
own past.
   ``It's time the Americans should know we are not happy being
treated as a charity case. And it's time, too, we Filipinos
shouldn't act@react as if our survival would forever be dependent
on the mercy and benevolence of Ole Uncle Sam,'' said a recent
editorial in Manila's ``Business World.''
   Base opponents like to recall days when the country was under
U.S. colonial rule and more recent times when President Reagan
called Marcos ``a force of reason and moderation in Asia'' and Vice
President George Bush praised him for his ``adherence to democratic
principles.''
   The United States prefers to remember Americans and Filipinos
fighting and dying side-by-side in World War II and shared cultural
and political values. American diplomats work overtime trying to
counter the rather loud anti-base voices.
   But one U.S. Embassy official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the time when U.S. envoys spoke and Filipino
officials fell into line are over.
   ``It's real diplomacy in the trenches,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>__</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Denis Gray, bureau chief in Bangkok, Thailand,
has covered Southeast Asia for The Associated Press since the early
1970s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
