<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CigaretteSuit-Stocks     07-14 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Suit-Stocks,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts: Tobacco Stocks Rise On Word Of Plaintiff's Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney Marc Z. Edell is used to having
jurors listen to him. But the reaction of the stock market caught
him off guard when his comments about cigarette-health litigation
sent tobacco stocks sharply higher.
   ``It's nice to be so important that people listen to what I
say,'' said Edell, who represented the widower of a lung-cancer
victim in a landmark lawsuit that led to the first damage award
against a cigarette-maker for a smoker's death.
   Analysts Wednesday said Edell's prediction to a group of
investors that liability cases would not seriously damage the
financial health of cigarette makers prompted a buying spree for
tobacco stocks.
   In the most dramatic example, Philip Morris Cos. Inc. jumped $6
between July 6, the day before the luncheon investment meeting, and
Wednesday, when the stock closed at $89.87{.
   RJR-Nabisco's stock rose $4.12{ to $51.87{ during the period;
Loews Corp., owner of cigarette maker Lorillard Inc., rose 87{
cents to $67.50; American Brands rose 75 cents to $49.87{; and
Liggett Group Inc. rose 12{ cents to $8.
   All but Liggett had shown slight declines the day before the
meeting. The Dow Jones Industrial Average dipped from 2,130 to
2,104 between July 6 and Wednesday's close.
   Analysts attributed much of the rise to Edell's comments to
about 60 institutional investment clients of Sanford C. Bernstein &
Co. Inc. of New York.
   ``I don't think there's any other explanation for it,'' said
Bernstein tobacco analyst Marc Cohen.
   ``It was very clear that people walked out of that meeting
feeling very comfortable,'' he said, adding that tobacco stocks
began an upward move that afternoon.
   In a telephone interview, Edell said he told the investors
nothing other than what he has said before and after the widely
reported verdict in federal court in Newark on June 13, that he did
not think cigarette liability cases ``are going to have a serious
financial impact on these companies.''
   The jury ordered Liggett Group Inc. to pay $400,000 in damages
to Antonio Cipollone for the death of his wife, Rose, who died of
lung cancer after 40 years of smoking.
   Many analysts have discounted fears that the Cipollone decision
would unleash a wave of liability cases against cigarette makers.
They noted that the jury exonerated Liggett, Philip Morris and
Lorillard of conspiring to defraud the public about the dangers of
smoking.
   Despite those views, many investment managers have taken a
``wait and see attitude'' toward tobacco stocks since the verdict,
Cohen said. But Edell's statement appears to have eased any
lingering investor fears about the stocks, he added.
   Also encouraging investors' enthusiasm was an indication from
Philip Morris and RJR that their second-quarter earnings, due to be
announced next week, would be about 30 percent higher than last
year, said Merrill Lynch analyst Allan Kaplan.
   Edell said Wednesday his firm has received more than a hundred
calls nationwide asking him to take smoker-death cases but that he
and his partners have not decided yet whether to accept any of them.
   Cohen said Edell told the investor group that he now could fight
a liability case at a cost of $200,000 following the work done on
the Cipollone case. The lawyer has said that the 4{-year Cipollone
case cost $2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
