<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Meese-Weld     07-14 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Weld,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Justice Department Official Denies Marijuna Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top Justice Department official denies
smoking marijuana while U.S. attorney for Massachusetts, and says
he was warned the allegation might come up at a hearing into
Attorney General Edwin Meese's conduct.
   ``I would have to be pretty dumb to smoke marijuana while a
sitting U.S. attorney,'' William Weld, the former head of the
Justice Department's criminal division, said in a telephone
interview Wednesday.
   Weld, who reportedly quit his Justice Department job because he
thought there was enough evidence to seek a criminal indictment
against Meese, told the Senate Judiciary Committee in a letter
Tuesday that the marijuana allegation was unfounded.
   Weld also told the panel that he would testify about why he
resigned. Meese, under fire from Congress because of questions
raised about his ethics, announced last week that he would leave
the administration by next month after an independent prosecutor
declined to bring charges against him.
   Weld said Duke Short, the Judiciary Committee's top Republican
aide, told him the committee had been informed of the allegation
and questioned whether it might ``complicate'' his testimony about
Meese, set for July 26.
   Weld confirmed Wednesday's story in the Washington Times that
the department's Office of Professional Responsibility last year
investigated an allegation he smoked marijuana while attending a
wedding in Virginia in 1982. At the time, he was Massachusetts' top
federal prosecutor.
   The investigation found no basis for the allegation, which was
raised in an anonymous letter to the department last July,
according to The Boston Globe.
   However, the Times quoted sources as saying that Frank McNamara,
the current U.S. attorney for Massachusetts, saw Weld smoking
marijuana at the wedding.
   ``I'm not going tell you it's not true,'' the newspaper quoted
McNamara as saying.
   ``I don't know why Frank would say that,'' Weld said. ``It's
absurd.''
   Attempts to reach McNamara for comment Wednesday were
unsuccessful. A receptionist said McNamara was in Washington but
could not say where. A message left on his home answering machine
was not returned.
</TEXT>
