<DOCNO> AP880714-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HamadiTrial     07-14 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Hears Accused Hijacker Was Sought On Murder Charges In
Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi, on trial for
murder and air piracy in the 1985 TWA hijacking, was being sought
on murder charges in his native Lebanon in 1983, according to
evidence introduced today.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger read a document from
authorities in Lebanon that said an arrest warrant was issued for
the defendant in 1983 on charges of murder and unlawful use of
weapons.
   The document did not contain details of the alleged crimes, and
Hamadi said, ``I don't know anything about it.''
   The TWA jetliner, on an Athens-to-Rome flight, was hijacked in
June 1985. U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem of Waldorf, Md., was
killed after the hijackers forced the plane to land in Beirut.
   Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage during the 17-day ordeal.
   Hamadi, who came to West Germany in 1982, also testified today
that he worked at a cemetery in Saarlouis in 1983 while his
application for political asylum was pending.
   He said he tried to commit suicide, once by swallowing pills in
1983 and once before by slashing his wrists, because he was
depressed about his life in West Germany and because of
developments in Lebanon.
   Hamadi has said he returned to Lebanon in 1984 in part because
his application for political asylum was not approved.
   A Shiite Moslem, Hamadi testified Wednesday that he belonged to
the Shiite Amal militia between 1980 and 1982 in Beirut and was
involved in battles there.
   But he denied involvement with Hezbollah, or Party of God, a
radical pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem group believed to be the umbrella
organization for gunmen holding foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   One of Hamadi's brothers, Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, is chief of
security for Hezbollah in Beirut. Another, Abbas Ali Hamadi, was
convicted in April of kidnapping two West Germans in Lebanon in an
attempt to win Mohammed's freedom. He was sentenced to 13 years in
prison by a Duesseldort court.
   Speaking in Arabic, Hamadi told the court today that while
living in Beirut he had been trained to fight as an Amal member.
   ``I was forced (by circumstances) to carry weapons. I wanted to
fight against Israel,'' Hamadi said, making his first statements to
the Frankfurt court since his trial began last week.
   ``There is a saying in our country: In Lebanon, you are born
with a weapon in your hand,'' he said.
   Hamadi said he was trained by Amal to use a rocket-propelled
grenade launcher and other weapons.
   Asked whether he had owned hand grenades, Hamadi answered:
``Everyone had these at home. You could buy them like you buy
eggs.''
   He told the court he had smuggled liquid explosives into West
Germany twice, contradicting a statement he made to police after
his January 1987 arrest. At the time, Hamadi told police he thought
the bottles were filled with alcohol and denied knowing that they
contained high explosives.
   ``A certain person asked me to smuggle them in and hide them,''
Hamadi said. ``I did it twice. The second time I was arrested. ...
I don't know the reason why the explosives were brought in. I was
not told.''
   Hamadi was accused of involvement in the hijacking based on
evidence that includes fingerprints. West Germany last year
rejected a U.S. request for his extradition.
   Hamadi is being tried under heavy security in a specially
constructed prison courtroom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan     07-14 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationalists Inject New Blood Into Policy-making Body</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Nationalist Party gave new
blood to its policy-making body today by replacing several aging
holdovers from the Chiang Kai-shek era with a more dynamic
leadership.
   President Lee Teng-hui, who last week became the first native
Taiwanese to lead the party, has indicated that the newly organized
Central Standing Committee will try to bring further democratic
change to this Asian economic powerhouse.
   Twelve of 31 members of the committee stepped down, including
five of seven octogenarians. The group's average age fell from 70
to 63. For the first time, a majority of the members are native
Taiwanese, who now hold 16 seats.
   ``In the past, many of the party elders were completely out of
touch with the society,'' said Lu Ya-li, political science
professor at National Taiwan University. ``The younger members may
not be all reform-minded, but they must be more sensitive to what
the society wants. They know that there must be a democratic
change.''
   The new policy-making group, whose decisions are implemented by
the Nationalist government, was proposed by Lee. Candidates were
approved by the 180-member Central Committee, which was elected at
the weeklong 13th party congress that concluded Wednesday.
   The Nationalists began exercising one-party rule on this island
in 1949, when Chiang Kai-shek led them in flight from mainland
China after losing a civil war to the Communists. By claiming to
still represent all China, the party remained dominated by
mainlanders.
   But as the island prospered, the native Taiwanese who make up
about 85 percent of the island's nearly 20 million people pressured
for democratic change, leading to the lifting of martial law and
the end of a ban on opposition parties under President Chiang
Ching-kuo, eldest son of Chiang Kai-shek.
   Still to be changed is the parliamentary system in which
mainland Chinese Nationalists hold a majority of seats as a symbol
of the party's claim to China.
   Lee Teng-hui, who became president when Chiang Ching-kuo died
last January, has vowed to continue with political, social and
economic liberalization, but the pace of change is likely to depend
largely on the new policy-making committee.
   ``The pace of reform may be quickened,'' said Lu.
   Key figures remaining on the committee include Chief of General
Staff Hau Pei-tsun, Party Secretary-General Lee Huan and Premier Yu
Kuo-hwa.
   Lee Huan is seen as a supporter of the liberalization process,
while Yu is viewed as the most powerful holdover from the
authoritarian past of the Nationalist Party, also known as
Kuomintang.
   Yu received less support than many younger, vocal supporters of
liberalization during the congress, fueling specuation about his
political future. A Cabinet reshuffle is expected soon.
   The new Central Standing Committee members include four Chinese
mainlanders age 64 or over, two of whom are linked to the military.
   Also added to the policy-making body were five Taiwanese _ a
union leader, an industrialist, a leading central banker and two
top politicians from the southern port of Kaohsiung.
   The remaining new members are Frederick Chien, 54, Taiwan's main
representative in Washington; Education Minister Mao Kao-wen; and
47-year-old James Soong, a party deputy secretary-general who is
the youngest committee member and seen as a rising star.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
