<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NavyDeath     07-14 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Punished Sailors File Appeals In Recruit's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Navy swimming instructors punished
in the training death of a recruit have appealed the rank
reductions, pay forfeitures and other penalties imposed by their
commander, a Navy spokeswoman says.
   The punishments were for the March 2 death of Airman Recruit Lee
Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.
   Mirecki was described as being literally scared to death when he
was forced back into a swimming pool after he climbed out and said
he wanted to quit the air-sea rescue program at Pensacola Naval Air
Station.
   Other recruits were ordered to turn their backs to the pool and
sing the national anthem while Mirecki screamed for help, according
to testimony.
   ``It's not bad punishment,'' Petty Officer 2nd Class Frankie
Deaton, one of the instructors who is appealing, said after the
penalties were ordered June 29 by Rear Adm. David Morris,
then-chief of naval air training in Corpus Christi, Texas.
   ``But, hey, why am I being punished for doing my job?'' Deaton
asked. ``That's all I've done. I am not guilty of a crime. I will
go to my grave thinking that I did nothing wrong. I did nothing
that school hasn't taught me to do.''
   Deaton and Petty Officer 2nd Class John Zelenock were ordered to
forfeit half their basic pay for two months. A one-grade reduction
in rank was suspended on condition they maintain clean records for
six months.
   Petty Officers 1st Class David Smith and Richard Blevins each
were demoted one rank to petty officer 2nd class and are to be
restricted to the base for 30 days.
   All four had been charged with conspiracy to commit battery and
involuntary manslaughter, but the latter charge was dropped in each
case.
   The appeals will go to Morris' successor, Rear Adm. Jimmie W.
Taylor, and then to Vice Adm. N.R. Thunman, Kay Esty, a spokeswoman
for Thunman, said Wednesday. There is no limit on how long the
appeals may take.
   A fifth instructor, Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael Combe, and
Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, the former officer in charge of the Navy's
rescue swimmer school, face court-martial in the case.
   Combe is charged with involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy to
commit battery; Torchia is accused of dereliction of duty. No trial
dates have been set.
</TEXT>
