<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Mendel     07-14 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Mendel,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Oldest Veteran Dies at Age 104</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel Leroy Mendel, who was turned away from
the Army in 1898 because he was too young to enlist but lived to
become the nation's oldest veteran, died at the age of 104.
   Mendel died in his sleep Wednesday, said a friend, Jim Phillips.
   He was past commander-in-chief of the Spanish-American War
Veteran's Association, despite having never served in the war.
   The Fort Worth, Texas, native was only 14 when the U.S.
battleship Maine was sunk on June 23, 1898, in Havana Harbor, Cuba,
then a Spanish port. But he was unable to enlist in the Army until
after the Spanish-American war officially ended.
   He enlisted in 1901 at age 17, hoping to join in fighting that
continued in Guam, Puerto Rico and the Philippines.
   ``I wanted to go to the Philippines to fight,'' Mendel said in a
1983 interview. ``But they said I was too young ... had to be at
least 20. It was one of the biggest disappointments in my life.''
   Instead of carrying a gun onto the field of battle, Mendel spent
his three-year military career carrying a football on the athletic
fields at Fort Sam Houston. In 1902, he was cited as the best
athlete in the U.S. Army.
   With Mendel's death, the last known veteran of the
Spanish-American war era is Nathan E. Cook, 102, of Tempe, Ariz., a
Navy veteran with 44 years of military service.
   A widower, Mendel is survived by a son, Robert L. Mendel of
Brookfield, a daughter, Fern Varley of San Francisco, two grandsons
and a great-granddaughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
