<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz     07-14 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Opens Talks With Chinese On Cambodia, Missile Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen of China today opened talks on the Cambodian
conflict and U.S. concerns about Chinese missile sales in the
Middle East.
   Shultz, on the sixth stop of a nine-nation Asian tour, arrived
today from Hong Kong for a two-day visit.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Jin Guihua said efforts to end the
nine-year Vietnamese military occupation of Cambodia would top the
agenda.
   China and the United States both demand the withdrawal of
Vietnam's estimated 120,000 troops, but Washington and other
countries have expressed concern that the China-backed Khmer Rouge,
part of a three-party anti-Vietnam resistance, could regain power
when Vietnam leaves.
   The Khmer Rouge under Pol Pot killed more than 1 million
Cambodians through its fanatical agrarian reform policies while
ruling from 1975 until the Vietnamese invasion in late 1978.
   China, the main supplier of arms to the Khmer Rouge, recently
said the Communist group should not be the dominant force in a
future Cambodian government.
   China's Foreign Ministry recently called for freezing military
forces of all sides and nominating for a future government leaders
of various Cambodian factions who are acceptable to all parties.
   The plan effectively would rule out the return of Pol Pot and
other Khmer Rouge leaders linked to past atrocities.
   Vietnam, battered by economic failures at home, has announced
plans to withdraw 50,000 troops this year and the rest by 1991. It
has also agreed to meet representatives of the three-party
resistance coalition in Indonesia later this month.
   Shultz on Friday is to meet senior leader Deng Xiaoping, Premier
Li Peng, Vice Premier Wu Quexian and Communist Party chief Zhao
Ziyang for talks expected to touch on Chinese arms sales to the
Mideast, U.S.-Soviet developments and security at the Seoul Olympic
Games.
   A senior U.S. State Department source said in Hong Kong
Wednesday that Shultz would tell Chinese leaders that their
ballistic missile sales to the Middle East are adding another
element of instability to that volatile region.
   China has sold CSS-2 intermediate-range missiles to Saudi Arabia
and may be marketing a shorter-range weapon, the M-9, which has a
range of between 190 and 370 miles and is still being tested.
   It has denied selling the M-9 to Syria and says the CSS-2s sold
to Saudi Arabia are non-nuclear and defensive.
   Chinese arms sales to the Middle East were also a major topic on
Shultz's last visit to China, in March 1987. He urged China to stop
supplying arms, including Silkworm missiles, to Iran.
   China consistently denies it sells Iran weapons and strongly
criticized Washington's decision last fall to temporarily freeze
relaxation of restrictions on U.S. high technology sales to China
because of the alleged Silkworm sales. Washington lifted the freeze
last March.
   U.S.-Chinese relations are marked by steadily expanding trade,
social, academic, military and scientific links.
   Trade topped $10 billion last year and U.S. investors have
committed $3 billion to Chinese industry, more than any other
nation or region except Hong Kong.
   The Beijing government is actively courting American businessmen
and seeking U.S. participation in China's ambitious development
programs.
</TEXT>
