<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LionTamer     07-14 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lion Tamer,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manual That Calls Jailers `Lion Tamers' is Withdrawn</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 10th graf, bgng `Little kids...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A manual that compares jailers to lion
tamers and calls inmates ``big cats'' who may need their food
drugged to calm them has been withdrawn from a jail staff-training
program.
   Titled ``The Lion Tamer,'' the illustrated six-page pamphlet has
been in circulation since 1982 and was used to train at least 50
Santa Clara County deputies.
   Sheriff Robert Winter on Wednesday ordered the guide removed as
he soon as he found out about its existence, said Sgt. Cary Colla.
   ``All big cats aren't the same,'' the text reads. ``You got your
African lions, you got your Bengal tigers, you got your pumas and
you got your leopards. Now your African lions come from Africa.
Your Bengal tigers come from Asia. Your pumas come from the
southwest or south of the border.''
   It goes on to refer to the ``leopards'' as crazy and say that
they may need to have their food ``doped.''
   The guide uses sexual slang to describe the positive side of
working as a jailer.
   ``Little kids and old ladies are dazzled by the lion tamer.
Young ladies fall in love. ... I mean, he is one macho S.O.B.,''
the manual says.
   A spokesman for the Sheriff's Department denied that prisoners
are drugged.
   But William Frazier, a Contra Costa County sheriff's officer who
wrote the guide, conceded that drugs are routinely used in jails to
control mentally ill or violent inmates who have taken PCP.
   Frazier denied that the book is racist or sexist.
   ``It's misunderstood,'' he said. ``We're not training nuns to
run a convent. I've been told by more officers that this appealed
to their fears.''
   The guide was part of a course taught by Naber Technical
Enterprises, a private Novato firm contracted by the jail to train
workers.
   ``The potential for violence is real and we wanted something to
guide a staff apprehensive about losing barriers between themselves
and inmates,'' said Bill Naber, president of the company. ``The
analogy was not meant to be demeaning.''
</TEXT>
