<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0825EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0499,0706</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede SCZCECIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says He Seeks Return To Lenin's Goals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with today's comments to intellectuals. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev told
Polish intellectuals today that the basic goal of his reform
program is to ensure that working people live a better life.
   Gorbachev said he wants to return to the approach of Vladimir I.
Lenin, founder of the Soviet state, who he said staged a revolution
against exploitation to make man ``master of his own spirit.''
   The Soviet leader, on a six-day tour of Poland, spoke to several
dozen academics, writers, scientists and cultural figures in the
ornate gilded ballroom of Warsaw's Royal Castle. Polish state
television broadcast the meeting.
   A Polish physicist in the audience thanked Gorbachev for the
decision by the Soviet Communist Party conference to erect a
monument in Moscow to victims of the late Soviet dictator, Josef
Stalin.
   The scientist, Jan Rychlewski, said his father was among the
Polish communists who disappeared in Stalin's purges.
   ``We will treat this monument as his grave,'' the physicist told
Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev, speaking in Russian, told his audience that during a
stop at a farmer's house near Sczcecin on Wednesday, he was asked
what he was trying to accomplish with ``perestroika,'' his program
to restructure and modernize the Soviet economy and society.
   ``Simply, we want, in spite of everything ... for working people
to lead a better life,'' Gorbachev said he replied.
   Gorbachev, who grew up on a farm in southern Russia, added that
socialism must make humanitarianism its most important achievement.
   By improving the lives of the people in both the Soviet Union
and Poland, all other fields of life will be transformed as well,
Gorbachev said.
   Intellectuals can offer their support to reconstruction and
renewal, but its main goal is to improve the lives of workers and
farmers, Gorbachev said. On the ``train of perestroika'' he said,
``these are the most significant and main passengers.''
   Later, Gorbachev drove across town to party headquarters to meet
with the leadership of the communist Polish United Workers Party.
   On Wednesday, Gorbachev told about 3,000 shipyard workers in
Sczcecin he is looking to Poland for ideas to help solve economic
problems at home and avoid making costly political mistakes.
   ``We find many useful things in your experiences,'' he said.
   The speech was greeted with polite applause but little outward
enthusiasm by the workers, who were admitted by invitation. The
Soviet Union buys about half the ships built at the yard, once a
Solidarity stronghold.
   Attempts by Poland's communist authorities to revive the
nation's stagnant economy are complicated by the Soviet bloc's best
organized opposition.
   Solidarity, the outlawed independent labor federation, was
stifled in a 1981 military crackdown. But dissatisfaction with
communist authorities' unwillingness to share some measure of power
or allow free trade unions is still strong enough to trigger
disruptive strikes.
   Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski also is embarked on a reform
campaign, and both leaders have stressed their common goals during
the Soviet leader's visit.
   But Poland has so far failed in its attempt to bring prices more
in line with actual costs and trim heavy government subsidies.
   Gorbachev told his nation's Communist Party conference last
month that a similar revision of the state-set price system is
crucial to the success of his economic reforms.
   Jaruzelski's government raised prices an average of 40 percent
this year, almost immediately touching off a wave of strikes.
   Wage pressure quickly outpaced the increases, triggering
inflation that has hit 60 percent so far this year.
   Polish leaders now acknowledge that their price reform effort
was a failure.
   Gorbachev later paid a private visit to an agricultural complex
that serves as a model of high-productivity farming in western
Poland. He also stopped at a prize-winning beef and dairy farm
owned by Franciszek Bakan. Private farmers till most of Poland's
arable land.
   Gorbachev has proposed that the Soviet Union return to family
farming by leasing land to farmers to increase crop production and
reduce the nation's dependence on grain imports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
