<HEAD>Dukakis Unconcerned About Issues Differences With Bentsen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis says Democratic running mate
Lloyd Bentsen will disagree with him on some issues but their
campaign will stress the general themes the two men can agree on.
   ``We're going to agree and we do agree on most issues,'' the
likely Democratic nominee said Wednesday. ``We'll disagree on some,
but we both share a deep and abiding commitment to economic growth
and opportunity for the people of this country.
   ``And that will be the central thrust of our campaign,'' the
Massachusetts governor said at a news conference with the Texas
senator.
   ``He wasn't looking for a clone of Michael Dukakis,'' Bentsen
said. ``He is a man who will reach out to differing viewpoints.''
   Bentsen is more conservative than Dukakis on several issues.
   He favors supporting the Contra rebels in Nicaragua, voted for
President Reagan's 1981 tax cuts, and supports a constitutional
amendment to balance the budget. He also supported building the B-1
bomber and the MX missile, and has voted for allowing prayer in
schools and imposing the death penalty.
   ``His job is to vote as he sees fit in the Senate and I assume
he will continue to do so,'' said Dukakis, who opposed all of
those. He said Bentsen's different thinking would be a strength.
   ``One of the reasons I picked Lloyd Bentsen is because I know
that he will challenge me,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis used the questioning to get in a dig at Vice President
George Bush, the likely Republican nominee, saying he expects
Bentsen would ``come right into my office'' if the National
Security Council was considering a ``cockamamie'' idea like selling
arms to Iran.
</TEXT>
