<2ND_LINE>PM-Thornburgh-Justice, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0543,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Successor to Examine Morale at Department</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 8, Asked in a, and 12, That's a question, to
CORRECT CBS to ABC.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Thornburgh, President Reagan's choice
as the next attorney general, said today he will talk to top
Justice Department officials in the next week about improving
morale following the departure of Edwin Meese III.
   ``I want to take a very careful look at what the level of
commitment and what the level of morale is within the department,''
Thornburgh said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' program.
   ``I hope within the next week or so to begin some conversations
with key people in the department so I can make that assessment (of
morale) and we can deal with whatever problems exist there,'' said
Thornburgh, who was interviewed from Boston.
   The former Pennsylvania governor said he would provide ``a firm
hand at the tiller'' of the department.
   Reagan named Thornburgh, a former prosecutor and head of the
Justice Department's criminal division, to replace Meese, who
announced his resignation July 5 after saying a special
prosecutor's report cleared him of allegations of wrongdoing.
   Meese, who will depart in late July or early August, said he was
not leaving the department in disarray.
   Several top aides had only been on the job less than two months
and two high department officials resigned in March to protest
Meese's continued tenure. Replacements for those people were found
only after a highly public search in which the attorney general was
rejected by other recruits.
   Asked in a separate interview today on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America'' program about possible morale problems, Thornburgh said,
``Obviously there have been some distractions and a lot of pressure
in recent months. But I think that can be dealt with appropriately
with a firm hand at the tiller.''
   ``Everybody has their own management style,'' Thornburgh, 55,
said when asked how he would differ from Meese.
   ``What I hope to bring is a firm management style and a
commitment to the principles that make for firm and fair law
enforcement. I would much prefer to look forward than look back.''
   Thornburgh, considered a moderate in Republican circles, also
left open the possibility that he would accept an offer to stay on
in the post if Vice President George Bush is elected president in
November.
   ``That's a question that Vice President Bush would have to
decide if he were elected. It's no secret that I am a supporter of
the vice president,'' Thornburgh said on ABC. ``I'll take it on one
day at a time and see what ensues.''
   There has been speculation that Thornburgh might be tabbed as
Bush's running mate in the fall.
   ``That's George Bush's decision,'' Thornburgh told NBC.
``Obviously when an offer like that is forthcoming from a political
leader the stature of George Bush, it would get serious
consideration.''
</TEXT>
