<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Greece-ShipAttack 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Ship Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0517,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Linked to Ship Attack Convicted of Entering with Forged
Passport</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Palestinian convicted and sentenced,
saying he's a PLO member. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today convicted a Palestinian
believed linked to a terrorist attack on a Greek cruise ship of
entering the country illegally and sentenced him to seven months in
prison.
   Dozens of police with automatic weapons stood guard at the
Athens courthouse where Mohammed Rashid was tried before a
three-judge panel. Plainclothes officers packed the courtroom.
   ``I am a member of the PLO and the Palestine Liberation Army. I
was passing through Greece on a secret mission,'' Rashid, 34,
testified.
   ``The Americans are trying to convince people the Palestinians
staged the cruise ship massacre so that I would be released. This
is not true,'' he added.
   Rashid, 34, was accused of entering Greece May 25 with a false
Syrian passport. Police believe gunmen planned to hijack the City
of Poros cruise ship Monday in an attempt to free Rashid.
   Nine people were killed and 98 wounded when terrorists opened
fire on the ship with machine guns and hurled grenades.
   In Bagdhad, Iraq, a spokesman for Palestine Liberation
Organization chairman Yasser Arafat said the group condemned the
ship attack.
   Rashid is also wanted in the United States for allegedly
planting a bomb on a Pan Am jetliner in 1982 that killed one person
and injured 15.
   Rashid claimed his real name was Mohammed Hamdam. He said the
passport used to enter Greece was forged but added, ``We are a
refugee people and rarely can get papers.'' He said the passport
was given to him by his PLO superiors.
   The prosecution asked for a 10-month sentence.
   Greece says it is considering a U.S. extradition request but
that Rashid would have to serve his Greek sentence before he could
be sent to the United States.
   Rashid spoke in Arabic. His testimony was translated for the
court by a translator of the PLO mission in Athens. The trial took
90 minutes.
   Rashid's lawyer, Spyros Fytrakis, asked for Rashid to be freed
pending appeal, but presiding Judge Mihalis Margaritis ordered his
continued detention at Korydallos jail near Athens.
   Rashid was brought to the court Wednesday, but the trial was
held over for a day because his lawyer and interpreter were
unavailable.
   On Wednesday, a previously unknown group linked with
Palestinians claimed responsibility in Beirut for the ship attack.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist government was sharply
criticized in Parliament by the main right-wing opposition New
Democracy Party. It complained that the government failed to
protect innocent tourists at a time of heightened world tension.
   ``After the shooting down of the Iranian Airbus, it was possible
that there would be waves of terrorism and that Greek territory
could be threatened,'' said parliamentary deputy Nicolaos Kostakis.
   He was referring to the U.S. downing of an Iranian airliner on
July 3 over the Persian Gulf, killing all 290 people aboard. The
Pentagon says the plane was mistaken for a fighter.
   Merchant Marine Minister Evangelos Yiannopoulos denied the
government had been lax toward terrorists.
   The exact number of terrorists in the attack remained unclear,
with most accounts by survivors and authorities putting the figure
at three or four.
   In Beirut Wednesday, a group calling itself ``The Organization
of the Martyrs of the Popular Revolution in Palestine'' claimed
responsiblity for the attack in a statement delivered to a Western
news agency.
   It said the attack was in retaliation for ``the escalation in
the operations and murder and extermination by the murderous
Zionist-American gangs in Palestine, Lebanon, the (Persian) Gulf
and all over the world.''
   The statement also claimed responsibility for the explosion of a
car near the cruise ship's home dock about six hours before the
attack on the vessel. The blast killed two people in the car.
   Police speculated the two were accomplices of the ship attackers
and that automatic weapons, grenades and explosives found in the
car were intended for hijacking the ship.
</TEXT>
