<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Netherlands-Kidnap     07-14 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Netherlands-Kidnap,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20-Year Prison Sentence In Kidnap-Murder of Grocery Tycoon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch court today sentenced an
unemployed business consultant to 20 years in prison for the
kidnapping and murder of a Dutch grocery tycoon.
   Ferdi Elsas, 45, was found guilty last month of kidnapping and
shooting Gerrit Jan Heijn, vice president of the
multimillion-dollar Ahold retail concern. Heijn was abducted Sept.
9. His body was found buried in a forest in April.
   Heijn's family paid about $4 million ransom in cash and diamonds.
   Elsas appeared unmoved when Court President C. Terwee read a
summary of the ruling. It was not immediately disclosed whether
Elsas would appeal.
   Heijn, who was 56 at the time of his abduction, was seized at
gunpoint outside his home while leaving for a dental appointment.
   At his trial, Elsas testified that after jumping into the retail
executive's car, he forced Heijn to drive to Renkum near Arnhem in
the eastern Netherlands.
   There, the two walked through a forest for hours, and, after
sharing some sandwiches and orange juice, Elsas killed Heijn with a
shot through the back of his head, according to Elsas' testimony.
   Elsas buried his victim in a grave he had dug weeks before.
   Elsas was arrested after police discovered a 250-guilder note
from the ransom, which surfaced in an Amsterdam supermarket close
to Elsas' house.
</TEXT>
