<DOCNO> AP880714-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-IRAAttack     07-14 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-IRA Attack,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Release Picture of Car Sought in Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH REIMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUISBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German officials today
released a photograph of a car sought in connection with an IRA
bomb attack that injured nine British soldiers.
   Two bombs exploded outside a British army barracks in this
residential town before dawn Wednesday, blasting a hole through a
wall and tearing off part of the roof. Nine soldiers were treated
at the scene for injuries.
   At about the same time as the explosion, shots were fired from a
speeding car at a police road check. No one was injured in the
shooting, but the BMW sedan bearing Dutch license plates got away.
   ``The federal prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe has now released
a photograph of the car to the news media to help in tracing it,''
Duisburg police spokesman Reinhard Pape said today in a telephone
interview.
   Col. Michel Baugniet, chief spokesman for the British army in
West Germany, said he could not provide any information on the
progress of the investigation.
   ``The federal criminal police are leading the investigation, and
they haven't released anything on it,'' Baugniet said.
   About 500 soldiers from the British army's 3rd Armored Division
Transport Regiment are based in Duisburg, 30 miles north of
Cologne, as are soldiers from the regiment's 35 Squadron, which
served in Northern Ireland in 1987.
   The blast Wednesday was the latest in a series of attacks by the
Irish Republican Army on British targets on the European continent.
The group is waging a guerrilla campaign to drive the British out
of Northern Ireland.
   In a statement released in Dublin, the IRA said it carried out
``the bomb attack in West Germany against crown forces.'' It did
not elaborate.
   On March 6 in Gibraltar, British commandos killed three unarmed
IRA guerrillas. In apparent retaliation, IRA terrorists killed
three British airmen in the Netherlands in two separate attacks May
1.
   Two days later, a car bomb was found at a British military base
in the central West German city of Bielefeld. The bomb was
discovered by an alert guard and disposed of before it could
explode.
   A March 1987 car-bomb attack on a British army headquarters in
the West German city of Rheindahlen was the first IRA strike in
continental Europe in about a decade. The blast injured 31 people.
</TEXT>
