<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ComanchePeak     07-14 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Comanche Peak,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuclear Board Dismantled, Completing Pact with Citizens Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By READ MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year dispute over alleged construction flaws
in the Comanche Peak nuclear plant has ended with regulators
endorsing a $10 million settlement between opponents and the
plant's parent utility.
   The deal between the Citizens Association for Sound Energy, the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission and Texas Utilities, Comanche Peak's
operator, ends the last major citizens' opposition to NRC licensing
of the nearly completed plant. ``To me, it's a stunner ... 10 years
of fighting this plant (is over),'' Anthony Roisman, an attorney
for CASE, said Wednesday during the final meeting of the Dallas
Atomic Safety and Licensing Board.
   The three-member board, chaired by Peter Bloch of the NRC,
officially dissolved at the end of Wednesday's hearing.
   It had been formed to investigate CASE's allegations.
   The dispute, which spanned nearly a decade, resulted in the cost
of Comanche Peak to balloon from an estimate of under $1 billion to
$9.1 billion.
   Bloch praised Jack Doyle, a former Comanche Peak engineer who
resigned to point out flaws to the NRC that included faulty welds,
metallurgy and pipe.
   ``Though he isn't a degreed engineer, he knew the truth about
this plant when people who were hired for millions of dollars
either didn't know the truth or refused to see it,'' Bloch said.
   Last week, CASE agreed to drop opposition to Comanche Peak in
exchange for a five-year term for its leader, Juanita Ellis, on a
committee overseeing the plant.
   CASE also will be reimbursed $4.5 million in legal fees and
other expenses by Texas Utilities, utility attorney George Edgar
said.
   In addition, Texas Utilities will set aside $5.5 million to
cover any damages it might have to pay in some other legal actions,
said spokesman Dick Ramsey. Some 50 workers involved in the
construction of the plant have suits pending with the Labor
Department charging construction flaws, said Ms. Ellis.
   In 1984, when the utility began to address the issues raised by
CASE in 1978, Doyle said ``the cooperation has been unbelievable.
At first I thought I was being conned _ I had to be conned. I now
know that was not the case.''
</TEXT>
