<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     07-14 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Wounded in Clash With Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian protesters fought with Israeli
soldiers in the West Bank city of Nablus after reports that two
teen-agers wounded in earlier clashes had died. Hospital officials
said today that two protesters were shot.
   A 12-year-old boy from the Jewish West Bank settlement Gidot
Shomron was struck in the head by a rock in the nearby Arab city of
Qalqiliya, the army said. He lost consciousness for several hours
but was reported in good condition today.
   Dozens of enraged settlers tried to enter Qalqiliya after
Wednesday night's attack but were turned away by soldiers, the army
said. The army is investigating reports that the windshields of
three Arab-owned cars in the city were smashed.
   A small bomb apparently planted by Palestinian militants
exploded today just outside Tel Aviv University. The blast did not
cause injuries or damage, police said.
   In predominantly Arab East Jerusalem, police arrested a
16-year-old Arab caught throwing an empty bottle at an Israeli bus.
It was one of a chain of at least six stone- and bottle-throwing
incidents in the city.
   No one was hurt in the incidents, a police spokesman said.
   The army identified an Israeli soldier killed in a firefight
with Shiite Moslem guerrillas in southern Lebanon as Lt. Uri Maoz,
22, of Yesod Hama'allah near the Lebanese border. Three guerrillas
also were killed in Wednesday's battle.
   Two Nablus teen-agers who were shot Monday in clashes with
Israeli troops died Wednesday, hospital officials said. The
fatalities brought to 222 the number of Palestinians killed in the
7-month-old Arab uprising. Four Israelis have died.
   The deaths sparked fresh protests Wednesday night in Nablus, the
largest West Bank city and a focal point of recent violence.
   About 30 Arabs took to the streets and stoned Israeli soldiers,
army officials said.
   Two Palestinians, a 26-year-old man and a 24-year-old woman,
were shot in the clash, said officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad
Hospital. The man was reported in serious condition with a bullet
wound in his stomach.
   Army officials said they knew of an Arab being shot and were
investigating the circumstances of the shooting.
   Maoz was the eighth Israeli soldier to be killed this year in
clashes in southern Lebanon or during guerrilla infiltration
attempts into Israel. About 30 Israelis have been wounded.
   More than 110 Arab guerrillas also have been killed this year,
according to Israeli reports.
   Also Wednesday, chief military prosecutor Brig. Gen. Amnon
Strashnov said 1,500 Palestinians held without charges in so-called
administrative detention have filed appeals.
   Military judges issues rulings in 450 cases, and in 100 appeals
ordered the detention period reduced or the prisoner released,
Israel army radio said.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, assailants stoned four Israeli buses and
a private car, Israel radio said. In one incident, a soldier aboard
a bus fired in the air as he chased the stone-throwers. Police
arriving at the scene arrested a 16-year-old Arab.
</TEXT>
