<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CouncilWars     07-14 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Council Wars,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor's Allies Reshape Committees; Fuels Black Political Divisions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council allies of Mayor Eugene Sawyer have
stripped power from his key opponents in a meeting marked by
name-calling and police intervention, driving a deeper political
wedge into the city's black community.
   ``This just opens all the old wounds,'' said political scientist
Paul Kleppner of Northern Illinois University.
   Most white aldermen voted to oust eight opponents of the black
mayor, including several influential black aldermen, from committee
chairmanships during an unruly council meeting that ended late
Wednesday.
   At one point during the meeting, police officers rushed to the
floor to break up a near-fight between Dorothy Tillman, a black
Sawyer critic, and Marlene Carter, a black Sawyer ally.
   ``One more step and I would have put her on the floor,'' Ms.
Tillman told reporters. ``My mama didn't buy me dolls when I was a
girl.''
   The session was reminiscent of the raucous, all-night council
meeting in December when Sawyer, then an alderman, was named to
succeed Harold Washington, the city's first black mayor, a week
after Washington's death. Sawyer was supported then by many of the
same white aldermen who helped reshape the committees Wednesday.
   Sawyer told reporters he would have preferred to wait until the
end of the month to restructure committee leadership so he could
get more support for the plan. But he said the majority of the
council ``got anxious.''
   ``I had to seize control,'' he said.
   ``We have an agenda to move, a city to run. They have another
agenda,'' he said of his opponents, ``and it's not mine.''
   Allies of the mayor said the committee reassignments were
necessary because Sawyer's opponents were using their posts to
spoil his administration.
   Sawyer needed a ``real balanced reorganization,'' said Michael
Sheahan, a white supporter.
   But opponents predicted further erosion in Sawyer's black
political base.
   Many of the blacks in the gallery shouted, ``Go home, Uncle
Tom!'' to some of the black aldermen who defended the purge.
   ``Mr. Mayor, I think you've made a terrible mistake,'' alderman
Danny Davis said on the Council floor, pointing a finger at Sawyer.
``It looks like everything we fought for, that Harold Washington
died for, is being turned back.
   ``I guess you and your colleagues have declared war in the black
community.''
   Davis is one of three ousted aldermen who have indicated they
will run against Sawyer for mayor.
   Kleppner, who has tracked voting patterns in Chicago for the
U.S. Justice Department, said Sawyer will find few political gains.
   ``He can't go back to his normal constituency _ blacks,''
Kleppner said. ``There's no place else but to go to the white
ethnics, the opponents of Harold Washington, who put (Sawyer) there
in the first place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
