<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingYacht     07-14 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Yacht,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Sailor Safe, But Yacht In Shambles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A contestant in a single-handed
trans-Atlantic yacht race who had not been heard from since late
last month has been found but with her sloop in a shambles.
   ``I feel fine, wonderful,'' said Noelle Corbett of Miami. ``But
I feel very disappointed to have come this far and not be able to
finish the race.''
   Corbett, 33, was found Tuesday aboard her 39-foot sloop,
Outrageous, by a fishing boat, authorities said. She was one of the
last remaining contestants in the Carlsberg Single-Handed
Transatlantic Yacht Race.
   Corbett's sloop, which was less than 100 miles from the finish
line in Newport when found, was towed into Woods Hole, Mass., by a
Coast Guard cutter.
   Corbett said she weathered three gales during her crossing from
Plymouth, England. The boom of her yacht was broken. Part of her
rigging was broken. Her sails were in shreds, except for one small
headsail, the only one she could use. She had no electric power for
the last 10 days and her autopilot was out of commission.
   She said her husband, Jim, plans to repair the yacht at Woods
Hole and make the rest of the trip under power to Newport, she said.
   More than 90 sailors left Plymouth on June 5. Seventy-one have
finished the race; 21, including Corbett, have withdrawn, and three
British sailors are still at sea.
</TEXT>
