<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan-POWs     07-14 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-POWs,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Alliance Agrees to Talk To Soviets About POWs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghan guerrilla alliance has
agreed to direct talks with the Soviet Union about prisoners of
war, the alliance chairman said today.
   Sayed Ahmad Gailani refused to say whether the decision cancels
earlier guerrilla vows to keep Soviet prisoners of war for leverage
in future talks on a new Afghan government.
   There was no immediate comment from the Soviets.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, leader of one of two Hezb-e-Islami factions
within the seven-party guerrilla alliance, claims to have ``a good
number'' of Soviet prisoners. Last week, he had said no
negotiations for their release would take place ``until all Soviets
leave all Afghanistan.''
   But Wednesday's decision to negotiate with the Soviets was
unanimous.
   Farooq Azam, with Gailani's National Islamic Front of
Afghanistan, said reports reaching the guerrilla alliance say the
Soviets are ready to negotiate with the guerrillas about prisoners
of war.
   The Soviet Union says 312 soldiers are missing. The guerrillas
refuse to say how many prisoners they hold.
   The International Committee for the Red Cross has been given
responsibility for prisoners of war, said Diego Cordovez, U.N.
special envoy, but the guerrillas say they will talk only to a
Soviet delegation. Talks must be direct or not at all, said Azam.
   Gailani refused to say whether the alliance decision means the
guerrilla groups will pool their prisoners and decide their fate as
a single unit or whether they will remain prisoners of individual
groups.
   In March, representatives of Hekmatyar's group met with a Soviet
delegation to negotiate a prisoner exchange, and a formula of one
Soviet prisoner for 25 Afghan guerrillas was struck. However,
Hekmatyar cancelled the agreement after an agreement was signed
April 14 in Geneva, under which the Soviets agreed to withdraw
their troops from Afghanistan.
   The only prisoner exchange since the accord was in late June,
when Rasoul Sayyaf's Ittehad-e-Islami group turned over one Soviet
soldier for seven Afghan prisoners.
   Gailani said the decision to open direct talks with the Soviet
Union on prisoner exchanges was made on ``humanitarian grounds.''
   The Soviets entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
Marxist government fight the guerrillas, who wanted to set up an
Islamic state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
