<DOCNO> AP880714-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Methodists-Politics     07-14 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Methodists-Politics,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates For Methodist Bishops Become Political Animals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE JUNALUSKA, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men and women who seek to become
bishops in the United Methodist Church are supposed to wait for
their ``calling,'' but some of them also believe it helps to
campaign a little for the job.
   Seven new bishops _ a record for the jurisdiction _ will be
elected at this week's Southeastern Jurisdictional Conference
before the gathering of 588 Methodists from nine Southeastern
states ends Saturday.
   In the weeks leading up to the meeting, some of the 14 official
candidates issued brochures touting themselves. Some of them also
have a member of their delegation acting as campaign manager.
   Campaigning is nothing new to the jurisdiction, but some
observers believe it has become more of a factor this year.
   ``I believe God can live with this process better than the
backroom politics of past years,'' said one delegate, Nowell
Bingham of Murray, Ky.
   The current nominating system was put into effect back in the
1970s in an effort to open up the election process, said Bob Lear,
director of the United Methodist News Service in Washington.
   Before that, he said, most of the work was done behind the
scenes.
   ``The nominating system has had the affect of making the
politics more intense,'' said Lear, who has been covering church
elections since 1960. ``I have a stack of campaign brochures in my
office to prove it.''
   Under the new system, candidates go before their local
conference to explain their positions. The local delegates then
decide which candidate from their area to endorse. Delegates to the
regional conference make the final selection.
   Retired Bishop H. Ellis Finger, of Knoxville, Tenn., was elected
in 1964, before the nominating system existed.
   ``There obviously were conversations but you weren't required to
appear before the delegates for an inquiry,'' he said. ``A person
who was elected in those years was presented in conversation, in
dialogue.''
   C.R. Hager, a delegate from Lexington, Ky., was a member of the
committee that revised the election system.
   ``There was a lot of concern about the advertising,'' he said.
``Before that, it wasn't public. It was a calling, so a candidate
wasn't supposed to get out to publicize himself.''
   Hager believes the current system is far superior to the old
one. ``It gives us the opportunity to know about the candidates,''
he said.
   Bingham said all 14 official candidates met with the various
delegations at the church's general conference earlier this year in
St. Louis. ``We videotaped it so we could bring it back for our
church members to review,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
