<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Oil     07-14 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Oil,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Announces Atlantic Oil Find</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Sarney announced
that Brazil has discovered about 100 million barrels worth of oil
in the Atlantic Ocean.
   ``Tests carried out off the coasts of Parana, Sao Paulo and
Santa Catarina states have revealed a 26-square-mile basin with
potential for producing as much as 10,000 barrels a day,'' Sarney
told reporters Wednesday.
   Brazil produces about 600,000 barrels of oil a day.
   In March, Sarney said the state-run oil company, Petrobras,
suspected there were oil deposits in the region but gave no
estimates of the quantities involved.
   According to Sarney, the oil was discovered 112 miles off
Brazil's southern coast at a depth of 390 feet. He also said the
government oil monopoly had found substantial reserves of gas in
the new basin.
   Brazil for decades produced oil only in its northeastern
regions, but in the 1970s major off-shore finds were made off the
coast of Rio de Janeiro state, allowing Brazil to increase its
domestically produced oil supply from 20 percent to 55 percent.
   The country now produces about 60 percent of the oil it consumes.
</TEXT>
