<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Latvians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0556,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Dissident Grigoryants and 14 Others Arrested After
Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `The fate...' with 3 grafs to ADD report that
protesters held at militia post. Picks up 6th pvs, `The Latvian...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a dissident journalist and 14
other demonstrators today after they unfurled the Latvian flag and
several protest banners near the Kremlin.
   ``We have the right to speak out. That is what democracy is,'' a
Latvian demonstrator told a police officer who ordered the group to
disperse. ``Is this glasnost?'' asked the man, referring to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of open debate.
   The man then opened Latvia's red and white flag. A plainclothes
officer immediately ripped the flag from the man's arms and dragged
him to a bus.
   Other officers grabbed the rest of the demonstrators who had
gathered in pouring rain on the steps of the Lenin Library _ within
sight of the Kremlin _ and hauled them onto the yellow bus.
   The fate of those arrested was not immediately clear.
   One demonstrator who apparently managed to elude arrest, Andrei
Shilkov, telephoned The Associated Press and said the protesters
were held at a Moscow militia post. Shilkov is a correspondent for
the unofficial magazine ``Glasnost.''
   A worker at the post told the AP by phone the demonstrators had
not been arrested and then hung up the phone.
   The Latvian man was wearing a T-shirt referring to the 1941
deportation of tens of thousands of Baltic residents whom dictator
Josef Stalin accused of being Nazi sympathizers. The Soviet Union
annexed the Baltic nations of Latvia, Estonia and Lithuania in 1940
under a secret agreement with Nazi Germany.
   The journalist, Sergei I. Grigoryants, whom Gorbachev condemned
in a May interview as a ``parasite'' ``sponging on the democratic
process,'' managed to elude officers for a few minutes. But after
handing reporters a statement about the protest, he too was
arrested.
   The demonstrators also included representatives of informal
political groups from Estonia and Lithuania. Also present were
Ukrainian human rights activists.
   One protester held a banner demanding in English, ``Return
Nagorno-Karabakh to Armenia.'' Another held a sign that read in
Russian, ``Freedom to Paruyr Ayrikyan,'' an Armenian nationalist
arrested in the republic's capital, Yerevan, in March.
   Armenians have been campaigning since February for transfer of
the mostly Armenian Nagorno-Karabakh region from the republic of
Azerbaijan to Armenia.
   Grigoryants, 47, has become one of the Soviet Union's most
prominent political activists.
   After spending four years in prison for underground writings, he
was released in February 1987 under a general amnesty. Since then,
he has taken advantage of Gorbachev's openness policy to produce a
magazine called ``Glasnost.''
   On May 9, however, he and four other people were arrested
outside the house they were using as an office for the magazine. He
spent seven days in jail on a conviction of disobeying a police
officer.
   Andrei Shilkov, 36, another member of the ``Glasnost'' magazine
staff, was arrested today.
</TEXT>
