<HEAD>At Least Four Dead After Suspected Crack House Is Firebombed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf with four grafs to UPDATE with quotes from
neighbors; ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apartment building described by neighbors as a
crack house was firebombed today, and at least four people were
killed and six injured, police and fire officials said.
   ``All the witnesses that were interviewed have indicated there
was a firebombing,'' said a police arson inspector who declined
identification.
   A homicide officer who refused to give his name said at least
four people were killed. The victims could not immediately be
identified. ``We don't even know their sex,'' he said.
   No arrests were made, the arson inspector said, adding that the
bodies of other victims might be found in the ruins.
   Six people, including two who jumped from the second floor, were
taken to Detroit Receiving Hospital, the homicide officer said.
Their conditions were not immediately known.
   The blaze, reported at 3:16 a.m., was brought under control more
than four hours later, said a Fire Department dispatcher who also
declined to be identified.
   Otto Cureton, who lived next door, said he heard glass breaking,
went outside and saw five men running away. ``I thought they were
trying to break into my house,'' he said. ``I didn't even know it
was a fire.''
   Cureton and Doretha Thompson, who also lived next door,
speculated that the fire was set by rival crack dealers.
   ``The police had to come here a number of times,'' said Ms.
Thompson, 35, who with her two daughters escaped injury. ``They did
their business right outside.''
   The wood-frame duplex in which Cureton and Thompson lived also
was burned out.
</TEXT>
