<2ND_LINE>PM-Doctor-Death,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Dies During Surgery, Colleague Flies 40 Miles To Complete
Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNION SPRINGS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only obstetrician-gynecologist in
two rural counties died while performing a hysterectomy, and
another doctor had to fly 40 miles from Montgomery to complete the
operation.
   Dr. Robert X. Williams, 54, suffered a heart attack Wednesday
and was pronounced dead in the operating room of Bullock County
Hospital, officials said.
   A helicopter from St. Margaret's Hospital flew in Dr. Judi
Jehle, who successfully completed the surgery, said Don Priori,
chairman of the Bullock County Hospital Board.
   Williams' death leaves Bullock and Macon counties without an
obstetrician-gynecologist. The two counties in southeastern Alabama
are among the poorest in the state and have high infant-mortality
rates.
   ``As far as OB delivery goes, it will close us up,'' Priori said.
   Williams delivered between 60 and 80 babies a month, he said.
``That's a pretty heavy delivery load for one doctor,'' Priori
said. ``He had more than two a day.''
   Priori said a search has begun to try to find a replacement
physician.
   After Williams' death Wednesday, two women who had gone into
labor were rushed to Baptist Medical Center in Montgomery.
   ``We're worried about the women who are real close to
delivery,'' Priori said. ``The two we sent to Baptist hospital in
Montgomery by ambulance were already having contractions. We're
watching several others now. We have the ambulance standing by.''
   Bullock County's infant mortality rate in 1987 was 21.5 deaths
per 1,000 births, according to state health officials. The state
average was 12.2.
</TEXT>
