<HEAD>ACLU Challenges New Jersey Town's Law Requiring Permit to Move</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with hearing postponed, city
attorneys declining comment. PICKS UP graf 7th pvs, `The ordinance
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union is
challenging an ordinance requiring people to obtain a permit from
the police chief before they can move in or out of the city.
   The ACLU is defending Lenna Palmer, who is accused of violating
the municipal code by moving out of East Orange, an urban,
blue-collar community of 77,000 outside Newark. Palmer received a
summons in May.
   ``The city has a right to know when people move in and out of
its town,'' said city Clerk Earl Williams. He said said the purpose
of the ordinance is to allow officials to find people who owe the
city money.
   But Eric Neisser, legal director of the state ACLU, said the
``basic right of all people in this country is to travel and move
around, obviously in states and between states, and this ordinance
restricts that right.''
   ``It affects privacy primarily because the ordinance says you
have to file an application telling them where you're moving to,''
Neisser said.
   At a hearing today, Municipal Judge Ernest Booker postponed the
case until Aug. 17 after city attorneys said they needed more time
to study the issues.
   The judge also told both sides to submit arguments explaining
why issues of constitutionality should be decided by a municipal
court.
   Police Chief George Daher was out of town and could not be
reached for comment Wednesday, officials said.
   The city's attorneys declined to comment outside court today.
   The ordinance requires a person to file with the chief a $2
application listing the person's old and new address, the date of
the move and how the person's property will be transported.
   Moving is prohibited after sundown or on Sundays and violators
are subject to a $500 fine and 90 days in jail.
   Marianne Tolomeo, an ACLU attorney defending Ms. Palmer, said
the U.S. Supreme Court has held that there is a constitutional
right to travel and struck down a Nevada law that levied a $1 tax
on everyone leaving the state.
   Ms. Palmer now lives in a neighboring community.
</TEXT>
