<HEAD>Three Children Drown When Wake From Tugboat Knocks Them Down in
River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three children who drowned when a tugboat's
wake apparently knocked them off their feet had been warned by
their parents or grandparents to stay away from the river, the
coroner said today.
   The three were wading in the Tennessee-Tombigbee River with two
other children Wednesday morning, said police spokesman Willie
Williams.
   He identified the dead as Sherea Blanks, 9, and Andrea Nettles,
10, both of Jackson, and Kevin Scruggs, 10, of Detroit, who was
visiting his grandparents.
   A 10-year-old and a 9-year-old escaped unharmed.
   Alabama Electric Cooperative workers on the other side of the
river saw the children go under and called police, said Clarke
County Coroner Wayne Lathan.
   ``The river is not that deep where they were but the kids were
not that big,'' Lathan said. ``Apparently the wake from the tug
must have knocked them off their feet.''
   He said although the children had been warned not to go to the
river, ``they slipped off and went down there anyway.''
   Swimming in the river is not prohibited, but Lathan said the
children were near a bend unsafe for swimmers because of the wake
from river traffic.
