<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0490 07-14 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Confiscate Sugar Refinery, Opposition Says Crackdown
Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs: `The Agrarian...' and 1
graf after 18th graf pvs: `The Foreign...' to CLARIFY how the
nationalization is seen as repressive and contradictory of recent
moves by Ortega.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government has
nationalized the nation's largest and oldest private enterprise in
what the opposition calls the latest in a series of repressive
moves.
   The Agrarian Reform Ministry announced the takeover of the San
Antonio sugar refinery on Wednesday. It said the owners hadn't
invested in the company since 1981, hurting sales, dollar income
and working conditions.
   The move leaves nearly the entire sugar industry in the hands of
the government, which has virtually no money to pay compensation.
The San Antonio mill had become a symbol of private enterprise,
which the opposition favors over socialism.
   The crackdown by the Sandinistas, who in recent months appeared
to be easing controls on society, began Sunday when police used
tear gas to break up an authorized opposition march.
   They beat and arrested several dozen of the 10,000 demontrators.
   The crackdown appears a reaction to continued attacks by
U.S.-backed Contra rebels, the appearance of U.S. Embassy personnel
at Sundays march, increasing domestic dissent and pressure from
hardline Sandinista leaders.
   With the economic crisis deepening, opposition groups seem
stronger and more united than ever.
   On Monday, the Foreign Ministry ordered the expulsion of U.S.
Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other embassy diplomats.
   The Sandinistas charged that the U.S. Embassy supported Sunday's
march as part of a plan to destabilize the government by creating
an internal front.
   At the same time, the Sandinistas closed the Roman Catholic
radio station indefinitely and suspended for 15 days the
publication of the only opposition newspaper, La Prensa.
   The press restrictions mean neither can cover ceremonies next
Tuesday celebarting the ninth anniversary of the revolution that
ousted President Anastasio Somoza or the ``hunger march'' an
opposition group plans for July 24.
   Since August, the Sandinistas had loosened the reins to comply
with a regional peace plan, restoring many liberties taken away
during the nearly 7-year-old war with the Contras.
   La Prensa was permitted to reopen after being shut 15 months and
to publish without censorship for the first time in five years.
   The moves paid off when in February, Congress rejected President
Reagan's request for continued military aid to the Contras.
   But hardline Sandinistas, including Interior Minister Tomas
Borge, reportedly objected to the concessions. Borge controls the
media and the police.
   In March, the Sandinistas began peace talks with the Contras and
on March 23 a temporary cease-fire agreement was signed. A series
of meetings since has failed to produce any concrete results.
   Talks broke off June 9, but the Sandinistas have twice
unilaterally renewed temporary truces. Over the past week, they
have reported daily Contra attacks.
   The latest bulletin by the Defense Ministry said one civilian
was killed and six wounded Wednesday when a Tranportation Ministry
truck ran over a mine about 95 miles northeast of Managua.
   The Foreign Ministry sent a note to U.S. Secretary of State
George P. Shultz protesting the incident.
   The expropriation of the sugar mill appears to contradict
earlier statements by President Daniel Ortega.
   In mid-June, Ortega announced the latest in moves designed to
revive the economy. The government says the war has caused $3.6
billion in damage, and annual inflation runs well over 1,000
percent.
   Ortega said the government needs to move away from Marxist
economic measures and lean toward capitalism. He said monetary
rather than moral incentives should bolster production.
   But most sectors balked, and the Sandinistas ended up agreeing
to provide a small amount of beans, rice and sugar to workers in
non-productive areas, such as doctors, teachers and soldiers.
   The San Antonio sugar refinery confiscated on Wednesday was
described as ``the last of a mixed economy in Nicaragua'' by
Gilberto Cuadra, the vice president of the anti-government Private
Enterprise Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
