<HEAD>Imported Toy Carts Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two types of toy carts imported from Taiwan
are being recalled because they could pose a choking hazard, the
Consumer Product Safety Commission announced today.
   Labeled ``Musical Car ST-22 (A or B) Made in Taiwan,'' the toys
came in both wind-up and battery-powered models and sold for about
$2.50 each, according to the importer, Li Peng Enterprises of Los
Angeles.
   The toys consist of a panda pushing another panda in a
four-wheel cart. Each cart has an umbrella with plastic balls and
disks hanging from it. These items can come off and present a
choking hazard for small children, the safety commission said.
   Parents should take the toy away from children and either
discard it or return it to the retailer for a refund, the agency
said. About 4,800 of the wind-up versions and 3,600 battery-powered
toys were sold between November 1987 and January of this year,
officials said.
   People needing more information can contact the safety
commission at 1-800-638-2772.
