<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0422 07-14 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0422,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Fernandez Challenges Secrets Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 8 grafs new; picks up 4th graf, The statute, and SUBS pvs
6th graf, Fernandez's lawyer, to make editing changes to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the case of an ex-CIA agent
accused of conspiring to illegally ship arms to Nicaraguan rebels
today rejected a defense objection to pre-trial procedures for
handling classified documents.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. approved security
rules proposed by prosecutors to govern the handling of thousands
of pages of classified documents that were gathered by prosecutors
in the case.
   A defense attorney for Joseph F. Fernandez, the CIA's former
station chief in Costa Rica, argued that the order contained so
many restrictions on the use of classified documents by the defense
team ``as to be constitutionally faulty.''
   ``This is a completely unprecedented case, in terms of the
defendant and the nature of the indictment and the nature of the
information that will be needed'' to defend the charges, said
defense lawyer Thomas E. Wilson.
   Robinson approved the protective order proposed by prosecutors
on the staff of independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh but said he
would be willing to make changes if the defense found the rules
unworkable.
   The order restricts the use of classified documents to a secure
facility that is supervised by a court security officer. Witnesses
whom defense lawyers want to show documents must sign pledges not
to reveal the information to others.
   Robinson granted Wilson's request that the names of people
signing such pledges not be shown to prosecutors. ``You don't need
to know that,'' the judge told Hassler.
   The judge scheduled an Aug. 15 hearing to consider Fernandez's
challenge to the constitutionality of the Classified Information
Procedures Act as it applies to his case.
   The statute requires defendants to notify the government of
specific government secrets they plan to divulge during the trial
to defend criminal charges.
   The defense contends that the requirement tramples on
Fernandez's right to a fair trial because the case involves at
least 60,000 secret documents as well as witnesses whose very
identity is still classified.
   Wilson argued in court papers filed Wednesday that prosecutors
would be tipped to the defense strategy if told in advance of the
secrets he planned to divulge.
   ``Testimony of virtually every government witness (and the vast
majority of likely defense witnesses) will inevitably contain a
great deal of classified information,'' the defense brief said.
   ``Even the identity of many of the witnesses in the case _
witnesses for both the government and the defense _ will be
classified,'' Fernandez's lawyer said.
   Wilson noted that Fernandez's testimony to congressional
committees investigating the Iran-Contra affair was given in closed
sessions and released only after numerous references to classified
information were deleted.
   Fernandez, who operated in Central America under the pseudonym
of Tomas Castillo, is charged with conspiring to operate an illegal
arms-supply network to the Nicaraguan rebels in defiance of a
congressional ban on such military assistance.
   He also is accused of lying to his CIA superiors as well as to
the presidential commission headed by former Sen. John Tower,
R-Texas, that investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
   His constitutional challenge is similar to one mounted by fired
White House aide Oliver L. North, former national security adviser
John M. Poindexter, and arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air
Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord.
   The four are charged with conspiring to illegally divert
U.S.-Iran arms-sales profits to the Contras.
   In that case, U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell denied a
defense motion to declare the statute unconstitutional. Gesell has
ordered four separate trials and scheduled North's for Sept. 20.
   On Wednesday, Gesell also scheduled closed hearings on Aug. 8
and Aug. 22 to consider North's proposals to use secret documents
at his trial.
</TEXT>
