<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MsvsMrs 1stLd-Writethru a0525 07-14 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ms vs Mrs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0525,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Apologizes For Outlawing `Ms.' and Maiden Name</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs with judge apologizing. PICKS UP 8th
graf pvs, `During a ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 73-year-old federal judge apologized today
for outlawing the courtesy title Ms. in his courtroom and
interrupting a race discrimination trial to scold an attorney for
using her maiden name.
   ``I unfortunately lost my temper,'' Senior U.S. District Judge
Hubert I. Teitelbaum said in a statement.
   ``I have always referred to married women by their married name.
This is the way my generation was taught,'' he said. ``I recognize
your right to be addressed in any manner in which you see fit, and
I apologize for my comment and the resulting situation.'
   Teitelbaum directed his apology to Barbara Wolvovitz, whom he
told on Friday, ``From here on, in this courtroom you will use Mrs.
Lobel. That's your name.'' She is the wife of University of
Pittsburgh law professor Jules Lobel.
   The judge originally threatened the lawyer with jail when she
resisted, and when her co-counsel, Jon Pushinsky, came to her
defense, Teitelbaum found him in contempt for ``officious
intermeddling'' and gave him a suspended 30-day jail sentence.
   Ms. Wolvovitz on Monday asked for mistrial, which Teitelbaum
rejected, adding, ``What if I call you sweetie?'' He then settled
on calling her ``counselor.''
   In his apology, Teitelbaum said he would grant a mistrial if the
defense requested one again before the jury returned with a verdict.
   During a disjointed dialogue Friday that covered about 20 pages
of court transcript, Teitelbaum told Ms. Wolvovitz that Mrs. Lobel
is her legal name ``under the laws of the state of Pennsylvania.''
   ``And that's what I want you to be, to call yourself from here
on in this courtroom,'' he said. ``That's an intolerable kind of
thing.''
   The judge claimed a married woman must petition Common Pleas
Court for permission to use her maiden name. However, the
Pennsylvania Family Law Practice and Procedure Handbook said no
legal proceedings are required.
   Teitelbaum, presiding over a race discrimination suit against
PPG Industries Inc., also asked each of the six female jurors
Friday if she used her husband's name or maiden name. All used
their husbands' names.
   The trial began June 23, but the issue of ``Ms.'' in
Teitelbaum's court never surfaced before Friday.
   The case went to the jury Wednesday. Ms. Wolvovitz said she
would not decide whether to file a complaint against the judge
until after the jury delivers its verdict.
   Teitelbaum, 73, a former U.S. attorney appointed to the federal
bench by President Nixon in 1970, declined to comment Wednesday to
The Associated Press.
   According to the American Bar Association, Ms. Wolvovitz could
file a complaint with the 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals in
Philadelphia, which could decide to publicly or privately admonish
the judge, said Ernest Zavodnyk, with the Chicago-based judicial
administration division.
   Ms. Wolvovitz, 36, said she was ``in shock for two days.''
   ``I've practiced for 10 years. I've gotten into arguments with
judges but never over something like this. I can't quite understand
what happened,'' said Ms. Wolvovitz, who had never argued a case
before Teitelbaum. ``After it was over and the jury left, I had
tears in my eyes.''
   ``We didn't know what to do. She started crying. I started
crying,'' said Ms. Wolvovitz's client, Charles Gavin.
   Teitelbaum retreated Monday on his threat to jail Pushinsky,
saying, ``Did you really think you were going to jail?''
   When Pushinsky said he didn't ``draw any conclusions,''
Teitelbaum said, ``I just thought over the weekend I'd let you
think about it.''
   ``I never thought he was such a Neanderthal,'' said National
Organization for Women President Molly Yard, a Pittsburgh resident
who is familiar with Teitelbaum. ``I can't understand how anybody
who's bright enough to be on federal court can make such an error
in judgment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CurlingIronRecall     07-14 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Curling Iron Recall,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conair ``Wave Maker'' Curling Iron Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three models of the ``Wave Maker'' curling
irons by Conair are being recalled because of a possible burn
hazard, the Consumer Product Safety Commission announced today.
   The agency said the 1987 models CD 20M, CD 21M and CD 22M may,
under certain conditions, short circuit and pose a burn or fire
hazard.
   Only about 5,000 of the approximately 76,000 units sold pose the
problem, the agency said. However, 82 incidents have been reported
of the line cord shorting or igniting. About 20 cases involved
minor burns to users, officials said.
   The curling irons have mauve handles, silver barrel and white
plastic tip. They carry the model number and the following date
codes: 01 87E, 02 87E, 03 87E, 04 87E, 05 87E, 04-87 and 05-87.
   Owners of the irons should stop using them, tag the unit with
their name and address and mail it to Conair Corporation-Wave
Makers, 11 Executive Avenue, Edison, N.J. 08817. The company will
repair or replace the irons and reimburse the customer for postage.
Customers may also return the irons to the retailer where purchased
for a refund.
   Some of the Wave Makers were repaired before going on sale, and
those carry a label marked ``inspected'' with the letter `R' after
the model number.
   People needing more information can call Conair at
1-800-631-5391 or the Safety Commission at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
