<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PeaceConvoy 1stLd-Writethru a0494 07-14 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peace Convoy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0494,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Vehicles in Veterans' Peace Convoy Cross U.S. Border,
Spokesman Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with group spokesman saying all 15 convoy
vehicles have crossed border, quote from Customs saying no change
in policy. Editing thereafter to delete redundant material and
tighten. No pickup. May be topped; convoy group to hold news
conference 1 p.m. EDT in Nuevo Laredo, Mexico.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 14 trucks and a bus in the Veterans'
Peace Convoy carrying supplies to Nicaragua have crossed the border
into Mexico despite earlier U.S. efforts to block the group's
journey, a spokesman said today.
   The vehicles that arrived at this Texas-Mexico border city
Friday crossed the Rio Grande without incident. Among them were
three vehicles that had earlier been stopped and towed away on
Saturday, said spokesman Raul Valdez.
   ``The same vehicles that got stopped Saturday ... paid 75 cents
and got across,'' said Valdez.
   He said the 15 vehicles were clearly marked ``Veterans Peace
Convoy'' or displayed similar slogans. One truck has been shuttling
people back and forth across the border, he said.
   He said the group is puzzled why American authorities stopped
trying to block the convoy.
   Customs officials had prevented the trucks from crossing the
border at least three times, contending that taking the vehicles to
Nicaragua would violate a 3-year-old trade embargo against that
country.
   Customs Service spokeswoman Donna De La Torre in Houston said
today the agency has not changed its policy.
   ``Three vehicles did cross yesterday but they declared their
intent to go to Mexico only. It is not against the law to go to
Mexico. A fourth vehicle also approached and the driver said he was
going to Nicaragua, but he was not allowed to cross,'' she said.
   ``I am aware of reports that other vehicles have crossed since
then,'' she said. ``But they have crossed without the knowledge and
approval of the U.S. Customs Service. Without advance notice of
export activity, the Customs Service does not staff southbound
lanes. I would not be surprised that some vehicles had mingled with
legitimate traffic and crossed.''
   Texas Rural Legal Aid lawyer William Beardall told a federal
judge Wednesday that 10 convoy vehicles had crossed without
incident. His comments came during a hearing on a lawsuit convoy
members filed against the government to try to win approval to take
the vehicles, which are loaded with food and medical supplies, to
Nicaragua.
   Convoy members oppose U.S. government policies in Nicaragua,
including the embargo and U.S. support for Contra rebels fighting
the leftist Sandinista government. The group is also sending about
300 tons of aid by ship.
   ``A vehicle can also be used to commit an act of terrorism,''
Justice Department attorney John Tyler said at Wednesday's hearing.
   The government's position is that the food and medical supplies
qualify as humanitarian aid exempt from the embargo but that the
vehicles do not constitute humanitarian aid.
   Convoy members have refused to sign forms promising they will
return the vehicles within 30 days.
   U.S. District Judge George P. Kazen gave both sides until July
21 to file briefs in the case.
   The convoy first tried to cross the U.S. border June 15, and
Customs officials temporarily detained four trucks.
   On Saturday, police arrested eight convoy members when they
refused to leave the road leading to a toll booth at a Rio Grande
bridge. One of the eight was arrested again Monday when he tried to
drive across again.
   Violating the embargo could mean 10 years in prison and fines up
to $50,000, Conroy said.
</TEXT>
