<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AldaySlayings     07-14 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alday Slayings,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Guilty In Slayings of Farm Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last of three men awaiting retrial in
the 1973 slayings of six members of a farm family pleaded guilty
today and was sentenced to life in prison.
   George Elder Dungee, 50, pleaed guilty to six counts of murder.
He was to have been retried later this year. His 1974 conviction
had been overturned by a federal appeals court on grounds that
pre-trial publicity prevented a fair trial.
   Muscogee County Superior Court Judge Hugh Lawson sentenced
Dungee to three consecutive life terms and three concurrent life
terms.
   ``This is the sentence we had hoped to get to avoid the death
penalty,'' said defense attorney Stephen Bright.
   Seminole County District Attorney Charles Ferguson had announced
this week he would not seek the death penalty against Dungee
because of a new Georgia law prohibiting execution of the mentally
retarded.
   Court-ordered tests, he said, found Dungee ``significantly
sub-average'' in intelligence.
   Dungee, Carl Isaacs and Wayne Coleman were convicted and
sentenced to die for murdering six members of the Ned Alday family
during a robbery at the Alday farm near Donalsonville in Seminole
County.
   The three escapees from a Maryland prison killed five Alday men,
shooting them at close range in a mobile home, then raped and shot
a woman in a field nearby. Their convictions were overturned in
1985.
   Isaacs was convicted earlier this year in a retrial in Houston
County and was again sentenced to death. Coleman was convicted in
DeKalb County but avoided the death penalty when the jury
deadlocked over the sentence.
   Bright said Dungee has an IQ of 64-69.
   ``His involvement was by far the least of any of those
involved,'' Bright said. ``There's no doubt his mental limitations
had something to do with it.''
</TEXT>
