<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseProbe-Newspapers     07-14 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Newspapers,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Prosecutors Oppose Disclosure of Defense Fraud Documents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publication of search warrant affidavits in
the probe of defense industry fraud could prompt destruction of
evidence, said prosecutors in opposing efforts by two newspaper
publishers to unseal the papers.
   ``Revealing the contents of the affidavits may well encourage
document destruction and other acts that would have the practical
effect of putting major felons beyond the reach of justice,'' U.S.
Attorney Henry Hudson of the Eastern District of Virginia said in a
brief filed Wednesday.
   The Times Mirror Co. group, publisher of the Los Angeles Times,
and Copley Press Inc., publisher of the San Diego Union and the
Tribune, joined last week in efforts to have the affidavits made
public.
   The newspaper organizations petitioned to unseal all documents
relating to search warrants executed June 14 at Southern California
offices of the Northrop Corp., Teledyne Industries, Litton
Industries and the Los Angeles home of defense consultant Fred
Lackner.
   A hearing is scheduled Friday before a U.S. magistrate on
motions made by the news media organizations.
   The prosecutors contended that disclosure of the information,
which includes details of wiretaps and was used to persuade judges
to approve search warrants, could prompt destruction of evidence
and might encourage ``selective amnesia'' among witnesses.
   ``In the short time since the execution of the search warrants
became public, the government has already become aware of several
incidents of destruction of documents related to this case,'' said
the brief by Hudson and three of his assistants. They also noted
that ``the affidavits discuss specific statements from intercepted
conversations,'' which would clearly reveal the identities of
targets of the investigation.
   The publishers contend most information about the probe is
already public.
   The prosecutors asked that the affidavits remain sealed until
the investigation has progressed ``to the point where it can safely
withstand disclosure of the sealed information.''
</TEXT>
