<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SafetyLesson-Rescue     07-14 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Safety Lesson-Rescue,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girls Remember Fire Safety Lesson, Rescue Elderly Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-age girls rescued an
87-year-old man from his burning house, and said they remembered
from a junior high school lesson what to do.
   Shontier McDaniels and Wanda Boone, both 15, were walking
Wednesday night with another friend, Chevon Moore, also 15, when
they noticed flames in the home of Josh Williams.
   Williams said he was watching television in his bedroom when he
felt heat behind him. He said he unsucessfully tried to douse the
blaze with water from his kitchen.
   Miss Moore went for help while Miss McDaniels and Miss Boone,
both students at McIntyre Junior High School, went to the house.
   ``Then I snatched the door open and realized (there) was too
much smoke in the house,'' Miss Boone said. ``Shontier and I began
to crawl on the floor on our knees.''
   They said they learned from fire safety films how to behave
during a fire.
   Confronted with thick smoke in the front of the house, the two
teen-agers crawled back out the front door, ran to the back of the
house and re-entered through the back door, again on their hands
and knees.
   ``I was on the floor crawling when I saw a lot of flames on the
right side of me,'' Miss McDaniels said, ``but I did not see Mr.
Williams because of the smoke.''
   But then she said she heard Williams throwing water on the fire.
   That enabled the two to locate Williams, and they grabbed him by
the arms and pulled him from the house.
   ``I was glad to see them,'' said Williams, who was not injured.
   Meanwhile, Miss Moore had located a neighbor who reported the
fire.
   Fire Capt. H.B. Hadden said the fire was caused by smoking in
bed.
</TEXT>
