<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Park-Klansman     07-14 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Park-Klansman,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Names Park For Klan Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has voted
unanimously, including a black councilman, to name one of its city
parks in honor of former Mayor James R. Venable, a Ku Klux Klan
leader.
   Black councilman Robert Smith said he voted for the designation
because Venable had donated the land for the park and said the
attorney's Klan membership ``was not my concern.''
   But Coleman Seward, of the DeKalb County branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said he thought
the decision was ``awful.''
   Recreation director Barbara Holladay said Venable, a former
Imperial Wizard of the National Knights of the Ku Klux Klan,
donated the land to the city in the early 1970s. She said the
council voted Tuesday to name the park for Venable ``while we were
going through the master plan for parks and recreation.''
   Council members ``wanted to do it while he is still living,''
she said.
   ``We feel he should be recognized for giving the land to the
city,'' said Mayor Jane L. Rhodes.
   Gloria Brown, a black community leader, said that despite his
Klan activities, many black residents of the city think of Venable
as just another resident.
   ``Many black people have worked for him, and he has been very
good to them,'' she said.
</TEXT>
