<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--JellyfishInvasion     07-14 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Jellyfish Invasion,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jellyfish Invade Bahrain's Main Water Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hordes of jellyfish clogging the intake
pipes at this arid nation's main water distillation plant threaten
to jam the system.
   Two truckloads of the clear jellyfish are removed daily from the
pipes used to pump water from the sea into the plant for
desalination.
   ``There's a continuous number of jellyfish, and we have men
working round the clock'' to remove them, said Abdulla Juma,
director of electricity for the island nation in the Persian Gulf.
   So many jellyfish are heading into the plant, he said, that
officials fear shredded pieces of jellyfish could soon turn up in
the bathtubs and kitchen sinks of the plant's customers.
   The invasion, which baffles environmental experts, has yet to
affect production, Juma said.
</TEXT>
