<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Cancer-Award     07-14 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cancer-Award,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Germans, U.S.-Based Scientist Win Cancer Research Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swiss cancer research foundation on
Thursday awarded its annual $265,000 prize to two West Germans and
a U.S.-based Spanish scientist for their work in genetics.
   The Dr. Josef Steiner Foundation prize was shared by Mariano
Barbacid of the National Cancer Institute in Frederick, Md., and
Thomas Graf and Hartmut Beug of the European Laboratory for
Molecular Biology in Heidelberg.
   Barbacid helped identify the characteristics of the first known
human cancer gene and discovered that certain chemicals cause
cancer by mutating this gene, the foundation's announcement said.
   Graf and Beug were honored for work on the effect of two
cancer-causing genes on blood cells and bone marrow.
   Steiner, a Swiss farmer's son who became pharmacist, died of
diabetes in 1983 at age 94. He willed his $6.5 million fortune to
cancer research.
</TEXT>
