<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Kirk     07-14 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kirk,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Phones Jackson and Their Negotiations Proceed, Chairman
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk said today
that Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis had spoken within the last
24 hours, and that two campaigns were continuing to talk although
platform negotiations remain broken off.
   ``I know there has been a conversation between the two
candidates and several conversations between the two campaigns,''
Kirk said. ``So I think we'll be moving forward to make sure there
are continuing discussions and hopefully we'll be able to resolve
any differences on substantive matters.''
   A day earlier, Jackson's convention manager, Ron Brown,
disappointed over Dukakis' selection of Sen. Lloyd Bentsen for his
running mate and angered that Jackson learned of the selection from
the press, said the campaign had broken off talks over 13 still
disputed platform issues.
   Asked if there are ongoing talks about the platform, Kirk said:
``At this moment there are not. The effort between the two
campaigns is to assure there will be.''
   He said Dukakis called Jackson ``within the last 24 hours.''
   He said Dukakis wanted ``to make sure that any
misunderstandings'' about how Jackson was informed of the decision
were resolved. ``I think it's ... just one of those matters of
timing and certainly wasn't intended as a signal of disrespect or
insensitivity,'' the chairman said.
   Kirk said he spoke with Jackson to explain his own role in
introducing Dukakis and Bentsen and the press conference announcing
Bentsen's selection in Boston on Tuesday, when Kirk presented them
as the 1988 party ticket.
   ``I talked with Jackson about that myself and I said the numbers
were clear in terms of the presidential nomination, the choice had
been made with respect to the vice presidential nomination, that
the party was anxious to direct its attention and its effort
against the Republicans in November without in any way turning our
back on the important contribution Rev. Jackson has and will
continue to make to that effort.
   He cited ``the reality of the numbers'' and added, ``I think
it's important for me and my role to continue to keep the focus on
the November election. ... The quicker all of us can close ranks
and button up the unified Democratic Party, I think it's in the
greater interest of succeeding in the fall.''
   Kirk said Jackson listened and added, ``He might have had a
different point of view.''
   Kirk also announced the addition of four speakers to the
convention program: Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., on defense and national
security issues; Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., on keeping a Senate
majority; Gov. Gerald Baliles of Virginia, representing the
Democratic governors; and Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., on the role of
the presidency.
</TEXT>
