<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OilSpill     07-14 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Spill,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Docking Tanker Crashes, Spills Oil In Harbor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleanup crews today worked to
contain 630,000 gallons of crude oil spilled into the harbor when a
Singapore-owned tanker crashed into a mooring structure, the Coast
Guard said.
   Cleanup could take at least a week in what is believed to be the
worst spill in the port's history.
   The extent of any environmental damage was not immediately known.
   Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Dave Wilder said the Nord Pacific was
coming into dock when it struck a mooring spar late Wednesday. ``It
put an 8-foot by 1-foot gash in one of the cargo tanks about a foot
above the water line,'' Wilder said.
   Crews immediately placed oil containment booms alongside the
vessel, Wilder said.
   ``We've got vacuum trucks on scene removing the oil,'' he said.
``The wind is such that it's pushing it into the harbor and at this
point we're trying to contain it and get as much equipment on the
scene as soon as we can to remove it.''
   The Nord Pacific was en route to a refinery here when the
accident occurred.
