<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ShantytownArson     07-14 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shantytown Arson,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yale Alumnus Gets Probation In Shantytown Arson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yale alumnus charged with setting fire
to anti-apartheid shanties on the Ivy League campus was placed on
two year's probation today.
   Dr. Elwood Bracey, 52, of West Palm Beach, Fla., was not
required to admit guilty in receiving special probation under which
the charge will be dismissed and his arrest record erased if he
fulfills terms set by the judge.
   Bracey said the June 5 fire was not a racist act and that he set
the blaze because of the shanties' proximity to a war memorial. He
is a Vietnam veteran.
   ``I feel strongly about the war memorial at Yale,'' he told
Superior Court Judge Robert Reilly today. ``It was defamed by the
vulgar shanties.''
   Reilly ordered physician to pay $5,000 apiece to the Yale
Coalition Against Apartheid and the Fire Department for a video
camera and cellular telephone.
   Bracey was als required to pay Yale an unspecified sum for
damage caused by the fire and perform 400 hours of community and
medical service.
   Anti-apartheid activists had argued the crime was too serious to
justify special probation.
   ``It's just a way to whitewash the issue,'' Charlotte Hitchcock
of the Coalition Against Apartheid said before Wednesday's hearing.
   Bracey, who was at Yale for an alumni weekend the day of the
fire, was apprehended blocks away by another alumnus who said he
was jogging when he saw Bracey, dressed in a suit and tie, fleeing
the burning shanties.
   Bracey was charged with arson. He had been free on $50,000 bond
since his arrest.
   The shanties had stood for more than two years near the
university's administration building. The ramshackle array was
built by students to protest apartheid and Yale's investments in
companies doing business in South Africa.
   A 40-foot wooden memorial wall was erected June 16 to replace
the shanties.
   Assistant State's Attorney Burton A. Kaplan said the
prosecution, Yale and the Police and Fire departments took no
position on Bracey's application.
   ``It's one of those cases where it's up to the judge,'' Kaplan
said.
</TEXT>
