<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BabyAbduction 1stLd-Writethru a0538 07-14 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Abduction, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0538,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abducted Baby Found, FBI Arrests Woman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with details on kidnapping, woman's background,
hearing scheduled; CORRECTS Cabell-Huntington to Cabell Huntington
throughout. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newborn taken from her hospital crib
two days ago was back in her parents' arms today after FBI agents
arrested an Ohio woman on charges of kidnapping the child by posing
as a nurse, officials said.
   The woman, Linda Lou German, had called an abduction hotline and
insisted the child was hers, then came to the hospital with the
baby, a prosecutor said. German, 26, of Wheelersburg, Ohio, was
charged with a federal count of kidnapping, which carries a
sentence of up to life in prison, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Joseph Savage Jr.
   German, who has a 3{-year-old daughter, had ``endured some sort
of trauma'' and ``she wanted a baby of her own,'' said Janet
Ferguson, a spokesman at Cabell Huntington Hospital.
   Prosecutors said German will undergo a psychiatric examination.
   Arraignment scheduled for this morning was delayed without
explanation.
   Three-day-old Lindsey Manns was in good health at the hospital,
Ferguson said.
   Savage said German had called an abduction hotline at 9 p.m.
Wednesday, saying she had an infant and ``My relatives don't
believe it's mine.''
   German arrived at the hospital with the baby Wednesday night and
told FBI agents she had given birth in early July at a Lexington,
Ky., hospital, the prosecutor said.
   The FBI called the hospital, where there was no record of the
birth, and a doctor's exam determined she hadn't given birth
recently, he said.
   The infant was taken Tuesday from Cabell Huntington Hospital's
third-floor maternity ward. Officials said they believed the
kidnapper, wearing a nurse's uniform, carried the baby through the
front door.
   On Wednesday, Donald and Linda Manns had tearfully pleaded for
the return of their daughter.
   ``I'd just like to say, whoever's got it, please bring it
back,'' Donald Manns said. ``Just call and tell us it's all right.''
   The prosecutor said German was believed to have been involved in
an attempted abduction Sunday of another baby born at the same
hospital. No charges have been filed in that case, he said.
   In that case, a woman told state police that after she delivered
her baby at the hospital, she received a visit from a stranger who
told her she had recently lost a newborn baby.
   The mother told police that the woman showed up at her home in
Mingo County with a gift for the baby.
   Once inside, police were told, the woman was allowed to hold the
baby, then brandished a knife and threatened to take the infant.
State police said the intruder fled when another person walked into
the room.
   ``We suspect a connection between the two incidents because of
the time frame and the fact that both incidents involve babies born
at the same hospital,'' said Sgt. F.H. Butler.
</TEXT>
