<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WeaponsCarrierTheft     07-14 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weapons Carrier Theft,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Crashes Army Weapons Carrier Into Capitol Barrier Following
Chase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man driving a weapons carrier believed
stolen from an Army National Guard Armory led police on a chase
through the District of Columbia before crashing into a cement
barrier outside the U.S. Capitol early Thursday, officials said.
   ``The vehicle wasn't armed,'' said Walt Ferguson, a spokesman
for the Metropolitan Police Department. ``But it's capable of
carrying missiles and automatic weapons.''
   The camouflage-colored vehicle was discovered missing at about
6:30 a.m. EDT from the Maryland Army National Guard's Armory
Compound in Annapolis, according to Lt. Col. Howard Freedlander, a
spokesman for the National Guard.
   The thief broke the lock on the fence gate, then broke into the
vehicle, which starts with a switch instead of a key, Freedlander
said.
   ``It's an odd-looking vehicle,'' Freedlander said. ``If you saw
it on the road, it would really stand out.''
   Despite that, the driver managed to drive 50 miles from
Annapolis into the District of Columbia before police officers
spotted the vehicle about 2:30 a.m. and gave chase.
   The driver led officers at high speeds through the city,
striking two cruisers before plowing into a large stone barricade
at the north entrance to the Capitol. Police apprehended Dadailies
Ditgilvanni, 18, of Chestertown, Md., at the scene.
   The stolen vehicle, known in the military as a HMMWV, is a
light, highly mobile, four-wheel drive vehicle. A relatively new
vehicle that replaced the standard Army jeep, it can travel at
speeds up to 70 mph.
   The stolen HMMWV contained a missile carrier but no missiles or
weapons, Freedlander said.
   The Annapolis compound is surrounded by a chain-link fence, but
does not have a 24-hour security system. The vehicles are stored
there for training purposes.
   Ditgilvanni was charged with two counts of assault on a police
officer and one count of unauthorized use of a vehicle. He was
hospitalized with minor injuries which police said he suffered
during the chase, Ferguson said. No police officers were injured.
   The reason for the vehicle's theft and its trip to Washington
were not known.
</TEXT>
