<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Plans     07-14 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Plans,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese to Join Heritage Foundation, Hoover Institution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Departing Attorney General Edwin Meese III
will join the Heritage Foundation next month to write and lecture
on issues ranging from drugs to the Constitution, the conservative
Washington research center said Thursday.
   Meese, the subject of a just-completed 14-month criminal
investigation, said he looks forward ``to a more reflective period,
without the white heat and daily pressures'' of government work
when he joins the Heritage Foundation as a ``Distinguished Fellow.''
   Meese also will be a ``Distinguished Visiting Fellow'' at the
Hoover Institution at Stanford University in Palo Alto, Calif., the
Justice Department said.
   Heritage Foundation President Edward Feulner called Meese ``one
of the conservative movement's most valuable resources.''
   Hoover Institution President Glenn Campbell said it will be
``very good to have Mr. Meese in our coffee room, so that scholars
learn that translating their ideas into policy and programs isn't
quite as simple as they think it is.''
   At the Heritage Foundation, Executive Vice President Phil
Truluck said ``Ed Meese more than anyone is symbolic of the ideas
of the Reagan revolution and we're pleased that he's come to
Heritage to continue to fight for those ideas.''
   In articles, lectures and round-table discussions, Meese will
address questions concerning drugs, criminal justice and the
Constitution, but will delve into other areas in view of his broad
experience as head of the Reagan administration's Domestic Policy
Council, said Truluck.
   Meese was counselor to President Reagan from 1981 to 1985 before
becoming attorney general. Truluck said Meese's articles will be
printed in Heritage publications and placed in other journals.
   The Heritage Foundation and the Hoover Institution have hosted
several former Reagan administration officials.
   Secretary of State George Shultz has already agreed to join the
Hoover Institution staff after he leaves office.
   Meese announced July 5 that he would leave the administration by
next month. He said he had been vindicated in a criminal probe of
his activities because independent counsel James McKay had decided
not to seek his indictment.
   McKay filed an 830-page report that is to be made public
shortly. It was referred last week to Solicitor General Charles
Fried, a step that could lead to an ethics review of Meese by the
Justice Department's Office of Professional Responsibility.
   Meese has worked for Reagan longer than any other aide, joining
him when Reagan was elected governor of California in 1966 and
working as a senior staff member until 1974.
   He taught at the University of California School of Law in
Berkeley from 1965 to 1967 and was director of the center for
criminal justice policy and management at the University of San
Diego from 1977 to 1981.
   Meanwhile Thursday, Richard Thornburgh, President Reagan's
nominee to become attorney general, said he will soon talk to top
Justice Department officials about improving morale following
Meese's departure.
   ``I want to take a very careful look at what the level of
commitment and what the level of morale is within the department,''
Thornburgh said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' program.
   ``I hope within the next week or so to begin some conversations
with key people in the department so I can make that assessment (of
morale) and we can deal with whatever problems exist there,'' said
Thornburgh, who was interviewed from Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
