<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0567,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Acknowledges He And Bentsen Disagree On Some Issues</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 11 grafs new with Dukakis telephoning Jackson, Kirk
comments; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng, `Dukakis and Bentsen.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis telephoned Jesse Jackson in an
attempt to improve their strained relations, according to the
Democratic Party chairman, who today predicted a resolution of
differences that threatened to disrupt the national convention next
week.
   Dukakis' plans for a show of unity have been clouded by
Jackson's hints that he might challenge the selection of Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas for the No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   The Massachusetts governor phoned Jackson ``within the last 24
hours'' to ensure that any misunderstandings about how Jackson was
informed of Bentsen's selection were resolved, said Paul Kirk,
Democratic National Committee chairman. Jackson first learned of
the selection from reporters, not Dukakis.
   ``I think it's ... just one of those matters of timing and
certainly wasn't intended as a signal of disrespect or
insensitivity,'' the chairman said.
   Jackson hinted Wednesday that he might challenge Dukakis'
selection of Bentsen at the convention.
   Asked in Chicago if there would be a floor fight next Thursday
when the convention is asked to ratify Dukakis' choice, Jackson
said, ``I'm not suggesting that I will compete for a place on the
ticket, but the floor is wide open on Thursday night when the
recommendation is made.''
   Informed of Jackson's comments, Dukakis said, ``I'm confident
we'll have a united convention.''
   Kirk acknowledged that negotiations on the platform are still
stalled, and he said he had personally talked to Jackson to explain
his role in the Tuesday announcement of Bentsen as Dukakis's
running mate.
   Despite the problems, the party chairman said, ``I think we'll
be moving forward to make sure there are continuing discussions and
hopefully we'll be able to resolve any differences on substantive
matters.''
   On Wednesday, Dukakis, drawing an obvious contrast to Republican
rival George Bush's service in the Reagan administration, says he
would expect his vice president to ``challenge me'' and spell out
differences on issues and policies.
   At a Capitol Hill news conference, Dukakis and Bentsen
acknowledged they differ on some issues but insisted they were in
broad agreement on job creation, education, fair housing and health
care.
   Dukakis and Bentsen met with reporters after a day of joint
appearances in the nation's capital during which they tried to
dampen discontent among blacks angry over the fact that Jackson
received no advance notice of the selection of Bentsen.
   After a fund-raiser at the Georgetown home of Pamela Harriman,
Dukakis returned to Boston and the struggle to find about $100
million in cuts to bring his state budget into balance.
   His state budget problems are a potential embarrassment to
Dukakis as he prepares to accept the Democratic presidential
nomination at the party's national convention next week in Atlanta.
   His abilities as a manager and the robust economy of his state
have been cornerstones of Dukakis' campaign to convince voters he
is the most qualified presidential candidate.
   Dukakis and Bentsen were asked repeatedly about their
differences on such questions as abortion, school prayer, Contra
aid and the 1981 tax cuts proposed by President Reagan.
   ``As long he's a U.S. senator from Texas, he's going to vote his
conscience,'' said the Massachusetts governor.
   Then he added, ``If we are elected in November, then obviously
the relationship will change.''
   Bentsen had no argument with that assessment.
   ``As vice president of the United States, I would give him the
very best counsel I could when I agreed or disagreed on the
issues,'' said the Texas senator. ``But there's only one president
of the United States and he's the man that bears the ultimate
responsibility and pays the ultimate price.''
   Dukakis said, ``One of the reasons I picked Lloyd Bentsen is
because I know he will challenge me as vice president.''
   The Massachusetts governor also seemed determined to contrast
what he would expect from a vice president to the perception that
Bush often has played a passive role in that office _ at least so
far as can be gleaned from the public record.
   Bush told reporters in California last spring, ``I hold back
speaking in meetings because I don't want the president tohave to
be choosing between his vice president and the other members of the
Cabinet. And I hold back sometimes because I worry about leaks.''
   The prospective Democratic ticket got a cool reception during a
joint appearance at the annual convention of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, but Dukakis
said, ``I thought it was terrific.''
   ``I understand there were a great many people in that room who
are actively involved in the Jackson candidacy, who cared very
deeply about it and are disappointed he didn't win,'' he said.
   The reception was no different than a Greek-American group would
give Jackson if he appeared before them after defeating Dukakis in
a race for the nomination, he said.
</TEXT>
