<HEAD>Gastroenteritis And Cholera Kill 14 In New Delhi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gastroenteritis and cholera have claimed
14 lives in the capital over the past four days, a city official
said Thursday.
   Heavy monsoon rains began recently, and most of the deaths have
occurred in the eastern suburbs of New Delhi on the banks of the
Yamuna river. Many of the neighborhoods do not have proper
sanitation facilities.
   Four children were among the victims of gastroenteritis that has
spread in some camps run by the government for the poor people.
   The official of the Municipal Corporation of New Delhi, speaking
on condition of anonymity, said seven of the 14 people had died of
cholera.
   Water-borne diseases are spreading in areas with inadequate
sanitation, he said. Some water lines were reportedly contaminated
by sewage.
