<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-Columbus,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan To Build Replica Of Santa Maria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan will build a replica of Christopher
Columbus's ship, the Santa Maria, and sail it from Spain to Japan
in 1992 to mark the 500th anniversary of the explorer's discovery
of America, an official said Thursday.
   Akihiko Osugi, an official at Kadokawa Publishing Co., said the
plan was announced Wednesday by company president Haruki Kadokawa,
who is chairman of the organizing committee.
   Osugi said that at the suggestion of Eikichi Hayashiya, a former
Japanese ambassador to Spain, Kadokawa and other businessmen,
politicians and scholars decided to fulfill Columbus' dream of
sailing from Spain to Japan.
   He said Japanese technicians will build a replica of the
three-mast Santa Maria, used by Columbus when he discovered
American in 1492. The replica, to be built in Barcelona, Spain,
will cost $9.85 million, he said.
