<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Newborn-Airliner 1stLd-Writethru a0505 07-14 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newborn-Airliner, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0505,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Gives Birth, Then Abandons Baby on Plane</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with woman surrendering. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman suspected of giving birth in an
airline bathroom and stuffing the infant under the sink was
arrested this morning for investigation of attempted murder.
   Christina Locasto, 24, of New York City turned herself in to San
Mateo County Sheriff's deputies in Redwood City and was jailed on
$50,000 bail, said Lt. Mike Dow.
   A United Airlines cleaning crew found the infant in a
blood-spattered bathroom about 20 minutes after Flight 35 from
Newark, N.J., landed at San Francisco International Airport on
Wednesday, authorities said.
   ``The cleaning crew heard the baby crying, and that was what led
them to the baby,'' said Rob Doughty, an airline spokesman in
Chicago.
   Minutes earlier, the mother had disappeared among the 252 other
passengers who had disembarked after the non-stop flight. The baby
apparently had been born five hours earlier, before the plane took
off, Dow said.
   ``She had the baby and she stuffed it under the sink. That's
attempted murder,'' Dow said.
   The baby was listed in good condition at Mills Memorial Hospital
in San Mateo, where nurses named the 8-pound, 9-ounce girl
Elizabeth. The brown-haired, blue-eyed infant is ``just
beautiful,'' said spokeswoman Traci Ward.
   Locasto's husband, Louis, 26, who traveled with her and their
3-year-old daughter on the flight from New Jersey, was not
arrested. ``We have reason to believe at this time he didn't know
she was pregnant,'' Dow said.
   Detectives traced Locasto through the passenger list and
contacted the couple's relatives on the East Coast, who contacted
relatives the Locastos were visiting in Los Altos, Dow said. The
couple had planned to go to Disneyland, he said.
   After a series of telephone calls, Mrs. Locasto turned herself
in, accompanied by a lawyer, Dow said.
   Dow said flight attendants told him a woman had asked to use the
bathroom as the flight prepared to leave. The plane was delayed 30
minutes as attendants pounded on the door, urging her to come out
so the plane could take off, he said.
</TEXT>
