<DOCNO> AP880714-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ReaganVisit 1stLd-Writethru a0520 07-14 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan Visit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0520,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Visit To Drought Area Clouded By Rain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Reagan visit to farm;
PICKS UP 13th graf pvs, `Corn stalks ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Drought, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DU QUOIN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's nothing like a presidential visit
into drought-ravaged territory to get the rains falling again _ at
least in the eyes of farmer Herman Krone.
   ``It just tickles me to death,'' said Krone, who today hosted
President Reagan at his 2,800-acre farm in Southern Illinois. ``If
he (Reagan) can make it rain, he's done enough for me.''
   Reagan walked through corn and soybean fields on the farm,
towering over the corn, normally 8 feet high by now but today less
than half that height. Soybean plants were a quarter of their
expected size.
   ``What I saw was not a pretty sight,'' Reagan said.
   The nearly 2 inches of rain recorded on Krone's farm this week
is turning once-parched fields into muddy pastures. And 25 miles
away in Marion, motorists have been driving through flooded
downtown streets.
   ``Four or five days ago, my corn looked like pineapples ...
leaves dying,'' the 63-year-old Krone, a Reagan admirer, said
Wednesday.
   Until Monday's rain _ sporadic showers have soaked the area
since _ ``the grass would just crack under your feet,'' he said.
   ``The grass is starting to come back, and if I can get some
continued rain, I could get some recovery on my pastures.''
   Today's forecast called for mostly sunny skies, hot and humid
conditions with highs in the 90s.
   Agriculture experts, however, insist that recent rain _ up to 4
inches over some of the flatland region _ won't help much of the
already damaged corn crop.
   But the president's visit, they say, is a good gesture on
Reagan's part and should help get federal aid for farmers who have
substantial crop loss.
   ``Myself, I'm not looking for a handout,'' said Krone, who added
that he doesn't receive any federal subsidies. ``I can survive if
there's no rain and it (the drought) continues.''
   Even so, at the Krone farm Reagan saw some 400 acres of a
1,200-acre corn crop that is irreversibly damaged by drought, an
estimated $35,000 loss.
   Corn stalks that should be 10- to 12-feet high by this time of
year only measure from 2- to 5-feet with burnt, brownish tassels,
the farmer said.
   The dry spell also has parched 125 acres of pasture used to feed
Krone's 150 head of cattle. For the past month, he's had to feed
the cattle alfalfa hay.
   ``My farm will be a good representation of the drought, although
it has rained here,'' said Krone, dressed in a blue-and-beige
``Agratech'' cap, a gray T-shirt, faded blue jeans and leather work
boots.
   Reagan was scheduled for stops in Moline, Ill., and neighboring
Davenport, Iowa, before returning to Washington, D.C..
   ``Even though it has rained, when the president looks at the
crops, he's going to see a bad situation,'' said Steve Newman of
the Illinois Farm Bureau. ``There's nothing like looking at the
problem square in the face and making some decisions.''
   Bob Spitze, professor of agriculture economics at the University
of Illinois, said the Reagan visit adds support to a $5.5 billion
relief-drought package under consideration by Congress.
   ``Now that the administration has said, `The condition has
worsened enough, it is a major catastrophe and we need
legislation,' it legitimizes the relief-drought package which has
already been developed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
