<DOCNO> AP880714-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialPoll     07-14 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Poll,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On Issues and Core Support, Poll Finds a Close Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the presidential race begins in earnest,
nearly 60 percent of the Americans who plan to vote say they
already have decided whom to support, a Media General-Associated
Press poll has found.
   A third of the remainder are strongly leaning to Vice President
George Bush or Gov. Michael Dukakis, leaving just 23 percent of
voters as the undecided group that is likely to decide the
election, the poll found.
   Among those who said they have decided on a candidate, 48
percent in the national survey of 1,223 adults backed Dukakis and
42 percent supported Bush. The race was a dead heat among the
strong leaners.
   The remaining undecided group was dominated by voters of the
middle ground: half were self-described moderates and nearly half
said they were independents.
   There was no clear sign where those voters might go. While
Dukakis led among moderates and independents who have decided
already, the race was closer for the moderates and independents who
were leaning strongly.
   Other national polls have sought to measure the candidates'
standings among all registered voters, a broader gauge that also
has showed a close contest. A CBS News-New York Times poll Monday
had it 47-39 for Dukakis.
   The Media General-AP poll, with a 3 point margin of error
overall, was conducted by telephone June 22 to July 2 among 1,223
randomly selected adults. It was completed before Dukakis named
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas as his running mate Tuesday.
   Another finding of the poll countered the suggestion that voters
place great value on a exciting style that is lacking in Dukakis
and Bentsen, and in Bush on the Republican side. Only 5 percent
said they value a candidate's personal style over his position on
the issues, while 79 percent said issues were more important.
Twelve percent said the two were equally important.
   The survey found a virtual tossup in perceptions of the
political parties' abilities to handle key issues _ a common
measure of voter leanings at this stage of the race. The result
emphasized the closeness of the race: In the most frequently cited
economic and social issues, the deficit and drugs, the parties were
rated equally.
   Respondents were asked, regardless of whether or how they may
vote, which party was best able to deal with important issues. On
economic matters, 34 percent said the federal deficit was
paramount, and they were evenly split on which party can best
handle the deficit: 34 percent said the Republicans, 31 percent
said the Democrats. The rest had no opinion.
   The Democrats were favored strongly on unemployment, the next
most-often cited economic issue of six that were offered.
Twenty-eight percent said unemployment was most important, and
nearly half said Democrats were best able to handle it. Fewer than
a fifth picked the Republicans.
   Inflation was rated third as the key economic issue, cited by 13
percent, and again the parties were ranked equally in their ability
to handle it. Dealing with foreign trade, rated fourth, went to the
Republicans, 42-32.
   On social issues, more than a third of respondents said illegal
drugs were the most important of six choices, and nearly a fifth
each cited poverty and AIDS. The parties ranked evenly on handling
drugs, but Democrats were rated far better on poverty, 51-17
percent, and better on AIDS, 33-20 percent.
   Republicans were rated better, 40-24, on dealing with crime, the
next most-cited social issue. Democrats did better on handling the
last two issues _ the environment, 49-20, and civil rights, 56-12.
   On foreign affairs, a fifth of respondents said U.S.-Soviet
relations was the key issue, a fifth said it was the spread of
nuclear weapons and nearly a fifth said it was unrest in the Middle
East.
   Republicans were judged better able than the Democrats to handle
the Soviets, 44-32, and Middle East unrest, 38-29. The parties were
rated about evenly on their ability to deal with nuclear
proliferation.
   Unrest in Central America and the Third World debt were ranked
lower in importance; the Republicans scored better at handling
Central America, 44-33, while the parties were rated evenly on
dealing with the debt crisis.
   For the respondents who said they planned to vote, economic
issues in general were the most important, cited by 55 percent.
Just 13 percent said social issues were the most important, and 10
percent said foreign affairs; 21 percent volunteered that the three
were equally important.
   The Media General-AP poll consisted of telephone interviews June
22-July 2 with a randomly selected sample of 1,223 adults across
the nation. Media General Inc., a communications company based in
Richmond, Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond
News Leader, the Tampa (Fla). Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in
Charleston, S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
