<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrossingDeath     07-14 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crossing Death,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Who Hit Children Was `Teaching Passengers a Lesson'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing two children
when he drove through a school crossing at at least 50 mph was
speeding to ``teach his passengers a lesson'' for making him late
to work, investigators say.
   Michael D. Brandon, 21, who had no driver's license, failed to
stop even when a police officer stood in his path and aimed his gun
at him, police said.
   Two other children, including a 12-year-old crossing guard in
plastic hat and vest, were injured Tuesday when the car struck them
as they walked in front of Hawthorne Elementary School.
   Brandon had been speeding ``to teach his passengers a lesson for
making him late to work'' at his job as a janitor, investigators
said Wednesday.
   He was held without bail for investigation of two counts of
murder, two of assault with a deadly weapon and one of assault with
a deadly weapon _ the car _ on a police officer.
   Police said Brandon's vehicle was going at least 50 mph when it
swerved around a car stopped in front of the crosswalk.
   An Alameda police officer, in Oakland to make an unrelated
arrest, tried to stop the car by standing in its way, revolver
drawn, but the car didn't slow, and the officer couldn't shoot
because of the crowd of children, police said.
   He leaped aside at the last moment, said to Lt. Jim Hahn.
   The car was found two miles away and a witness led police to
Brandon's home nearby. Brandon's two passengers came forward on
their own and face no charges.
   Brandon told police he fled because ``he just didn't want to be
there because it was such a mess,'' officers said.
   The accident killed 10-year-old Rene Zuniga, and his cousin,
8-year-old Carlita Rosales. Carlita's sister, 6-year-old Angela
Rosales, was in good condition at Children's Hospital with a
concussion and fractured leg.
   The crossing guard, Maglia Dominguez, suffered a broken collar
bone. She was released from Kaiser Hospital on Wednesday.
   ``It was going fast, fast,'' she told The (Oakland) Tribune. ``I
saw it hit the kids. They bent like this,'' she said, bending
forward at the waist. ``Then the car hit me, but I don't remember
hitting the street.''
</TEXT>
