<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GM-AutoSafety     07-14 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Auto Safety,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Introducing New Safety Steering Wheel on 1989 Cavalier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILFORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economy-car buyers will be the first to
benefit from a less expensive safety innovation developed by
General Motors Corp. _ a steering wheel that flattens itself
against the driver's torso in an accident.
   GM President Robert Stempel said Wednesday that GM is
introducing its new self-aligning steering wheel on the 1989
Chevrolet Cavalier. The device will be phased in later on other
cars not equipped with more expensive airbags.
   The wheel is a hollow hub on six metal tabs that collapse on
impact, distributing the force evenly and reducing the potential
for head and chest injuries, the automaker said.
   Most cars equipped with airbags have tended to be more expensive
models because economy car buyers are less willing to pay the cost
of an airbag, Stempel said.
   Spokeswoman Jane Mott said today GM would not divulge how much
the steering wheels or airbags would add to the cost.
   Automakers are required by the federal government to have
passive restraints _ either driver-side airbags in addition to
manual shoulder-lap belts or automatic shoulder belts _ by 1990.
   GM, the nation's No. 1 automaker, will include driver-side
airbags as standard equipment on 500,000 middle- and upper-range
cars a year by 1990, Stempel said.
   Stempel said GM won't begin including passenger-side airbags as
standard equipment until 1992 because the technology is still being
developed.
   He said passenger-side airbags are harder to position because
passengers tend to sit in a variety of postures, especially in
larger cars.
</TEXT>
