<DOCNO> AP880714-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Northeast Bjt   07-14 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Northeast, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Signs of Drought in Northeast: Short Corn, Brown Lawns, Low Rivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Watering the lawn in Plymouth can mean a ticket.
Boaters on Pennsylvania's Allegheny River are warned to watch out
for underwater hazards in increasingly shallow water. Egg farmers
are selling birds for slaughter because of rising feed prices.
   The Northeast is suffering through a dry spell that compares in
some spots to the Midwestern drought.
   ``Peas have essentially been taken off the market,'' said Don
Geise, a field man at Furman's, a Northumberland County, Pa., farm
where nearly 85 percent of the pea crop was stunted by the drought.
   Pennsylvania drought damage has approached the level of the
parched Midwest: 95 percent of its farmers report inadequate soil
moisture, 86 percent of pasture land is below average, 23 percent
of the soybean crop is rated poor or very poor.
   Pennsylvania issued a drought watch this month calling for a
voluntary 5 percent reduction in water consumption. Rainfall in the
Philadelphia area _ where the temperature has hit 100 degrees three
times already _ is about 7 inches off the average for this time of
year of 20.55 inches.
   Farmers in western Massachusetts report up to 75 percent losses
of peas and 25 percent failures of green peppers. All five acres of
one grower's eggplant crop were destroyed and another lost his
small carrot crop.
   What's a farmer to do?
   ``I don't know _ keep irrigating and hope, pray,'' said Scott
Danner, sales coordinator for the Pioneer Valley Growers
Association in Whately, Mass., a 66-farm cooperative.
   The Midwestern drought has raised the price of poultry feed in
the Northeast by 30 percent.
   ``Feed has been as high as I've ever seen it and I've been in
business 35 years,'' said John Ricca, president of Westminster Egg
Farms in Westminster, Mass., whose 560,000 birds lay about 200,000
dozen eggs a week.
   The price of a ton of feed _ made of soybean and corn, two
hard-hit Midwestern crops _ that cost $130 last year now sells for
$200. Ricca said he has begun selling birds for slaughter earlier
than normal to reduce production.
   In the driest summer in Connecticut since 1910, about 600 acres
of state woodland have burned in the past week. Gov. William A.
O'Neill banned open fires in or within 100 yards of brush, forests
or grass fields _ the state's first such summer ban.
   More than 5,000 acres of forest have burned in the Palisades
Interstate Park complex in New York and New Jersey, according to
the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation,
closing down more than 350 miles of trails.
   Corn plants in Connecticut are about three feet shorter than
normal, said David T. Schreiber, executive director of the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's stabilization and conservation service
in Windsor, Conn. State officials have received reports of dried
out pumpkins, small tomatoes and hard fruit.
   Just 0.77 inches of rain has fallen since July 1 in
Massachusetts, far below the monthly average of 3.94 inches. The
water level in the state's main reservoir has fallen 13 feet below
normal, leaving the state supply at 76 percent of capacity.
   In Plymouth _ one of 31 Massachusetts communities to declare
water emergencies _ officials have handed out 150 citations to
people who have ignored lawn watering restrictions. A handful of
second offenders have been fined $25.
   ``We're trying our damnedest to make these people understand the
seriousness of the problem,'' said Leighton Peck, public works
director in the town of 45,000.
   But compared to other sections on the country, Northeast growers
remain sanguine.
   ``It's hard to say `drought' when you look at the Midwest
crops,'' said Danner of the Massachusetts cooperative. ``It all
comes down to what you consider a drought. I'd say we're in a
severe water shortage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
