<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Doctor-Death     07-14 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctor-Death,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Dies During Surgery; Leaves Rural Area Without OB Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNION SPRINGS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two poor, rural counties with some of
the nation's highest infant mortality rates have no one to deliver
babies after their only obstetrician-gynecologist died while
performing surgery.
   The death of Dr. Robert X. Williams has forced the only public
hospital in Bullock and Macon counties to refer women in labor to
Montgomery hospitals 40 miles away, the administrator of Bullock
County Hospital, Duane Brookhart, said Thursday.
   ``The loss of a physician is going to reduce access to health
care, particularly for the poor who can't afford to travel long
distances for medical care,'' said Jim McVay, spokesman for the
state Department of Public Health.
   At least 27 of Alabama's 67 counties are without a hospital
providing obstetrical services, according to the Alabama Hospital
Association.
   Williams, 54, collapsed with a massive heart attack and was
pronounced dead in the operating room at the hospital in Union
Springs on Wednesday morning, officials said.
   He had nearly completed a hysterectomy when he died. St.
Margaret's Hospital in Montgomery used its emergency helicopter to
fly Dr. Judi Jehle to Union Springs to complete the surgery, which
was done without complications, hospital spokeswoman Cathy Ellis
said Thursday.
   ``The patient was given a spinal (anesthesia) and she was awake
during the entire thing,'' Ms. Jehle said. ``When I got there ...
she seemed pretty calm, but she watched the whole thing.''
   Because of Williams' death, ``we have had to cease OB
delivery,'' the hospital adminsitrator said.
   Williams was the only obstetrician in the two-county area and
delivered 30 to 50 babies a month. He had delivered several babies
Tuesday, ``and I could tell from his on-call room he had been at
the hospital all night,'' Ms. Jehle said. ``When I left, one of the
nurses shook her head and said, `He worked himself to death.'''
   Ms. Jehle said it was ironic she was called in to complete the
surgery because she recently decided to give up the obstetrical
part of her partice because of the long hours. She said Williams
had been scheduled to leave on a cruise this weekend to celebrate
his 32nd anniversary.
   A family physician in Macon County, Arvind Patel, also has been
delivering babies at Bullock County Hospital, but he can't because
there is no longer a surgeon on call in case a Caesarean section is
needed, Brookhart said.
   When Williams' died, two women were at the hospital in labor,
but they were transferred by ambulance to Montgomery, where they
delivered. No women had been transferred Thursday, Brookhart said.
   The hospital administrator said he already is working to recruit
another physician.
   ``This is a relatively poor area. A lot of the patients are
Medicaid and uninsured. With all the other liabilities an
obstetrician faces, it is hard to recruit,'' he said.
   In 1986, Alabama had the highest infant mortality rate of any
state, with 13.3 out of every 1,000 babies dying before their first
birthday. In 1987, it dropped to 12.2, but complete national
statistics are not yet available for comparison.
   McVay said Bullock and Macon counties ``have traditionally had
one of the highest levels of infant mortality in the state.''
   Bullock County's rate was 26.2 in 1986 and 5.1 in 1987, although
that figure was skewed by a small number of births. Macon County's
rate was 12.6 in 1986 and 15.9 in 1987, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GEBuilding     07-14 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GE Building,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockefeller Center's RCA Building to be Rechristened GE Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The landmark RCA Building _ a 70-story art deco
tower at the heart of Rockefeller Center _ is being renamed the GE
Building after the company that bought RCA and its network TV
division, NBC, two years ago.
   NBC President Robert Wright announced the decision in a memo to
employees Wednesday.
   ``It seems sort of the obvious evolution of things,'' said NBC
spokeswoman Betty Hudson.
   The RCA Building is a popular tourist spot for its swank Rainbow
Room restaurant, observation deck and NBC studios, where ``The
Today Show,'' ``Saturday Night Live,'' and ``Late Night With David
Letterman'' are taped.
   The building is owned by Rockefeller Center, but General
Electric has the right to change the name it's had for more than
five decades.
   Five blocks away is another landmark known as the General
Electric Building. It was once known as the RCA Victor Building
before GE moved in in 1933.
</TEXT>
