<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildShot     07-14 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Shot,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect Free on Bail in Shooting of Paralyzed 6-year-old</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 6-year-old boy told his father he wanted a
skateboard as his reward for surviving a stray bullet, fired in
what police believe was a drug-related shooting.
   But Ralph Brooks Jr. may never walk again, let alone ride a
skateboard, due to the .45-caliber slug now lodged just below his
heart, doctors said Thursday.
   John Templeton, pediatric surgeon at The Children's Hospital of
Philadelphia, said the bullet passed through the boy's spine before
stopping half an inch from his heart. He is paralyzed from the
waist down.
   Doctors who praised the boy's stamina said they would not remove
the bullet unless complications developed because of the risks
related to surgery that close to the heart.
   Police said the child apparently was caught in the cross-fire of
a shootout Tuesday that may have been part of a feud between drug
dealers.
   Police said witnesses told them Lonnie Summers, 21, fired
several shots at a passing car and one of them hit the boy. Summers
was arrested on charges of aggravated and simple assault,
recklessly endangering another person and violating the uniform
firearms act, police said.
   He was arraigned Wednesday and released on $10,000 bail,
officials said.
   Ralph was playing with one of his two sisters when the shooting
occurred.
   ``They shoot out there every day, two or three times a day,''
said Lula Carr, a 30-year-resident of the south Philadelphia
neighborhood. ``You stay in your house and you just try not to get
involved.''
   Bernadine Collins rushed outside when shots rang out Tuesday, to
where her children and grandchildren had been sitting, 20 yards
from Ralph.
   ``It's just another repeat of what happens all the time,'' she
said. ``It's not going to stop ... and this was only a ... baby. I
never knew a bullet could travel so far.''
   The boy's parents, Kimberly and Ralph Sr., said they held little
hope that their son's shooting would stop the drug dealers or
drug-related violence.
   ``This has happened so many times,'' Brooks said. ``I don't
think they feel like we feel.''
   The Philadelphia Daily News has established a trust fund to help
finance Ralph's education.
</TEXT>
