<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reunion     07-14 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reunion,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Reunited 13 Years After Saigon's Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 13 years of tearful prayers, two
Vietnamese sisters were reunited with their parents and six
siblings, who worked side by side in a small restaurant to buy the
girls' freedom.
   ``Our great dream has come true,'' a beaming Nguyen Van Trieu,
54, said Thursday at the family's restaurant, Kim's Coffee Shop.
   Van Trieu and his wife, Thi Khanh, last saw the two girls,
My-Chi, 20, and My-Hanh, 15, in Saigon on April 30, 1975, the day
the South Vieefore I die.' He's granted that, that's for
sure,'' he said.
   Tired from their journey, the daughters smiled shyly and
repeated the word ``happy'' as their parents detailed the family's
exodus.
   The couple fled with their oldest child, Kymberly, now 26,
leaving two sons and four daughters behind.
   Van Trieu, a military officer in South Vietnam, fled with
thousands of others from his country to avoid punishment from the
communists.
   The three were taken to a refugee camp in Arkansas, where they
spent several months learning English and waiting for an American
sponsor. In the fall of 1975, they were befriended by a church in
Memphis, Tenn., and, refusing welfare, worked at various odd jobs.
   The family sent thousands of dollars to Vietnam to pay bribes
and buy transportation for their children's freedom. Two daughters
and a son were allowed to leave Vietnam in 1980, and two years
later, another son was released.
   In 1982, the Nguyens opened their restaurant with $20,000
borrowed from friends. Living in an adjoining house, the entire
family worked without pay, preparing meals, waiting on tables and
washing dishes, as they continued sending money to Vietnam for the
release of the two remaining children.
   Except for letters and a few snapshots, the family had had no
contact with My-Chi and My-Hanh, who lived with their 87-year-old
maternal grandmother.
   It wasn't until June that the family learned permission had been
granted for My-Chi and My-Hanh to leave.
   ``We had hope,'' My-Chi said in Vietnamese. ``We're sleeping
here, but we still think we're in Vietnam.''
   The grandmother was supposed to come too, but at the last minute
decided she wanted to die in her homeland, Van Trieu said.
   Fearing last-minute complications, Van Trieu refused to believe
his daughters were free until he greeted them at Greater Pittsburgh
International Airport on Wednesday night, nine days after they left
Saigon, now known as Ho Chi Minh City. There had been no official
confirmation from the Vietnamese government that the two had been
allowed to leave as scheduled July 4.
   The Nguyens immediately recognized My-Chi and My-Hanh, who were
7 and 2 when the family was separated. The girls knew their parents
through photographs, but they had never before met their youngest
sister, Beatrice Ann, 12, who was born in the United States.
   ``We get along real good,'' Kymberly said. ``We thought there
would be a lot of differences and stuff like that. But it just
seems like old times.''
   The family celebrated with a party at their restaurant for
family and friends that continued into the morning. On Thursday,
Thi Khanh took her daughters shopping for clothes and on a tour of
their new hometown.
   Both girls plan to earn high school diplomas while, of course,
helping at the restaurant.
   ``We have a lot of blessings,'' Van Trieu said. ``All my family
is here. That's not a dream. That's a blessing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
