</TEXT>
<HEAD>Exotic Dancing, and Without Fear of Official Interference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nude dancing will be one of Atlanta's attractions
that visiting Democrats may choose to experience next week, without
fear of official interference.
   Chances that Atlanta's nude dancing clubs might have to shut
down prior to the Democratic National Convention fizzled Wednesday
when a judge delayed until next month a second round of hearings on
the constitutionality of a new state law banning the sale of
alcohol in such clubs.
   Fulton County Superior Court Judge Isaac Jenrette scheduled an
evidentiary hearing for Aug. 12 on The Gold Club's challenge to the
law. A temporary restraining order issued June 30 will continue to
bar enforcement of the law until Jenrette issues his ruling.
   The challenge now goes to Jenrette rather than directly to the
Georgia Supreme Court because Judge Luther Alverson, who issued the
temporary restraining order as presiding judge for the week,
refused to grant the state's request for a certificate of immediate
review.
   Alverson, who blocked enforcement of the law with an opinion
that it violated the state Constitution, later modified his ruling
to stress that it was temporary after lawyers from the attorney
general's office complained that they had not been given an
opportunity to offer evidence and examine witnesses.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Third Party Candidate Says City Hid Its Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third-party presidential candidate charged that
Atlanta city officials attempted to hide their homeless problem by
moving indigents from shacks under a viaduct near the Democratic
National Convention site into cheap apartments.
   ``The ramshackle, unsafe apartments (the homeless) were given
are meant to be temporary _ just long enough to keep this `eyesore'
from spoiling the sights for the convention delegates,'' Lenora B.
Fulani, candidate of the New Alliance Party, said Wednesday.
   Ms. Fulani, a developmental psychologist from New York, will be
the first woman placed on the ballot in all 50 states and the
District of Columbia for the Nov. 8 election. She is the first
black woman to receive federal matching campaign funds.
   Speaking on the steps of Atlanta City Hall, Ms. Fulani urged the
homeless to register and vote to assert their political rights.
   ``I believe that the solution to homelessness is an independent,
black-led and multiracialulti-racial third party in America that
stands for people instead of profits,'' she said.
   On Monday, city officials moved 16 homeless people from plywood
shacks and underground tunnels to apartments. Officials said the
move was for safety and security. They pledged to provide the
apartments only for 30 days.
