<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nurses     07-14 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nurses,530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: ``Carolyne'' 9th graf is cq</NOTE>
<HEAD>AIDS Nurses Honored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen nurses who specialize in caring for
AIDS patients were honored Thursday in ceremonies at the Department
of Health and Human Services.
   ``I don't think the American public realizes the strain that
AIDS has placed on our health care system, especially in those
cities with the highest rates of infection and the largest number
of cases,'' Said Dr. Robert E. Windom, the assistant HHS secretary
for health.
   He said the strain is not just financial, but on ``personnel
resources.''
   ``And by personnel resources, I mean nurses because it is the
nurses who give AIDS patients the warm, caring attention that makes
all the difference when you are ill,'' said Windom.
   ``When it comes to public recognition of this devotion to duty,
nurses have not had even one hand clapping,'' he said. ``That isn't
right. I've been a physician for 30 years and in my opinion nurses
deserve a standing ovation from the entire nation.''
   Windom said each of the 14 deserved to be singled out, but
emphasized that they ``are symbols for all of the nurses in our
country, so many of whom are equally deserving of public
recognition for the work they are doing.''
   He said he hoped the awards would ``help serve as a candle to
light the way for those young people who want a meaningful
profession to consider nursing as a career.''
   Coincidental with the awards ceremony, the department's newly
formed Commission on Nursing issued its first report _ concluding
that while the number of registered nurses in the United States is
at an all time high, the demand outstrips the supply.
   ``The commission has found that the situation for nurses and for
our health care system is serious and will require the attention
and concentrated efforts of all of us in the health care field,''
said Carolyne K. Davis, a nurse who heads the commission.
   The commission, formed in January, will make recommendations for
action in a later report.
   Meanwhile, it said, ``Nurses represent a bargain and hospitals
are too often using nurses to do the work of other employees,
especially as cutbacks occur among less highly trained personnel.''
   The report said a majority of hospitals are relying on overtime
work by registered nurses ``to staff their units adequately.''
   The nurses receiving awards from Windom were:
   Carol Price, Visiting Nurse Association of Brooklyn, N.Y.
   Mary Boland, director of AIDS nursing at Children's Hospital of
New Jersey, Newark, N.J.
   Barbara Russell, Baptist Hospital, Miami.
   Tracey Castleman, Kansas University Medical Center, Kansas City,
Kan.
   Christine Grady, Nancy L. Sears and Rose V. Thomas, all of the
National Institutes of Health in Rockville, Md.
   Terry Miles, St. Clare's Hospital, New York City.
   JoAnne Bennett, clinical consultant, Gay Men's Health Crisis,
New York City.
   Dorothy Ward-Wimmer, Children's Hospital National Medical
Center, Washington.
   Brenda L. Staton, D.C. General Hospital, Washington.
   Clifford l. Morrison, Robert Wood Johnson AIDS Health Services
Program, San Francisco.
   Helen Miramontes, Kaiser Foundation Hospitals, Santa Clara,
Calif., and Valley Medical Center, San Jose, Calif.
   Helen Schietinger, director of AIDS education and training,
California Nurses Association, San Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
