<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson 3rdLd-Writethru a0669 07-14 0945</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0669,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Asks Carter to Mediate Dispute With Dukakis Camp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 8 grafs, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, On
Wednesday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today he had received an
apology from a top aide to Michael Dukakis but is asking former
President Carter to step in and help ease continuing tension
between their two camps.
   Jackson said Carter could play ``a real role in facilitating a
meeting between the appropriate parties. He has gained the respect
of all of us.''
   Despite sending conciliatory signals to the Dukakis camp,
Jackson said, ``We will exercise all of our rights,'' and he added,
``We are prepared to deliberate and debate, Tuesday, Wednesday and
Thursday'' during next week's Democratic National Convention.
   At a news conference before heading to Atlanta, Jackson said he
did not want a ``personal apology'' but rather a role for his
supporters.
   ``Presently, I do not know the proposed strategy to win. At this
point, my constituency has no place on the team,'' he said.
   ``Mr. Bentsen symbolizes one wing of our party,'' he said. ``I
represent the other wing of the party. On a number of issues, our
views are opposite. That's all right. There is room for both. It
takes two wings to fly, and so far, our wing is not connected.''
   In what a Jackson aide called a ``good start'' to mending
relations between the two men, Dukakis telephoned Jackson on
Wednesday to try to ease misunderstandings over the way Jackson
learned about the selection of Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas as
Dukakis' running mate.
   Earlier Thursday, top Dukakis aide Paul Brountas called Jackson
on the same subject.
   On Wednesday, Jackson may have fueled the passions of those who
want to run him against Bentsen by saying the floor was ``wide
open'' on the vice presidential vote next Thursday night.
   Democratic National Committee chairman Paul Kirk said today in
Atlanta that Dukakis had talked to Jackson by telephone ``within
the last 24 hours'' in an effort to rebuild frayed relations.
   ``I know there has been a conversation between the two
candidates and several conversations between the two campaigns,''
Kirk said. ``I think we'll be moving forward to make sure there are
continuing discussions and hopefully we'll be able to resolve any
differences on substantive matters.''
   Jackson convention manager Ron Brown, also in Atlanta, said
Dukakis and Jackson agreed in their conversation to keep in touch
between now and Sunday, when both men are in Atlanta.
   ``It was an important call and a good start,'' Brown said.
   Asked if the call mollified Jackson about the perceived slight
over the fact that he learned of Bentsen's selections from
reporters, not Dukakis, Brown said, ``I guess his reaction is the
same as mine.''
   ``It just seems to us that the most important thing the Dukakis
campaign had to do during this process was consult with Jesse
Jackson and keep him informed. They failed to do either,'' Brown
said. ``That is a very significant oversight.''
   Jackson's departure by bus caravan to the convention city comes
as many of his supporters are still reeling from what they
considered Dukakis' snub.
   Dukakis says he tried to call Jackson on Tuesday morning to tell
him Lloyd Bentsen had been picked, but was not able to reach him.
He spoke with Jackson before the actual announcement, but after
reports were already circulating of the Texas senator's selection.
   And two Democratic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Jackson was told privately Monday afternoon that he would not
be picked. One source said Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas
told Jackson ``he would bring the ticket down'' if nominated for
vice president.
   A clearly irked Jackson complained in a news conference that
Dukakis is excluding him from the unity team Jackson has repeatedly
emphasized as the key to victory in November.
   ``At this point I'm not in the partnership,'' he said, adding:
``I'm not suggesting that I will compete for a place on the ticket
but the floor is wide open on Thursday night when the
recommendation is made.''
   ``I'm being asked to, in spite of inadequate communication and
not being recommended for the ticket, to motivate more people and
deliver more votes and pour out more energy at greater risk and
danger than any governor or any senator.''
   He would expect in return, he said, satisfaction for ``the
legitimate and reasonable requests'' of his constituents.
   On Wednesday night, speaking to Operation PUSH, the civil rights
group he founded, Jackson sounded similar themes, complaining about
exclusion.
   ``For too long, the power brokers have sat in small rooms with
closed doors and made great decisions,'' he declared. ``We must be
a part of this process. When they sit around these tables, the key
investors in our party are not in the group.''
   Jackson officials had been negotiating privately on unresolved
platform issues, but those talks were halted in light of the
running mate matter, Brown said.
   It's up to Dukakis ``to make it a unity convention,'' Brown
said, adding that Jackson has the logistical wherewithal to ``make
our presence felt'' on any matter at the convention.
   Jackson told his news conference that ``many people have a sense
of indignation and a sense of insult,'' about the handling of
Bentsen's selection.
   After Dukakis and Bentsen met with the Congressional Black
Caucus Wednesday, some of his Capitol Hill supporters said they
were satisfied the communication foul-up Tuesday was inadvertent.
   ``Lots of fences have been mended,'' said Rep. Mervyn Dymally,
D-Calif., chairman of the caucus. ``We have a very fruitful
discussion about the convention, the campaign and the presidency.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 5thLd-Writethru a0661 07-14 0935</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0661,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Asks Carter to Mediate With Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson-Carter comments in top 12 grafs, picking
up in 5th graf pvs, Democratic National; trims at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson today asked Jimmy Carter to mediate
his dispute with Democratic nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis.
Republican George Bush added his opinion that Dukakis could have
shown ``a little more in terms of sensitivity'' toward Jackson in
the way he announced his running mate.
   Jackson said former President Carter ``understands the
equation'' as the Democrats try to patch up relations between the
Dukakis and Jackson camps in the final days before the Democratic
National Convention.
   ``I simply want the respect and responsibility,'' Jackson said
at a Chicago news conference before starting a three-day bus trip
ending at the convention here.
   Bush made his comment on Dukakis and sensitivity as he traveled
to the United Nations Security Council, where he strongly defended
the United States' actions in the Persian Gulf.
   Relations between Jackson and Dukakis have been chilly since
Dukakis choose Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate on
Tuesday.
   The Massachusetts governor tried to warm up the situation with a
telephone call to Jackson on Wednesday.
   ``It was an important call and a good start,'' Jackson
convention manager Ron Brown said today. He said Dukakis tried to
explain the failure in communicating Dukakis' vice presidential
choice to Jackson before word got out on Tuesday.
   Jackson said he called Carter this morning to ask him to help
out.
   ``He has earned respect of all of us,'' Jackson said. ``He
understands the equation.''
   Jackson warned he still may challenge Dukakis every night of the
convention.
   ``It is an open convention. We have not yet made a decision
about all the strategies we will employ,'' Jackson said. ``We will
exercise all of our rights.''
   He said it is an ``open question'' as to whether he'll allow his
name to be entered in nomination for vice president.
   Democratic National Committee chairman Paul Kirk and House
Speaker Jim Wright, who will chair the convention, were both
hopeful that the differences between the campaigns could be
resolved.
   ``I think we'll be moving forward to make sure there are
continuing discussions and hopefully we'll be able to resolve any
differences on substantive matters,'' Kirk said in Atlanta.
   In Washington, Wright said Jackson had ``earned and fully
deserves a place in the highest councils, and he will have it.''
   Kirk acknowledged that negotiations on the platform are still
stalled, and he said he had personally talked to Jackson to explain
his role in the Tuesday announcement of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as
Dukakis's running mate.
   Dukakis and Bentsen spent Wednesday mending fences with major
Jackson supporters, with some success.
   ``It's a strong ticket. It's a winning ticket,'' said Rep. John
Lewis of Georgia after Dukakis and Bentsen met with the
Congressional Black Caucus on Capitol Hill. ``It was very friendly
in the room.''
   Bush, who is moving to start the process of selecting his own
running mate, talked to a breakfast gathering in Baltimore today
before heading to the United Nations.
   In Baltimore, Bush was asked how he would have handled Jackson
if he had been Dukakis.
   ``Maybe he (Dukakis) could have done a little more in terms of
sensitivity,'' he told the gathering of black businessmen.
   The Republican vice president said he and Jackson have ``a
pleasant relationship. ... I give him great credit for mobilizing
our attention on the need to address the narcotics question.''
   Then Bush flew to New York, where he was to speak for the Reagan
administration at the U.N. Security Council, defending the
government's actions in the shooting down of an Iranian airliner by
a U.S. warship in the Persian Gulf.
   Bush, in his prepared speech, blamed the Iranian government for
allowing the airliner to fly over the gulf as its gunboats and the
USS Vincennes were fighting, calling such a decision
``irresponsible.''
   ``One thing is clear,'' he said, ``the USS Vincennes acted in
self-defense'' in firing two missiles at the jetliner, which U.S.
officials say was mistaken for an Iranian F-14 fighter closing in
on the cruiser.
   Two new national polls gave sharply conflicting views of where
the race for the White House stands before the Democratic
convention opens _ and before the selection of Bentsen was
announced.
   The Los Angeles Times survey gave Dukakis an 11-point lead, 49
percent to 38 percent, over Bush in 1,763 telephone interviews with
registered voters conducted July 5-10. Several other national polls
have given Dukakis a lead of about 10 points.
   But a USA Today-CNN poll put the two contenders in a virtual
tie. That survey of 1,264 registered voters July 6-10 gave Bush 47
percent to Dukakis's 44 percent. Both surveys have sampling error
margins of about three percentage points, meaning the USA Today-CNN
results are a tie.
   Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, was spending the day at
the Statehouse in Boston, facing a state budget crisis.
   Jackson, beginning a three-day bus trip to Atlanta today, was
still frosty toward Dukakis. The civil rights leader has been
fuming over Dukakis' failure to tell him of his choice of Bentsen
Tuesday before he learned of it from reporters.
   ``After yesterday, many people have a sense of indignation and a
sense of insult,'' Jackson said at a Chicago news conference
Wednesday.
   At a Capitol Hill news conference, Dukakis said he had
apologized to Jackson when he did reach him Tuesday morning.
   ``I said I was sorry that I missed him on the first call,''
Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
