<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Radio     07-14 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Radio,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Visits Station Where He Began Broadcast Career</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Drought Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Thursday visited the
radio station where he began his career as a broadcaster a
half-century ago, saying broadcasting ``is a good way of making a
living and a good way of serving others.''
   Reagan stopped at station WOC after visiting drought-stricken
farm areas in Southern Illinois.
   Reagan was invited to the station, where he went to work in
1932, to dedicate a new building that opened several months ago.
   ``A lot has changed since 1932, but in a funny way the business
stays the same,'' said the president, who still delivers a weekly
radio broadcast.
   ``Its a good way of making a living and a good way of serving
others,'' he said.
   The new station is three miles from the building where Reagan
started work broadcasting football games.
   The original studio was on the top floor of the Palmer School of
Chiropractic, which is now the administration building of the
Palmer College of Chiropractic.
   Donna Kendall, director of public relations for the college,
said its name was changed several years ago and the school and the
radio station were severed from each other sometime around 1940.
WOC was an abbreviation for World of Chiropractic.
   Reagan first showed up at WOC in the late summer of 1932,
borrowing his father's Oldsmobile to make the trip of approximately
75 miles from the family home in Dixon, Ill.
   It was his first stop on a round of small-town radio stations he
planned to visit in search of a job.
   Although the station did not have an opening, Reagan talked the
station manager into giving him a tryout.
   The manager offered him a chance to broadcast a University of
Iowa football game the next Saturday for $5 and his round-trip fare
from Dixon.
   He was then hired to broadcast the games throughout the football
season, at $10 a game.
   After a regular staff vacancy occurred, he went to work for the
station at $100 a month on Feb. 10, 1933. According to historian
Garry Wills, in his book, ``Reagan's America,'' Reagan had left by
the end of May to work for WOC's sister station, WHO in Des Moines.
   He stayed in Des Moines radio until 1937, when it was off to
Hollywood and the movie career that paved the way for his entry
into politics and his election as governor of California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
