<DOCNO> AP880714-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ObeseDieters Bjt   07-14 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obese Dieters, Bjt,0804</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifteen Obesity Sufferers Make Last-Ditch Effort To Lose Weight</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Nellis, a former carnival worker,
dreams of climbing a Ferris wheel again. Ron Miller imagines
himself as Tina Turner's steady boyfriend.
   The two and 13 other tremendously obese people are living in a
hotel here as part of a diet program. Most say it's a matter of
life or death.
   ``It took a doctor to tell me I had no more than nine years to
live,'' the 690-pound Nellis, of Hurst, Ill., said Thursday. ``They
had kept after me. I was dumb before and didn't want to listen.''
   Entertainer and nutritionist Dick Gregory set up the free diet
program in the Howard Johnson's hotel June 5. He said his
Philadelphia-based Dick Gregory Health Enterprises is paying for
each participant with proceeds from the sale of his diet drink.
   Nellis, 31, who arrived Tuesday, must remain in his hotel room
for now because he cannot walk down the hall without stopping every
few steps to catch his breath.
   He must sleep kneeling at the side of the bed because he cannot
breathe lying down, and dreams of the day he can get a full night's
rest.
   Nellis said he weighed 250 pounds until age 21 and worked at a
carnival, scaling Ferris wheels and working 18-hour days. Then he
began less active work as a cab driver and the pounds began to pile
up.
   He does not know why he put on so much weight but said it forced
him to quit his job and go on disability eight years ago.
   Nellis said that by losing weight he will relieve his wife of 10
years and two stepchildren of tending to his every need.
   The dieters rise at 4 a.m., and obesity-related problems for
some begin immediately. For example, Nellis cannot lift his knee,
57 inches around, into the hotel shower, so he uses a plastic
swimming pool to wash.
   Breakfast begins at 5:30 a.m. with two glasses of spring water
followed by 30 to 45 minutes of walking for those who can handle
it. Those who can't, stay in their rooms until they are able.
   After another glass of spring water, participants stretch for 30
minutes and then eat breakfast _ half a grapefruit and half an
orange.
   Group meditation or prayer is next, and at 8 a.m. the
participants can return to their rooms for two hours of rest. They
then meet in a conference room for activities such as Monopoly and
backgammon.
   Lunch consists of raw vegetables or fresh fruit with more spring
water; during the afternoon they have Gregory's Bahamian Diet
drink. Dinner is the same as lunch. The group returns to their
rooms at 8 p.m. with lights out at 10.
   Gregory's company distributes his multivitamin powder through
mail orders and a nationwide network of sales people. The powder,
which sells in 16-ounce cans for $19.95, is mixed with fruit juice,
said Barbara Cain, a member of Gregory's staff.
   The powder has been sold since 1984, Ms. Cain said, adding that
exact yearly sales figures were unavailable.
   Gregory said the dieters needed to escape their
often-overprotective homes where their every whim was answered.
   ``These bodies were reserved for death,'' he said. ``It's
closing-down systems time. We're starting it up again. It's not
going to be easy.''
   Miller, 25, of Marion, Ind., who weighed 624 pounds when he
arrived last month, has dropped to about 500. His crush on
long-legged rock singer Tina Turner has been a major motivation to
shed pounds.
   ``I can't wait to meet her,'' Miller said with a laugh. ``I am
crazy about that woman. I want to be her next husband.''
   The battle against the bulge is constant.
   ``Some of us cry'' out of frustration at not being able to eat,
said Mike Parteleno, 30, of Struthers, Ohio. Parteleno said he
weighed 1,023 pounds when he met Gregory after hearing him lecture
in February. He said he has lost 307 pounds.
   Participants are weighed weekly on a specially designed
electronic scale that can weigh up to 2,000 pounds, said Ms. Cain.
   Nancy Gray, 48, of Duxbury, Mass., who weighs 338 pounds, is
participating with her 16-year-old son, Joe, who weighs 321. ``Life
was just a continuous meal for us,'' Mrs. Gray said, describing 2
a.m. forays into the kitchen to cook steak and mashed potatoes.
   Joenita Mitchell of Biloxi, Miss., who weighs 512 pounds and
arrived Wednesday, saw Gregory on a talk show. ``I eat, eat and
eat,'' said the 15-year-old, adding that she had a heart attack
when she was 14. ``It's taken its toll.''
</TEXT>
