<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Congress-Nicaragua     07-14 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Nicaragua,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OKs Resolution Condemning Sandinmistas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted 385-18 on Thursday to condemn
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government for ``brutal suppression
of basic human rights'' and urged the democracies of Central
America to meet to assess the situation.
   Unlike a similar resolution adopted by the Senate in a 91-4 roll
call Wednesday night, the measure drafted by the House's Democratic
leadership did not pose the possibility that military aid to the
Contra rebels might eventually be resumed.
   The House version condemned the Sandinistas for arresting more
than 40 people, including opposition leaders, and for closing down
the opposition newspaper LaPrensa for 15 days and a Roman Catholic
radio station indefinitely.
   It also urged Central American leaders ``to convene immediately
to assess the conditions in Nicaragua described in this
resolution.''
   ``I expect this body to take stronger action later,'' said Rep.
Robert J. Lagamarsino, R-Calif. ``This resolution contains strong
words. But it is just that _ strong words. There are no teeth in
this resolution.''
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said the resolution is necessary
because ``it is important that we in this country condemn any
violations of the principle of democracy.''
   Bonior said he believes there is still life in the peace process
fostered by President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica. ``The basis for
progress, I believe, still remains,'' he said.
   Earlier Thursday, U.S. Ambassador Robert Melton, expelled from
Managua this week by the Sandinistas, told the Senate Intelligence
Committee he believes congressional resolutions do little to sway
the Sandinistas.
   Melton said he does think ``the Sandinistas are impressed with
any evidence of resoluteness on the part of the Congress and
evidence of bipartisan resolve.'' But he added, ``I think the
Sandinistas are impressed more by actions than by words.''
   Melton said embassy functions have been so crippled by that
country's leftist Sandinista government that there are only ``very
marginal'' reasons to maintain diplomatic relations.
   The United States has made no move to end relations and
administration officials say they plan to replace embassy aides
ousted with Melton as soon as possible.
   ``One of the near-term tests is when we send new people there,''
Melton said. He said the manner in which they are treated and
permitted to operate ``will be a very real test of their (the
Sandinistas') desire to maintain relations.''
   The ambassador was asked by Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., if there
is any purpose for the United States to maintain a diplomatic
presence in Nicaragua, ``which gives legitimacy to the
government,'' if the embassy cannot function.
   ``Very marginal, very marginal purposes,'' Melton replied.
   He said that in his three months in Managua he was falsely
accused of masterminding ``Plan Melton,'' a conspiracy allegedly
aimed at subverting the Sandinista government.
   But Melton said there is ``not one scintilla of evidence'' that
he or the seven other U.S. diplomats expelled with him on Monday
ever engaged in espionage or any other activity that could have
justified action against them.
   The Sandinistas protested the contents of a speech Melton
delivered at the U.S. Embassy in celebration of Independence Day,
but he said the quotes to which they objected were not his but
those of Abraham Lincoln.
   Melton testified that embassy officials were followed by
Sandinista agents armed with cameras and that their photographs,
falsely identifying them as CIA agents, were printed in local
newspapers.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley reacted
sharply to a claim by the director general of the Nicaraguan
Foreign Ministry, Alejandro Bendana, that U.S. diplomats had
taunted Nicaraguan police at a rally last Sunday in Nandaime.
   Bendana sought to prove his case by showing a photograph on U.S.
news broadcasts of the diplomats with their hands raised.
   Mrs. Oakley called the use of photographs ``well-known
propagandistic devices'' because the message they convey can be
easily manipulated. She said the photograph shown by Bendana was
taken at a time when the embassy personnel were signaling other
members of their group to prepare to depart.
   Melton denied that embassy officials participated in the
opposition rally or were present in any other capacity than that of
observers.
   One committee member, Sen. Howard W. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said he
was skeptical that the Sandinistas expelled the U.S. diplomats with
no rational motive.
   ``I kid you not when I say there is something bothering me in
the back of my mind,'' Metzenbaum said. ``Why did President Daniel
Ortega _ in what seems to fly in the face of logic and reason _
take the steps that he did at the time that he did. I have the
feeling that I don't know everything.''
   Melton replied: ``If these actions seem irrational, it is
because they are.''
   Melton said that since arriving in Managua in April, most of his
requests for meetings with Sandinista officials were ignored and
the government attempted to discourage his contacts with opposition
figures, something he defended as normal U.S. diplomatic practice.
   He called the expulsion order ``an attempt to intimidate the
opposition, that's the way I think it should be recognized.''
   ``The message to the opposition is, `You're alone _ and you're
in our hands,''' he said.
</TEXT>
