<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DoubleJeopardy     07-14 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Double Jeopardy,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge's Solution To Embezzlement Works _ With One Hitch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman used money embezzled from her
new employer to pay back money stolen from her old employer,
prosecutors said.
   Ernestine Allen was arrested in June 1987 when the Gulf Group
Service Corp., a subsidiary of Gulf Life Insurance Co., discovered
she had been writing checks for undocumented insurance claims.
   A bookkeeper auditing Mrs. Allen's work discovered a $1,399
check was written for a fraudulent claim and mailed to her father's
home. Prosecutors said her father apparently was unaware of what
his daughter was doing.
   Mrs. Allen told company officials the check was the only one she
had written and she resigned her position, court records show.
Further auditing disclosed she had written 15 additional checks
using fraudulent documentation for a total of $10,300.
   The checks were deposited in a bank account at Marine National
Bank of Jacksonville.
   Mrs. Allen was charged with grand theft but agreed to repay the
money if the judge would withhold adjudication of guilt and not
sentence her to jail. She told prosecutors her family had agreed to
loan her the money for restitution.
   The judge sentenced her to one month's probation and ordered her
to pay back the money. He withheld a guilty ruling.
   She then got a job with Southeastern Metals Manufacturing Co.
   Mrs. Allen, 37, was arrested Wednesday and charged with five
counts of forgery and faces a charge of second-degree grand theft.
   Assistant State Attorney Lance Day said prosecutors have
evidence that Mrs. Allen took $47,725 from her new employer, by
writing 87 payroll checks to an employee who left the company a
long time ago. Mrs. Allen deposited the checks into her account at
Marine National, Day said.
   Day said authorities also have discovered five fraudulent money
orders issued for a total of $21,100. One was for $10,300, Day
said, the amount of the restitution to her first employer.
   Mrs. Allen was being held in the Duval County Jail.
</TEXT>
