<DOCNO> AP880714-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1551EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ConventionOverview Bjt   07-14 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Overview, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Where Red White and Blue Come Out Pink Gray and Pale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hard hats came off, the lights and music came
on, and the rostrum rose seemingly on its own Thursday, signaling
that the home of the 1988 Democratic National Convention is ready.
Well, nearly ready.
   Atlanta's Omni Coliseum, bedecked in a television designer's
vision of patriotic colors _ pink, gray and pale blue _ was
declared complete in a brief ribbon-cutting ceremony.
   Then it was back to work, because this enormous complex of
podiums, risers, camera platforms and network studios inside what
is otherwise home for the Atlanta Hawks basketball team won't be
fully ready until the gavel falls Monday.
   ``Don't take for granted it was just another day's work,''
Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk told construction workers
who gathered in the seats where delegates will sit next week. ``It
was a page in history.''
   The hall where Michael Dukakis will claim his party's
presidential nomination has been the scene of hurried preparations
for weeks, and as the advance wave of journalists and party
officials arrived over the last several days, they could hardly
hear each other over the din of construction.
   Kirk and Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young showed off the fancy
moveable podium sections after the ribbon was cut. They are
controlled with hydraulic lifts by a stage manager who will sit
behind the speakers _ and who has the power with a flip of a
control to make 5-foot 8-inch Dukakis look as tall as 6-foot 2-inch
Jackson _ at least on television.
   The entire hall is amazingly small _ so small that half the
4,212 delegates won't actually sit on the floor. They'll be in the
bleachers.
   What it looks like, actually, is a television set. And that's
basically what it is.
   ``I approached it from that standpoint,'' said Rene Lagler, a
California television set designer who planned the convention
interior.
   Lagler also came up with the color scheme, which he prefers to
call red white and blue.
   ``On camera the whole thing will look red, white and blue,'' he
said. ``Just squint: that's what it will look like on television.''
   Some squinters, however, found the colors remained pink, gray
and pale blue.
   Overhead, lights swiveled by remote control, as they will when
the convention begins, and canned music poured from giant speakers
that were sniffed by bomb-detecting dogs before they were lifted
overhead. For delegates in seats so poor they can't see, giant
television screens atop the whole thing will provide a view.
   Mike McCurry, the convention's director of communications, said
that while all looks pretty close to ready there are constant
demands for adjustments.
   ``I walked in here yesterday and thought, `My lord, they're not
going to be ready,''' McCurry said. ``But they've done a lot in two
days.''
   Even as the ribbon was cut, however, television microwave
receivers were still being installed above studio ``skyboxes'' that
allow anchormen to look down on the whole thing.
   CNN's team of correspondents, producers and crews had been
standing around for hours, their scheduled dress rehearsal of floor
coverage left dead in the water by a failed radio system.
   The big dispute of the week was over where the four television
networks' ``talent'' _ the big-name correspondents _ were going to
sit. After a howl of protest that they were being placed too far up
behind the podium, McCurry accommodated them with a closer spot.
   The full podium is 200 feet wide, though what moves is only a
smaller rostrum and surrounding area. The huge structure further
reduces in size what is already a small hall _ seating no more than
12,000 to 17,000 people for sports events.
   Just off the floor is the Hawks' office, where general manager
Stan Kasten strolled out to declare the hall unrecognizable.
   ``It's amazing,'' he said.
   Most of the 13,500 or so journalists won't even get in the hall,
or will only part of the time. They're being accommodated in the
vast Georgia World Congress Center, dubbed the ``Media Village.''
There's plenty of room _ but it's another world from the hall, and
to get there is a walk out doors and across the street.
   Outside the whole thing, scores of satellite uplink trucks were
being put in place, their dish antennas pointed skyward. There's a
mobile-home village of network equipment _ and the handful of
trailers the Dukakis and Jackson campaigns each will use as command
posts.
   Back inside, Lagler was looking over his labors when one of his
hard-hatted workers came up with a question: when was the meeting
to discuss tearing it all down after Thursday night.
   ``That'll be another problem,'' Lagler said, ``getting all this
out of here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
