<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndianArrest     07-14 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Arrest,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reservation Chairman Arrested on Narcotics Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRANDON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The narcotics arrest of the chairman of the
Mole Lake Indian Reservation was no surprise in light of the
Chippewa band's struggle with drug problems, says the vice chairman.
   Vice Chairman Roger McGeshick Sr. said he planned to call a
community meeting to discuss the arrest Tuesday of Arlyn Ackley as
well as narcotics traffic on the reservation in northern Wisconsin.
   Ackley, 36, chairman of the Mole Lake Tribal Council for six
years, was jailed on $10,000 bail on two counts of delivery of
cocaine.
   Brian Maloney, Oneida County district attorney, said Ackley also
faces cocaine charges in Forest and Outagamie counties, and could
be in danger from narcotics suppliers.
   An undercover agent purchased one ounce of cocaine from Ackley
two times in November, the Wisconsin Division of Criminal
Investigation said.
   McGeshick, 47, a cousin of Ackley as well as the tribal vice
chairman, called drugs the biggest problem on the 1,850-acre Mole
Lake reservation, home to about 375 members of the Sokaogon, one of
six bands of the state's 1,200-member Chippewa tribe.
   The arrest of Ackley, McGeshick said, would not affect the
band's business, including talks with the state concerning
off-reservation hunting and fishing.
   Each charge against Ackley carries a possible penalty of not
less than $1,000 nor more than $250,000, and a prison term of not
less than six months nor more than five years, Maloney said.
</TEXT>
