<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-Congress     07-14 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Congress,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Lawmakers See Protests, Meetings On Dukakis-Jackson Rift</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black members of Congress predicted Thursday
that there will be boisterous protests at next week's Democratic
convention in Atlanta over what they see as Gov. Michael Dukakis'
snub of Jesse Jackson.
   But some of the lawmakers also said they understand political
realities and will hold a black strategy session early in the week
in an effort to repair the schism between the Dukakis and Jackson
camps and end the quadrennial meeting as a unified party.
   ``Clearly the way Jesse Jackson was dealt with, on a personal
basis, looms as a monumental issue,'' said Rep. Ron Dellums,
D-Calif. ``It speaks to how black people are perceived in this
election. He is the personification of the hopes of millions of
people. Whether Mr. Dukakis understands that or not is something
that remains to be seen.''
   Jackson and his supporters were stung by Dukakis' selection of
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen for the vice presidential spot on the
Democratic ticket, and the hurt was compounded when Jackson first
learned about the choice from reporters rather than directly from
Dukakis.
   Dukakis telephoned Jackson on Wednesday to try to mend strained
relations, and Jackson said Thursday he had asked former President
Jimmy Carter to mediate between the two camps. Jackson also said he
got an apology from a top Dukakis aide but no apology from Dukakis.
   The lawmakers said their concerns extended beyond the personal
tiff to the appearance that issues of concern to blacks were being
given short shrift.
   Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., chairman of the Congressional
Black Caucus, said meetings aimed at healing the rift are being set
up for his group with Paul Brountas, the top Dukakis aide who ran
the campaign's vice-presidential search, and possibly later with
Dukakis himself.
   ``We are trying to salvage this,'' Dymally said, acknowledging
that there is a wide range of intensity about the matter among the
23 black House members who make up the caucus. ``We are practical
politicians.''
   Some caucus members said they recognized the danger to their
political standing if Jackson appears to be going to the convention
purely as a spoiler.
   The Black Caucus was working through Rep. Nicholas Mavroules,
D-Mass., to set up the meetings, and Mavroules said he expected
there to be a lengthy meeting, perhaps on Tuesday.
   ``I think it would be a very wise idea on the part of the
Dukakis people,'' Mavroules said. ``They can talk at length about
problems, about issues. And if they want, they can talk about the
Jackson thing ... I would like very much if we could have a nice,
good, normal, united convention.''
   Mavroules said the members of the Congressional Black Caucus
``play a very key role. We need them with us. I think most of them
want this settled.''
   Some of those lawmakers, however, appeared to be turning up the
heat on Dukakis. Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., vowed to stage a march on
Monday from the grave of slain civil rights leader Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. to the Omni convention center.
   Savage said another protest rally will be held on Wednesday near
the convention center just before the presidential nomination is
made, and said blacks would boycott the acceptance speeches on
Thursday of Dukakis and Bentsen if Jackson is not on the ticket.
   Dellums said Dukakis is showing ``a level of arrogance that is
extraordinary'' in not making an open and uncompromising apology to
Jackson. He and others said it is up to Dukakis to extend a hand to
Jackson and make a public show of concern for Jackson and the
issues he represents.
   ``I think there's going to be a lot of confusion down in
Atlanta, a lot of pain down there,'' Dellums said.
</TEXT>
