<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Unisys-ArizonaProbe 1stLd-Writethru a068od</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unisys-Arizona Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys Probe Involves Alleged Overcharges, Army Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 7th graf, ``The company'' with Unisys statement</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army Information Systems Command said
Thursday that a criminal investigation of Unisys Corp. in Arizona
involves alleged overcharging on a $9.2 million contract.
   The contract for computer support work between Unisys and the
systems command expired in September 1987 and relates to the way in
which costs were allocated by Sperry Corp., Army spokesman Al
Hinton said in a statement from Fort Huachuca, Ariz., where the
Army command is based.
   Sperry Corp. was merged with Burroughs Corp. to form Unisys
Corp. in 1986.
   Unisys has an estimated $80 million in computer hardware and
software support contracts with the Army Information Systems
Command. The Fort Huachuca investigation is separate from the
sweeping Pentagon bribery probe, in which Unisys is also involved.
   The command provides the Army worldwide with automated data
processing including office automation, communications, printing
and publishing, records management and visual information.
   The existence of the probe, under way for several months and
being conducted by the U.S. attorney's office in Tucson, was
confirmed Wednesday by Unisys from its headquarters in Blue Bell,
Pa., but no details were provided.
   The company said it ``has been cooperating with the office of
the U.S. attorney in Tucson, Ariz., in its investigation of a
contract with the Army Communications Center based in Fort
Huachuca.''
   Sperry and Unisys have provided software support to the command
for more than 10 years.
   The Wall Street Journal, which on Wednesday disclosed the
existence of the Fort Huachuca probe, quoted a source familiar with
the investigation as saying that the government contended it may
have been overcharged by as much as $10 million. But the Army
command statement said that ``any overcharges would be considerably
less'' in view of the total size of the contract of $9.2 million.
</TEXT>
