<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 2059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Convention     07-14 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Convention,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Logistically, the Jackson Camp Is Ready for Come What May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, weighing his strategy options for
the Democratic convention next week, has put together a
sophisticated logistical operation that can handle just about any
decision he makes, his convention manager says.
   When Jackson's bus caravan arrives in town this weekend amid
great hoopla, awaiting will be the technical backbone of his
convention operation, born of weeks of planning and gritty detail.
   The setup, with systems to communicate instantly with floor
delegates was put in place at a time when it was not known how much
it would actually be used, said Jackson's convention manager Ron
Brown.
   In light of developments this week, when Jackson suspended
continuing platform talks with the Dukakis campaign, decisions are
up in the air as to what he will do at the convention. The
operation could end up being more important than originally
envisioned.
   ``You can assume we have the wherewithal to make our presence
felt on everything that happens at the convention,'' said Brown.
   Democratic National Committee press secretary Mike McCurry, the
party's convention spokesman, says Jackson ``did what the
Democratic Party itself should have done _ went out and hired some
of the most experienced and best convention organizers.''
   The party staff even sought out Jackson team members for advice
on how to handle an occasional problem of their own, McCurry said.
   Although Gov. Michael Dukakis is the convention's inevitable
convention nominee, McCurry said Jackson has ``a very well
organized operation that would rival Gov. Dukakis.
   ``It goes without saying that Gov. Dukakis has more resources
and something of an edge as a front runner,'' McCurry said, but
added, ``I would put both teams on the field and know that you
would have a very even game.''
   As recently as Monday, Jackson's headquarters trailers outside
the convention hall had working phones, electricity, furniture and
staff moving in. Dukakis' trailers nearby were empty, with about
two dozen filled water-cooler bottles lined up underneath one.
   ``The Dukakis people are peeking in the windows of our
trailer,'' Brown joked early in the week.
   Jackson intends to use the machinery in the traditional manner _
with a ``whip'' system to communicate from telephones in
headquarters trailers to delegates on the convention floor.
   ``We ran a very serious presidential campaign and we're running
a very sophisticated convention operation,'' Brown said.
   ``We're serious players on the American political scene now and
in the future, and I think we have to demonstrate that. You have to
demonstrate competence ... sense of purpose, discipline.''
   This year's operation is miles ahead of Jackson's 1984 set up in
San Francisco, when he made his first presidential bid.
   That year, Jacksonspent a fraction of the estimated $500,000 he
is putting into his staff of about 50 and preparations for this
year's convention.
</TEXT>
