<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Libya, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0539,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Man Who Barricaded Self Inside Libyan Embassy Taken Into
Custody</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police saying man taken into
custody, situation ended. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said a pistol-wielding Arab man
who had barricaded himself inside the Libyan Embassy for almost 12
hours after employees refused him a visa was taken into custody
late today.
   ``The situation at the Libyan Embassy is over,'' said police
spokesman Helmut Kuehlmann.
   He declined to give further details, saying a press conference
was scheduled at police headquarters later.
   The unidentified gunman, who police said was in his 20s, had
demanded to be flown to Libya, said another Bonn police spokesman,
Hans Georg Classen.
   Earlier, Classen said the man claimed he escaped from a West
German prison.
   ``He told police he had broken out of prison in the federal
republic (West Germany) and that he now wants to go to Libya,''
Classen said.
   Classen said the man barricaded himself on the first floor of
the building. He said the man took no hostages but that several
employees were trapped on upper floors in the building, officially
called the Libyan People's Bureau. He said he didn't know how many
people there were.
   Classen said the employees couldn't leave because the gunman
controlled access to the stairways and doors.
   ``What we are trying to do right now is to prevent any taking of
hostages,'' Classen had said.
   Several embassy employees stood on a balcony watching as police
surrounded the area.
   Classen said the man was an Arab, but his nationality was not
known. He said the gunman demanded to be flown to Libya immediately.
   He said the incident began began when the man entered the
building to apply for a visa. The request was refused and the man
then pulled a pistol, Classen said.
   The police spokesman said no shots were fired.
   Police sealed off the area after they received the alarm shortly
before 10 a.m., Classen said.
   The embassy in on a quiet, tree-lined street in Bad Godesberg,
an area of Bonn where many embassies are located.
</TEXT>
