<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Mock Trial,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Summoned To Mock Trial Over Misconduct Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright was ``summoned''
Thursday to testify about misconduct allegations against him at a
mock public trial next week outside the Democratic National
Convention hall in Atlanta.
   A ``subpoena'' for Wright, D-Texas, to testify in his defense
was delivered to Marshall L. Lynam, the speaker's chief of staff,
by Eugene Delgaudio, executive director of Public Advocate, a
conservative-oriented ``citizens action committee.''
   Delgaudio, who wore black judicial robes, presented the summons
to Lynam in the speaker's press office under the watchful eye of
several Capitol Police guards who escorted Delgaudio out of the
building afterward. Delgaudio said he was not allowed to see
Wright, who was working in his office elsewhere in the House wing
of the Capitol.
   Reporters were barred from the office where Delgaudio and Lynam
met. An aide said later that Lynam was not available for comment.
   Delgaudio said members of Congress and convention delegates had
been invited to attend the mock trial Tuesday morning in a parking
lot reserved for demonstrations near the Democratic convention
arena.
   Delgaudio said a trial jury of public citizens will deliver a
verdict on charges against Wright, who will serve as chairman of
the Democratic convention starting Monday.
   The House ethics committee announced June 10 it had voted
unanimously to investigate allegations that Wright had abused the
powers of his office for personal gain and had intervened
improperly with federal bank regulators.
   Wright has denied any wrongdoing and charged that the ethics
complaint filed in May by Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., was
politically motivated.
   Delgaudio said his organization supports the 74 members of
Congress, including Gingrich, who have demanded appointment of an
independent counsel to investigate the allegations against Wright.
   ``We are concerned that a potential abuse of power is being
ignored,'' Delgaudio said. ``There needs to be a full disclosure of
all the facts.''
</TEXT>
