<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Trade     07-14 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Vows Renewed Trade Push as Panels OK Canadian Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, back in the Senate
after a campaign trip, said Thursday that running for vice
president will not distract him from pushing for final approval of
a wide-ranging trade bill.
   ``I'll be taking some of my time to work on that trade bill here
in the Senate,'' the Texan told reporters at a meeting of his
Finance Committee. He said he had ``talked to Governor Dukakis on
that'' and gotten the green light.
   The House approved the sweeping trade bill Wednesday and sent it
to the Senate, where action could follow next week's break for the
Democratic National Convention.
   Some Democrats are saying the decision by Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis to tap Bentsen as his running mate heightens
prospects for Senate approval of the legislation.
   The Finance Committee on Thursday approved a legislative
blueprint for implementing the U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement
approved in January by President Reagan and Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney. The plan also won approval from the House Ways and Means
Committee.
   The nation would phase out tariffs between the two nations over
the next 10 years.
   Under special procedures reserved for international trade pacts,
the administration will now introduce implementing legislation that
follows closely the blueprint drawn up by the two committees.
   Congress, in turn, guarantees the legislation speeded up
consideration with amendments ruled out.
   Administration officials appeared before the committee and
promised that the legislation would not include subsidies for the
U.S. uranium industry, which had been delaying action by the two
committees.
   Neither Bentsen nor Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., was willing to go along with the uranium
subsidy plan. An assortment of other squabbles also were settled
and officials said the path appeared clear for approval of the
agreement and the bill.
   ``We've set an example for the entire world on what can be
accomplished with free trade,'' Bentsen said. ``This is a historic
moment.''
   Rostenkowski issued a statement saying the lawmakers had
``reached agreement among ourselves and with the administration on
the details of the implementing legislation.''
   ``I believe that this consultative process has developed a
sound, well crafted implementing bill, which balances all
interests,'' he said.
   ``It fully carries out our obligations uknder the agreement but
also protects the legitimate intrerests of those few industries
concerned about possible adverse effects on their current business
dealings.''
</TEXT>
