<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DoubleLiverTransplant     07-14 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Double Liver Transplant,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smallest Liver Transplant Recipient Dies After Historic Dual
Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tiniest baby ever to receive a liver
transplant died Thursday, two days after doctors divided a donated
organ between him and another baby in the first U.S. operation of
its type, a spokesman said.
   Twelve-week-old Joseph Kovach died of heart failure at Wyler
Children's Hospital at the University of Chicago Medical Center,
spokesman John Easton said.
   The boy's heart had stopped briefly after the transplant and he
later suffered kidney and lung failure.
   The other baby, a 7-month-old girl, was ``doing very well,'' but
was listed in critical and stable condition, Easton said.
   The Kovach baby, of Geneva, Ill., weighed only 4.2 pounds
Tuesday when he received the transplant, which doctors regarded as
a long-shot for saving his life but his only hope, said his
physician, Peter F. Whitington.
   Joseph had previously undergone open-heart surgery to correct a
birth defect, but his heart was still weak and the stress of the
second operation was too much, Whitington said.
   His death will not discourage subsequent double liver
transplants, which could help other youngsters too small to
accommodate adult livers and likely to die while awaiting scarcer
children's organs, Whitington said.
   ``Technically, this is not a setback. His liver was functioning
very well this morning, even just before he died,'' Whitington
said. ``Of course that is not important to Joseph Kovach.''
   ``What we showed with this pair is that it's clearly technically
feasible,'' Whitington said. ``We did it under the worst of
circumstances ... with a very sick, very small baby that needed a
graft (new organ) we never would have gotten without a reduction''
in the size of the donor organ.
   Double liver transplants have been performed previously in
Europe, involving adult donors, but no double liver transplants had
been done previously in the United States, Easton said.
   Whitington said he told the boy's parents that any complications
at all would result in the child's death, and that ``if it all went
perfectly, there was a small chance he would make it.''
   Joseph suffered from cirrhosis, a type of liver damage that can
exist at birth from an unknown cause.
   He was the first child of Patty and Donald Kovach, a comptroller
for a Chicago firm, Easton said.
   The other youngster, Jaclyn Manrose of Crystal Lake, Ill., had a
hereditary defect called alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency, an
insufficent amount of an enzyme that can lead to hepatitis or
cirrhosis.
   Jaclyn is one of three children of Kathleen and Bob Manrose, a
maintenance specialist with United Airlines, Easton said.
   Jaclyn and Joseph received the divided liver of a 1-year-old
Illinois child who died in an accident, the university said.
   Two younger infants have received new livers at the University
of Pittsburgh's transplant center, but both babies _ ages 16 days
and 3 weeks _ weighed more than 6 pounds, Easton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Drought-GreatLakes     07-14 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Great Lakes,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Engineers Reject Diversion of Great Lakes Water to
Mississippi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers has rejected
requests from Illinois Gov. James Thompson and other officials for
increased diversion of water from the Great Lakes into the
drought-parched Mississippi River, an Army official said Thursday.
   ``We do not feel it is necessary to do it at this time,'' said
Robert Page, the Army's assistant secretary for civil works, after
testifying before the Senate merchant marine subcommittee.
   The decision was ``not politically motivated'' and was based on
engineering analyses, Page said.
   He said he wrote Thompson on Thursday to inform the governor of
the decision.
   Page said the decision will be subject to review by President
Reagan but the White House placed responsibility with the corps.
   ``We have talked with the administration about this,'' Page
said. ``It is left strictly up to the Army Corps of Engineers.''
   The decision was in response to Reagan's request that the corps
study the need for diversion, Page said.
   Thompson and officials from states bordering the Mississippi
asked for increased diversion of Great Lakes water after levels on
the river dropped, making the channel unnavigable to barge traffic.
   Barge shippers have estimated losses as a result of the stalled
shipping at up to $60 million. Some 3,000 barges have been stalled
as a result of low water.
   Presently, about 3,000 cubic feet per second are being diverted
from the Great Lakes to the Mississippi. The officials asked that
the rate be increased to 10,000 cubic feet per second for 100 days.
   The governors of four Great Lakes states opposed the diversion,
and only Thompson supported it among the leaders of the eight
states surrounding the lakes.
   Canadian officials also protested the proposed diversion.
   Page said the corps would have the legal authority to increase
the rate of diversion but would do so only after consultation with
Great Lakes states governors.
   Supporters of diversion argued the increased flow out of the
lakes would have a miniscule impact on the Great Lakes but would
have great benefits downriver.
   Opponents argued that the lakes water was needed in the Midwest
and Northeast and that increasing diversion would set an
unacceptable precedent.
   Page said increasing the outflow to 10,000 cubic feet per second
would not do much to help Mississippi navigation, and shoals would
continue to impede the flow of goods.
   He said the corps foresees through the summer ``we will still
have flow'' on the Mississippi.
   ``We see in the foreseeable future based on our forecast we
don't need (increased diversion) at all,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0177 </DOCNO>
