<2ND_LINE>AM-NAACP March,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP Delegates March on South African Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 NAACP members demonstrated
before the South African Embassy on Thursday to protest that
nation's system of racial discrimination, chanting ``let our people
go.''
   The demonstrators lifted up a grey casket into which NAACP
executive director Benjamin Hooks said he was imprisoning the
policies of apartheid, segregation, hatred, discrimination, unjust
treatment and inequality.
   He led the crowd in a pronouncement over the coffin, saying,
``dust to dust, ashes to ashes _ apartheid you'll never rise
again!''
   The coffin was placed into a white hearse as the demonstrators
sang ``Oh, Freedom,'' a song from the civil rights movement.
   Hooks prayed that ``those white folk in South Africa that call
themselves Christians may start acting like Christians and
recognize that they are their brother's keeper ... that we are all
one blood.''
   ``We come here today in the spirit of Walter White, Roy Wilkins,
Martin Luther King ... to say that we won't be satisfied until the
walls of segregation, apartheid and oppression are brought low in
South Africa,'' said the Rev. Jerry Guess, communications director
for the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   ``We come today praying that our own pharaoh, who sits at 1600
Pennsylvania Avenue, will hear these voices (and realize that) we
cannot exist in this world, half slave and half free,'' Guess said.
   The group gathered at the embassy after a half-hour march in
what was the culmination of South Africa Day at the 79th annual
convention of the NAACP.
   In morning sessions of the conference, Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., and Randall Robinson, head of TransAfrica, a lobby group
for the Caribbean and Africa, urged the delegates to support
legislation to impose stronger economic sanctions on South Africa.
</TEXT>
