<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AvonBoycott     07-14 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Avon Boycott,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Launches National Boycott of Avon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS_</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking paper mill workers Thursday called for
a national boycott of Avon Products Inc. because of the cosmetics
manufacturer's ties to International Paper Co.
   The link is Stanley Gault, who serves on the board of directors
of both companies in addition to his position as chairman and chief
executive officer of Rubbermaid.
   ``Avon is a corporate ally of International Paper,'' said Wayne
Glenn, president of the United Paperworkers International Union.
The union represents 8,000 IP workers who for more than a year have
been on strike, locked out or working without a contract at 17
plants across the country.
   The union is calling on women not to buy Avon cosmetics.
   ``Avon and International Paper are two separate companies,''
said Avon spokesman John Cox. The mutual board member is the ``only
tenuous link between the two companies. ... We think the boycott is
unwarranted.''
   Gault, who was in meetings all day and could not be reached, has
not been approached about resigning from the Avon board, Cox said.
   Gault, who was elected to the board in 1985, also got support
from IP, which said, ``Gault is an outside director, whose
independent judgment International Paper values highly.''
   IP spokesman Bill Fuller in a statement said the boycott was ``a
distraction from coming to grips with the things that have to be
done to put the disputes behind us.''
   Federal law generally prohibits picketing of neutral employers,
but an April Supreme Court decision said the law does not ban
non-picketing activities aimed at such businesses.
   ``The Supreme Court decision allows us to hold each of IP's
allies directly accountable,'' Glenn said, also reading from a
statement.
   The union is studying the affiliations of all 15 IP directors,
according to Bob Frase, Glenn's spokesman.
   The Avon boycott is the union's first national effort, but
several local boycotts are under way.
   The Bank of Boston is being boycotted because one of its
directors, Donald McHenry, also serves on the IP board.
   In Pennsylvania, the union has launched a boycott of the PNC
Financial Corp. W. Craig McClelland heads IP's Hammermill
subsidiary and sits on the board of PNC Financial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
