<DOCNO> AP880714-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra     07-14 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Seeks Court Order to Get Handwriting Samples</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh on
Thursday sought a court order to obtain handwriting samples from
former national security adviser John M. Poindexter and two arms
dealers charged in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case.
   Walsh also sought to obtain photographs of Poindexter and the
two arms dealers _ Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen.
Richard V. Secord _ to show to prospective witnesses in the case.
   The handwriting samples were needed, Walsh said, because had had
obtained ``numerous documents believed to contain the handwriting
of the various defendants.''
   Poindexter, Hakim and Secord are charged along with fired White
House aide Oliver L. North with conspiring to defraud the
government by diverting profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   Walsh noted that he had already obtained samples of North's
handwriting, as a result of a grand jury subpoena that was the
subject of a lengthy court battle last year.
   North, who was cited for contempt of court for refusing to
supply handwriting samples, challenged Walsh's legal authority to
obtain grand jury subpoenas. A federal appeals court upheld Walsh's
authority and enforced the subpoena.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell has ordered four separate
trials and scheduled North's to begin Sept. 20.
   In seeking the handwriting samples from the three defendants,
Walsh said ``it is well settled that a defendant has no valid claim
of privilege with respect to handwriting examplars.''
   ``Similarly, the government is entitled to take photographs of
the defendants, since it is well-established that neither the
Fourth nor the Fifth Amendment offers any protection against
compulsion to submit to such photographs.''
   In a related case, U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr.
approved the security procedures proposed by Walsh for handling
thousands of pages of documents in the case against former CIA
agent Joseph F. Fernandez.
   Fernandez, who operated in Central America under the code-name
Tomas Castillo, is accused of conspiring to set up an illegal
arms-supply network to the Nicaraguan rebels and subsequently lying
to cover up his activities.
   The order states that classified documents can only be examined
in the security facility under supervision of a court security
officer. The same facility was constructed by the Justice
Department to house documents turned over to the defendants in the
other Iran-Contra case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
