<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-Angola     07-14 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Says Talk of Withdrawal from Angola `Inexact'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban official on Thursday called
``inexact'' a U.S. statement saying Cuban negotiators reached
agreement in principle to withdraw Cuba's troops from Angola.
   But State Department and South African officials said it was
just a matter of semantics _ that Cuba did agree to bring its
troops home, but expressed that view in a ``statement of
principles,'' not in what diplomats would call an ``agreement.''
   The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Cuban, Angolan, and South African negotiators initialed a
statement of principles Wednesday calling for Cuban troops to leave
the Marxist-ruled southern African nation of Angola and for South
Africa to end its 73-year rule over Namibia, said Chester Crocker,
the U.S. mediator for the talks.
   They did not agree on a timetable for the Cuban withdrawal at
private meetings this week, said Crocker, the State Department
undersecretary for African affairs, on Wednesday.
   Alcibiades Hidalgo, a Cuban negotiator and member of the Central
Committee of Cuba's Communist Party, said Thursday:
   ``I would say it is not precise to say that an agreement has
been reached on the withdrawal of Cuban troops.
   ``This issue ... is part of all the discussions, is part of a
process that is continuing. I would qualify it as inexact to say
that an agreement has been reached on the withdrawal of all Cuban
troops.''
   ``It is our opinion that we made substantial progress.''
   Hidalgo spoke in Spanish through an interpreter at a news
conference at the Cuban Mission to the United Nations.
   A State Department official on Thursday saw no real
contradiction, saying, ``We have never used the term `agreement'.
What the Cubans agreed to is a set of principles. It doesn't
constitute a specific agreement.''
   The principles agreed to must now be signed by the Angolan,
Cuban, and South African governments.
   Military and political experts from those countries will meet in
August to work out details for a comprehensive settlement.
   A South African diplomat noted that the document Cuba initialed
refers to ``a peaceful settlement in southwestern Africa'' _
showing that a settlement of the southern Angola problem is part of
the set of principles.
   South Africa has said it would accept a U.N. Security Council
resolution calling for the independence of South-West Africa,
commonly called Namibia, when the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops
withdraw from neighboring Angola.
   The U.S. goal is a full Cuban troop withdrawal in one year, the
same time span that U.N. Resolution 435 sets for granting
independence to Namibia.
   Angola and Cuba had insisted that Cuban withdrawal take place
over four years.
   The United States was a party to the talks because it has been
supporting anti-communist rebels in Angola with funds and weapons
since 1985.
   Angola has been fighting a civil war since it gained
independence from Portugal in 1975, battling anti-communist rebels
in the south who call themselves UNITA, for National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola.
   South Africa has repeatedly sent troops from Namibia into Angola
to support UNITA forces in the fighting.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I under a League
of Nations mandate to administer the territory. The League's
successor, the United Nations, revoked that mandate.
   The four parties began their meetings in London last May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
