<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     07-14 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Won't Be Drawn Into Jackson-Dukakis Rift</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen refused Thursday to be
drawn into the rift between Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis,
saying it's up to Dukakis to mend relations between the two camps.
   Smoothing over tensions with Jackson is ``Gov. Dukakis'
responsiblity,'' said Bentsen, who was selected for the running
mate spot Jackson had coveted.
   ``I know he (Dukakis) has a high regard for Reverend Jackson. I
assume he'll have a meeting with Jackson,'' Bentsen said in a
session with reporters from his home state.
   ``Once again, that's a matter of communication with Reverend
Jackson,'' he said.
   Bentsen said he had no plans to meet personally with Jackson,
who was irked at learning of Bentsen's selection Tuesday from
reporters before he heard from Dukakis. Bentsen did, however, call
Jackson on Wednesday, and described it as ``a good conversation ...
a personal conversation.''
   Jackson received an apology Thursday from one of Dukakis' top
advisers, but said he was still asking former President Carter to
intercede. On Wednesday, Jackson said the floor was ``wide open''
on the vice presidential vote next Thursday night at the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta.
   Bentsen said ``it's up to Jackson to decide'' whether to stage a
floor fight over the vice presidential nomination.
   Bentsen, a conservative Democrat whose positions differ greatly
from those of Dukakis on such issues as an oil import fee, aid to
the Nicaraguan contras, and the death penalty, said he was
``looking for a good exchange of communication'' with the
Massachusetts governor.
   But, ``We're in accord on job creation, education, child care,
health care, having babies born with sound minds and bodies. These
are the things we share,'' Bentsen said.
   Bentsen, who once said the office of vice president was an empty
job, has changed his mind and is convinced Dukakis wants and will
treat him as a trusted adviser.
   Bentsen said he consulted with Dukakis' former lieutenant
governor, John Kerry, and studied ``the character of the man, not
diagrams and charts,'' before accepting the job.
   ``That was my major question. Was I really going to be able to
communicate, counsel and advise,'' Bentsen said. ``I kept checking
and studying ... and became convinced it could be a meaningful
job.''
   And Dukakis has assured him ``he very much wants to have my
input,'' Bentsen said. ``People told me that was his nature.''
   Bentsen believes he was chosen Dukakis' running mate because of
his legislative experience ``which exposes you to so many facets of
this country of ours,'' his proven ability to work with Congress,
and his exposure though the years to various heads of state.
   A senator since 1970, Bentsen is being opposed in his
re-election bid this year by Rep. Beau Boulter, a Republican.
Bentsen is legally allowed to run both races under a law passed in
Texas that allowed Lyndon B. Johnson to run for vice president with
John F. Kennedy as well as the Senate.
   Bentsen believes he and Dukakis will take Texas and its trove of
29 electoral votes as they campaign against adopted Texan George
Bush.
   ``I think it will be close. I think it will be tough, but I
think we'll win it,'' Bentsen said.
   ``Vamos a ver,'' he said in Spanish for ``We're going to see.''
</TEXT>
