<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Airliner-LastWords     07-14 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Last Words,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says Last Words To Airbus Pilot Were `Have A Nice Day'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-UN, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Shortly before Flight 655 was shot out of the
sky above the Persian Gulf on July 3, the Bandar Abbas tower had
these words of cheer for the departed Iran Air flight with 290
people aboard: ``Have a nice day.''
   Flight 655 responded: ``Thank you. Good day.''
   Tower: ``Good day.''
   That was at 10:24 a.m.
   Then nothing.
   Iran presented Thursday to the Security Council what it said was
a 14-minute transcript of communications in English between the
Iranian Airbus and control towers in Bandar Abbas, where it took
off; Tehran, where it originated, and Dubai in the United Arab
Emirates, its destination.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali-Akbar Velayati, said the USS
Vincennes must have heard the same communications, which clearly
identified the craft as a civilian airliner. Velayati said the
plane is identified, its altitude and course given, its destination
known and its transponder was on and transmitting its identity on
an internationally recognized civilian channel.
   ``Based on these easily verifiable facts,'' Valayati said, ``USS
Vincennes had well over 14 minutes _ and not four minutes as
American officials have claimed _ of prior knowledge that the
target was a civilian airliner on a scheduled flight from Bandar
Abbas to Dubai.''
   The transcript begins at 10:10 a.m., Bandar Abbas time, when the
pilot requests permission to start up his engine.
   The tower asked the pilot to make sure his transponder was
turned on and the pilot said it was.
   The plane took off at 10:17 a.m. for Dubai _ seven minutes after
the initial contact with the tower.
   The last communication between the pilot and Bandar Abbas tower
was recorded at 10:24 a.m., a routine exchange when the pilot did
not report any unusual or emergency condition.
   Vice President George Bush told the council the Vincennes' crew
sent seven unaswered warnings to the airliner before shooting it
down, believing it to be an F-14 on an attack course.
   ``One question that needs to be seriously examined,'' Velayati
said, ``is whether the captain of the USS Vincennes actually warned
its target that it intended to shoot ... or whether it simply
decided to shoot on a target which was admittedly unidentified at
the very least.''
</TEXT>
