<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Teamsters     07-14 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tight Race Seen in Selection of Successor to Presser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackie Presser's handpicked choice to succeed
him and the International Brotherhood of Teamsters' top official in
New England are locked in what labor sources say is a tight race
for the union's presidency.
   The Teamsters' 17-member General Executive Board meets here
Friday to pick a successor to Presser, who died last Saturday
following 18 months of treatment for cancer. Presser, 61, had been
the Teamsters' president since 1983.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, several sources said the
next Teamsters' president may get the post with a margin of only
one vote.
   Weldon Mathis, the Teamsters' secretary-treasurer and acting
president since May under an appointment from Presser, was expected
months ago to win election easily to the top job upon Presser's
death.
   But that was before a large rank-and-file rebellion over terms
of the union's two largest contracts with United Parcel Service and
the interstate trucking industry. Both were declared ratified even
though they were voted down by a majority of the covered members.
   Mathis is on the executive board along with 16 Teamster vice
presidents, many of whom at some time during the past two months
had seen themselves as succeeding Presser.
   In the past week, the competition to lead the nation's largest
union _ one in every 75 American workers is a Teamster, for a
membership of 1.6 million _ has evolved into a two-man race between
Mathis and William J. McCarthy of Boston, sources close to the
union said Thursday.
   Forces aligned with 70-year-old Joseph Trerotola of New York,
the union's ranking vice president and head of its East Coast
operations since 1969, have united behind McCarthy, sources said
Thursday.
   ``The Presser forces have lined up behind Mathis and the
Trerotola forces have lined up behind McCarthy,'' one source said.
``Everyone's reading is that it is real close.''
   McCarthy, 68, is said by several sources to have the support of
at least seven board members other than himself.
   Mathis, 62, whose career with the Teamsters began in Atlanta, is
believed to have an equal number, although one source said he has
``solidified support since May.''
   Another source described the contest as ``pretty close'' but
added that all 17 board members appeared to have made up their
minds on which way they would vote when they were last together at
Presser's funeral Tuesday in Cleveland.
   Breaking union tradition, McCarthy has been an outspoken critic
of the new three-year National Master Freight Agreement covering
some 200,000 Teamsters in the trucking industry.
   According to one source, Mathis offered during a board meeting
two weeks ago in Montreal to support McCarthy for the No. 2 job but
McCarthy declined.
   Whatever the count is in the closed-door meeting Friday, the
Teamsters are expected to follow their customary practice and
announce a unanimous vote for the winner when it all is over.
   That is what happened in 1983 when Presser was elected over Don
Peters, a veteran Teamster official in Chicago, to succeed Roy
Williams upon Williams' 10-year prison sentence on a conviction of
attempting to bribe a U.S. senator.
   Officially, the union is mum on the power struggle. Duke Zeller,
a spokesman for the union, said the only item on the agenda is
naming a new president and, possibly, a new secretary-treasurer.
   ``Historically, it goes pretty quickly,'' Zeller said. ``But
anything can happen.''
   The selection will occur just two weeks after the government
filed a suit seeking to place control of the entire union under a
court-appointed trustee, saying all of its top officials have
allowed the Teamsters to be controlled by leaders of organized
crime families.
   Among the allegations in the suit are that mob bosses in Chicago
and New York were the forces behind elevating Williams to the
union's presidency in 1981 and Presser to the post in 1983.
   A federal criminal court jury in May found that the government
lacked sufficient proof of that and attorneys for the union have
vehemently argued their is no organized crime influence at the top
of the union.
   At the time of his death, Presser was awaiting trial on federal
charges of labor racketeering and embezzlement in connection with
an alleged payroll-padding scheme at a Cleveland local that he also
headed. He had pleaded innocent to the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
