<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru a0741 07-14 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Leaders Arrive for First Meeting Since Summit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 12 to CORRECT spelling of Honecker and FIX
Zhivkov's name to begin with uppercase letter, picks up graf 13 `It
was...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of five Warsaw Pact countries
arrived Thursday to join Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in a
two-day summit expected to focus on reductions in nuclear and
conventional weapons.
   The meeting Friday and Saturday was to be the first of the
political-consultative council of the Warsaw Treaty Organization
since the U.S.-Soviet summit that ended June 2 in Moscow.
   The session will be Gorbachev's first opportunity to brief his
fellow communist leaders on his meeting with President Reagan. The
superpower leaders exchanged ratified copies of a treaty to ban
short- and medium-range nuclear weapons, most of which are deployed
in Europe.
   Enactment of the accord focuses new attention on long-stalled
efforts to reduce conventional forces in Europe, and Gorbachev
indicated that would be a priority item on the agenda of the Warsaw
Pact meeting.
   Talks on conventional force levels are to resume in Vienna this
fall, and Gorbachev suggested upon his arrival in Poland on Monday
that informal talks be held to search for a new starting point that
could lead to progress.
   ``Poland and the U.S.S.R., as parties to the Warsaw Treaty,
attach special importance to the quickest possible inauguration of
negotiations on the reduction of armed forces and conventional
armaments in Europe,'' said a communique issued by the two
countries on Thursday as Gorbachev concluded a four-day tour of
Poland in advance of the summit.
   Both countries are ``resolutely in favor of removing
disproportions and asymmetries existing in this area (and) are
ready for a realistic and constructive dialogue on the subject,''
the communique added.
   The NATO countries contend that communist forces hold a
dangerous two-to-one advantage tanks and artillery deployed in the
border regions separating East and West Europe.
   In a speech to parliament Monday, the first day of his six-day
visit to Poland, Gorbachev proposed withdrawing an unspecified
number of ``analagous'' Warsaw Pact air forces if NATO agreed not
to deploy 72, U.S.-built, F-16 fighter-jets in Italy.
   Speculation that the Warsaw Pact may be preparing for a dramatic
force pullback was raised in Washington last week, when a U.S.
State Department official said intelligence reports indicated the
Soviet Union was preparing to remove some or all of its 65,000
troops in Hungary.
   Joining Gorbachev and Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski for
the Warsaw Pact meeting are leaders from the other five pact
nations.
   Romanian leader Nicholae Ceaucescu, Czechoslovak leader Milos
Jakes, Bulgarian leader Todor Zhivkov, East German leader Erich
Honecker and Hungarian leader Karoly Grosz all arrived in Warsaw
late Thursday.
   It was Warsaw's turn to host the annual session of the communist
defense alliance founded in this Polish capital in 1955.
   The pact has been showing a greater degree of diversity in
recent years, with members taking divergent courses in response to
Gorbachev's program of ``perestroika,'' or reform.
   The meeting of Eastern European chiefs comes barely two weeks
after the Soviet Union's 19th Communist Party conference, which
endorsed an extension of Gorbachev's political and economic reforms.
   Poland and Hungary tend to be the pact's most enthusiastic
backers of reform. Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria are taking a more a
cautious approach, while East Germany shows only grudging interest
in conducting similar reforms.
   Romania, where power is concentrated almost entirely in the
hands of Ceaucescu, is conspicuously out of step with the reform
trend and sharply critical of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
