<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 2229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gore-Debt     07-14 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore-Debt,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Pays Off Debt Without Dukakis' Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, whose
Democratic presidential campaign fell flat outside the South, has
raised enough money to pay off his more than $2 million campaign
debt, a spokesman said Thursday.
   Gore was celebrating the achievement _ done without help from
successful Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis' campaign _ at a
dinner with major fund raisers at the Tennessee governor's mansion
in Nashville Thursday evening.
   Mike Kopp, Gore's press secretary, said the defunct campaign
raised more than $1 million in contributions and is due to receive
the balance needed to retire the debt in federal campaign money
matching the contributions.
   Gore owed $1.5 million, based on his latest Federal Election
Commission report on June 20. But Kopp said the campaign calculated
the final amount owed would be $2.1 million.
   ``We have as of this evening cash on hand of a little over $1
million,'' Kopp said. ``A lot of that came in overnight express
packages this morning.''
   Kopp said between 170 and 200 Gore fund raisers, each of whom
raised anywhere from $5,000 to more than $40,000 against the debt,
were attending the dinner and private concert by Gore supporter and
country singer Johnny Cash and his band. Also providing
entertainment was singer Crystal Gayle.
   Gore withdrew from the presidential race following a poor third
place showing in the New York primary. He scored victories in his
native South on Super Tuesday but was unable to match them
elsewhere.
</TEXT>
