<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-14 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEECH MOUNTAIN, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this ski resort town
believe a Garbage Day celebration is a great way to have a day go
to waste.
   They dressed up like trash, brought along bags of trash and
smelled trash during the sixth annual celebration Wednesday.
   The event began when the western North Carolina town was
incorporated and needed a garbage truck. The first truck was
christened with a bottle of champagne.
   Since then the celebration has continued each year with picnics,
costumes and contests with other area sanitation departments.
   ``It's crazy and I do crazy things like this,'' said Blanche
Ross, a schoolteacher on vacation from Orlando, Fla., who was
dressed as a bag of trash.
   Ms. Ross won first place for being dressed as the most
interesting bag of trash.
   ``I've put a lot of reusable items in (the costume) _ things
like an old bra that can be used as a slingshot, a mouse trap,
toilet paper and old cartons and things like that,'' she said. ``I
was really raunchy.''
   ``It was great it rained,'' added Sheila Maddux, executive
director of the Beech Mountain Chamber of Commerce. ``It made
everything smell a lot better.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEDFORD, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Motor Vehicles Division has
decided that no matter what the word ``petard'' means in French,
it's OK for Bill and Donna Brewster to use it on their Mercedes.
   Mrs. Brewster operates a business by the same name.
   Someone complained to the division that petard is a French
colloquialism meaning to break wind. The division ordered the
Brewsters to turn in their plate because it carried ``offensive and
vulgar connotations.''
   Brewster appealed.
   Armed with a pair of dictionaries, Brewster argued before a
state hearings officer April 14 that although the word may have
vulgar roots, petard today is neither vulgar nor offensive.
   ``We got a letter,'' Brewster said Tuesday. ``Seven pages of
gobbledygook, but we won.''
   The Webster's New World Dictionary College Edition defines
petard as an explosive device used in ancient times to force an
opening in a wall or gate, and a firecracker. However, the Latin
and French roots of the word do mean to break wind, the dictionary
adds.
   But the dictionary also notes the use in Shakespeare's Hamlet of
the phrase, ``hoist with one's own petard,'' meaning to be caught
in one's own trap.
</TEXT>
