<DOCNO> AP880714-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1901EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gorbachev-Thinkers     07-14 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Thinkers,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Intellectuals Appeal to Gorbachev for More Openness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish intellectuals and scientists met
with Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Thursday and asked him for more
artistic freedom, scentific cooperation, and a renewed Marxist
dialogue with religion.
   The most moving part of the two-hour session with the Soviet
leader came when a Polish physicist said his father was executed in
the Stalinist purge of the Polish Communist Party in the 1930s.
   He thanked Gorbachev for a decision to erect a monument in
Moscow to victims of Stalinist repression.
   Among those attending the meeting in the newly renovated
ballroom of Warsaw's Royal Castle were historians, scientists, film
makers, philosophers, journalists, musicians and critics _ about
300 of Poland's intellectual elite.
   The meeting was broadcast live on national television.
   The group included a smattering of moderate supporters of the
Polish opposition movement. Participating were Marcin Krul,
publisher of Poland's only legal private magazine; and Andrzej
Stemalchowski, president of the Catholic Intellectuals Club of
Warsaw.
   Also attending were composer-conductor Krzysztof Penderecki,
film maker Krzysztof Zanussi, actor Daniel Olbrychski and
controversial Marxist philosopher-economist Adam Schaff.
   Historian Bogdan Sucholdowski, chairman of the national
Commission of Culture, presided over the session.
   Gorbachev first gave an off-the-cuff monologue on
``perestroika,'' his program of economic and social reforms which
he said is intended to improve the lives of everyday people.
   He spoke in Russian. Many Polish intellectuals speak Russian,
and some participants did not require earphones to listen to a
translation.
   Physicist Jan Rychlewski then took the floor. He suggested that
socialist countries each concentrate their research in a few
limited fields to avoid being left behind by the West.
   Speaking in emotional tones, Rychlewski then apologized for
bringing up a topic ``which I ought not mention.''
   ``In the name of my family, in the name of my community, I would
like to thank the 19th CPSU (Communist Party of the Soviet Union)
conference and the delegates to that conference here, for the
decision to erect in Moscow the monument to the victims of
repression,'' Rychlewski said. ``Among those victims was also my
father, a Polish patriot and a Polish communist.
   ``We don't know where his grave is. But now we will treat this
monument as his grave. We will have a place to lay flowers.''
   Polish television showed Gorbachev nodding acknowlegement.
   Film maker Zanussi started his remarks by praising the Polish
film tradition, including the dean of Polish moviemaking, Andrzej
Wajda, who lionized the now-banned Solidarity trade movement in his
film ``Man of Iron.'' Wajda apparently was not present at
Thursday's meeting.
   ``The chances to make films expressing reality can only occur
when there is creative freedom,'' said Zanussi. ``We have often not
had such conditions.''
   Wojciech Zukrowski, chairman of the official Polish Writers
Union, said publishing long-banned books would quickly fill in the
``blank spots'' in history that Polish and Soviet historians are
now re-evaluating.
   Philosopher Janusz Kuczynski suggested to Gorbachev that the
Marxist concept of religion as the ``opium of the masses'' should
be redefined and called for reopening the dialogue between Marxism
and Christianity. The Catholic Church continues to play a central
role in Polish society, despite the officially atheistic stance of
the ruling Communist Party.
   Stelmachowski, the Catholic club president, speaking from home
after the meeting, said he found the discussion interesting but
that Gorbachev's brief reply promising written responses in a
volume to be published later ``left a feeling of hunger.''
   He said he was vaguely reminded of the trip to Warsaw in the
19th century of Czar Alexander II. The czar promised reforms but in
the end repressed Polish aspirations after a popular revolt against
Russian rule in 1863.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
