<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CBS-NBCPolls     07-14 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS-NBC Polls,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Poll Has Dukakis Drawing Even in Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis pulled even with Vice
President George Bush in Texas after naming Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas as his Democratic running mate, CBS News reported Thursday
night.
   The poll of 580 registered voters on Tuesday and Wednesday found
48 percent supporting Dukakis to 44 percent for Bush. The margin of
error was plus or minus four percentage points, making the race a
dead heat.
   Polls that were taken before Dukakis selected Bentsen on Tuesday
have found a big Bush lead in Texas, but showed the lead narrowing
to a dead heat if Bentsen were chosen. The CBS poll confirmed that
outcome.
   In another poll Tuesday, Dukakis led Bush by 10 points
nationally, a margin roughly in line with other recent national
surveys. The new poll, by NBC News and The Wall Street Journal, was
done before Dukakis chose Bentsen.
   Dukakis' selection of Bentsen was seen as a home-state challenge
to Bush, who maintains an apartment in Houston. But the CBS Texas
poll found that 57 percent of respondents do not think of Bush as a
``real Texan.''
   Bush was rated favorably by 44 percent of Texas voters and
unfavorably by 33 percent. Dukakis had a lower favorable rating, 37
percent, but also a slightly lower unfavorable score, 28 percent.
   Bentsen did better than either, with a 55 percent favorable
rating and an unfavorable rating of only 15 percent. Moreover, 21
percent said having Bentsen on the ticket made them more likely to
vote for Dukakis.
   The Texans also said they favored Bentsen for re-election to the
Senate over Republican Rep. Beau Boulter, 64-20. But 61 percent
said Bentsen should withdraw from the Senate race now that he is to
run for vice president, even though Texas law allows him to seek
both seats.
   In the national poll by NBC and the Journal, Dukakis' 10-point
lead was 5 points lower than in an NBC-Journal poll a month ago.
The poll was conducted July 8-11 among 1,695 registered voters, and
had a three point error margin.
</TEXT>
