<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL     07-14 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Donations Down To $25,000 A Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL's bankruptcy trustee said Thursday
that more guests at the Heritage Grand Hotel and income from
Heritage USA's new water park are helping offset donations that
have plummeted to $25,000 a day.
   M.C. ``Red'' Benton said the water park and stepped-up business
at the hotel are bringing in about another $25,000 a day, but with
the dwindling donations, the PTL ministry is still falling short of
the $60,000 a day it needs to operate.
   The difference is coming from profits from the sale of PTL
property that was sold this spring, he said.
   Benton said another round of on-air appeals for donations will
begin soon to remind viewers of PTL's television viewers of the
need for money.
   The lowest donations have fallen is $22,000 a day, in late May,
Benton said. Increased on-the-air appeals got the donations
temporarily back up to about $100,000 a day, but they've steadily
declined ever since.
   Benton said efforts to find a buyer for Heritage USA continue.
The ministry is working with several interested buyers, including
Charlotte businessman George Shinn and ousted PTL founder Jim
Bakker, he said.
   Benton also has established a Friday deadline for a $50 million
deposit by Australian businessman Gavin Morehu, who has said he
plans to offer $200 million to buy Heritage USA.
   ``We're still waiting on somebody to come up with a deposit,''
he said Thursday.
   Benton said he asked Morehu to deposit the money in escrow as
evidence of ability to make good on the offer, and he probably
would grant an extension of two or three days if one is requested.
   Bruce French, director of sales and marketing at Heritage USA,
said the water park is averaging just below 1,000 people per day.
   ``We're particularly happy with the regional attendance,''
French said. ``In the past, we counted on our visitors to be the
bulk of our attendance. This year we've turned that around and
decided to market to the area.''
