<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 5thLd-Writethru a0822 07-14 1169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0822,1150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Seek to Patch Dukakis-Jackson Rift as Convention Nears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 13th graf with CBS poll in Texas</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson asked former President Carter on Thursday to play
peacemaker in his pre-convention dispute with Michael Dukakis,
saying, ``I simply want respect and responsibility'' after the long
run for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Dukakis, six days away from officially becoming his party's
nominee, said that despite the tension, he expects Jackson to join
him and running mate Lloyd Bentsen in a convention display of unity.
   Vice President George Bush needled Dukakis from afar, saying he
thought the governor could have shown ``a little more sensitivity''
toward his rival in the manner in which he announced his choice of
Bentsen. Bush also went to the United Nations where he made a
high-visibility defense of U.S. actions in shooting down an Iranian
airliner.
   While there is plenty of time to settle matters before the
convention opens next Monday, Jackson's complaints could wind up
threatening efforts by Dukakis and Democratic Party leaders to
stage a unified, harmonious party meeting.
   Dukakis told CBS News in an interview he tried but failed to
reach Jackson by phone on Tuesday to tell him of Bentsen's
selection. He said Jackson should take no offense from their
failure to make a connection.
   ``Obviously in a contest like this somebody wins and somebody
loses and I'm the guy who's won and it's my job to go out and pick
a running mate,'' said Dukakis.
   Asked if the convention audience would witness a final display
of Dukakis-Bentsen-Jackson unity, he said, ``I expect that you
will.''
   Jackson did not specify any issues he wanted Carter to mediate.
He said he was not seeking ``a personal apology'' for Dukakis'
failure to notify him before word got out that Bentsen had been
picked for the vice presidential slot on the ticket.
   In Chicago, at a news conference before boarding a bus caravan
for the convention, Jackson said he would ``exercise all of our
rights'' at the four-day meeting, and added it's an ``open
question'' whether he will challenge Bentsen's nomination in
Atlanta.
   Dukakis, his nomination assured, spent the day working on state
budget problems and burnishing his credentials as a governor who
cracks down on drugs. The Massachusetts governor visited two state
troopers shot during an undercover drug operation and signed a
state law requiring tougher sentences for cocaine dealers.
   ``We're serious about a war on drugs in this state,'' he said.
   Bentsen spent the day in the Senate. He told reporters that
easing the tension with Jackson was ``Governor Dukakis'
responsibility. ... I know he has a high regard for Rev. Jackson. I
assume he'll have a meeting with Jackson.''
   Meanwhile, CBS said a new survey in Texas indicates that Dukakis
has pulled even with Bush since naming Bentsen as his running mate,
a marked improvement in his standing. A poll of 580 registered
voters on Tuesday and Wednesday found 48 percent supporting Dukakis
to 44 percent for Bush. The margin of error was plus or minus four
percentage points, making the race a dead heat.
   Bert Lance, who has advised Jackson during the presidential
campaign, said he believed Dukakis' rival would eventually support
the party's ticket. ``It's in the best interest of Jesse Jackson,
in my opinion, to see a Democrat elected in November,'' said Lance,
who once served as Carter's federal budget director.
   Carter declined comment on Jackson's statements, and Dukakis'
aides sought to minimize the dispute.
   Democratic Party officials held a symbolic ribbon-cutting
ceremony to mark the transformation of the Omni hall into a
convention city, complete with a huge movable podium in pastel
shades _ designed to be more pleasing to the eye than the
traditional red, white and blue.
   But if the hammering and sawing was nearly finished, the
political maneuvering was in full swing.
   Black members of Congress predicted boisterous protests at the
convention over what they see as a snub to Jackson.
   But some of the lawmakers also said they would try to hold a
meeting with Dukakis aides or perhaps the governor himself next
week in an effort to repair the breach.
   ``Clearly the way Jesse Jackson was dealt with, on a personal
basis, looms as a monumental issue,'' said Rep. Ron Dellums,
D-Calif.
   Jackson's call on Carter _ a Georgian who has remained generally
out of the spotlight since his defeat in 1980 _ came as party
chairman Paul Kirk and other Democratic leaders appealed for unity
to prevent the convention from deteriorating into a prime-time tug
of war.
   Officials spread the word that Dukakis had called Jackson on
Wednesday, and a Jackson aide termed the call ``a good start'' at
repairing relations.
   Both Kirk and House Speaker Jim Wright, convention chairman,
urged unity on the bickering sides. Wright predicted a harmonious
convention that will unite all factions and ``demonstrate that our
party is ready to govern.''
   For the moment, at least, there seemed little harmony.
   The most recent round of acrimony began when Jackson _ who
wanted the second spot on the ticket for himself _ learned of
Bentsen's selection from a reporter on Tuesday morning.
   Jackson told reporters in Chicago that Dukakis aide Paul
Brountas apologized for the way the notification was handled.
   He said he had talked to Carter and ``he wants to serve in any
way he can.''
   But he said, ``I do not seek a personal apology. The progressive
wing of the Democratic party seeks inclusion.''
   ``The issue of my constituency is not about the timing of a
call,'' he said. ``We want inclusion in the party at every level.''
   Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan said of Wednesday's
Dukakis-Jackson phone call, ``The governor obviously made it clear
that it was his own intention for the Rev. Jackson and all of the
candidates to hear the news from no one else but the governor.''
Gearan characterized the conversation as friendly, but declined to
say whether the governor had apologized.
   Jackson spokesman Ron Brown termed Dukakis' gesture an
``important call and a good start'' toward healing relations, but
made it clear he expects there will be numerous conversations
between the two men in the days ahead.
   Bentsen went about his Senate rounds as usual, although the
jockeying already was beginning among Texas politicians eager to
replace him in Congress if he wins the vice presidency.
   Bush traveled to the United Nations to represent the United
States at a Security Council debate over the Navy's downing of a
civilian Iranian airliner in the Persian Gulf. He called the
incident a ``terrible human tragedy,'' but defended the actions of
the Navy commander who gave the order to fire, and said Iran shares
responsibility in the 290 deaths for sending its plane into a
battle region.
   Jackson has ordered aides to break off negotiations with Dukakis
forces over the party platform. Kirk, in Atlanta, said those talks
had not yet resumed, although he said aides to the two men had
spoken.
</TEXT>
