<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0820,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Signs Drug Sentencing Bills; Visits Shot Troopers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf with Gearan saying no meeting set Sunday;
INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf pvs with more Dukakis comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, saying Thursday that his
state is ``serious about a war on drugs,'' visited two state
troopers shot during an undercover drug operation and signed
tougher sentencing standards for cocaine dealers.
   Dukakis, only days away from accepting the Democratic
presidential nomination, spent most of Thursday working on state
budget problems while aides tried to ease the continuing tension
between their camp and Jesse Jackson.
   Spokesman Mark Gearan said a face-to-face meeting between
Dukakis and Jackson likely would be arranged after both arrive
Sunday in Atlanta for the Democratic National Convention. But he
said no such talk had been scheduled.
   Dukakis, in a broadcast interview, defended his choice of Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas as a running mate, despite Jackson's
interest in the job.
   ``Obviously in a contest like this somebody wins and somebody
loses and I'm the guy who's won and it's my job to go out and pick
a running mate,'' he said in an interview with CBS.
   However, asked if the convention audience would witness a final
display of Dukakis-Bentsen-Jackson unity, he said, ``I expect that
you will.''
   In Chicago, meanwhile, Jackson called on former President Carter
to play the role of peacemaker in his pre-convention dispute with
Dukakis. He did not say what specific issues he wanted Carter to
negotiate with Dukakis but said he was looking for ``meetings of
substance ... about the fundamental issues.''
   Spokesman Gearan said Dukakis spoke Wednesday afternoon with
Jackson, who has been described by aides as ``flabbergasted'' that
Dukakis did not inform him of the selection of Bentsen as his
running mate until after word of the choice had been reported in
the news media.
   ``It was a good, friendly conversation,'' Gearan said.
   Later, he declined to answer directly when asked if the Dukakis
campaign felt it necessary to bring in Carter or any other mediator.
   ``Our campaigns have been talking throughout this process and we
are confident they will continue to talk and that we are going to
have a unified convention,'' Gearan said.
   The Dukakis campaign has said Dukakis tried to personally inform
all of the other candidates for the vice presidential nomination
about the selection of Bentsen early Tuesday morning but was unable
to reach Jackson and Ohio Sen. John Glenn before the selection was
reported.
   Dukakis declined to answer reporters' questions outside the two
hospitals where he visited the troopers who are recovering from
gunshot wounds suffered Wednesday night.
   Aides said he had already been scheduled to sign the
drug-sentencing bills Thursday and decided to do so at Boston City
Hospital after learning of the shootings.
   ``We're serious about a war on drugs in this state,'' the
governor said before he signed the bills on the hood of a state
police cruiser. ``We're working at it.''
   The measures lower from 28 grams to 14 grams the amount of
cocaine possession needed to trigger a mandatory minimum three-year
sentence, increase the minimum sentence for possession of 28 grams
or more to five years and set a minimum 10-year sentence for
possession of 100 or more grams of cocaine.
   The laws also increase penalties for first offenders convicted
of possessing cocaine with intent to distribute and for those
convicted of selling the drug to minors.
   Back at the Statehouse, Dukakis met with staff and legislators
as he looked to trim as much as $200 million in spending before
signing the state's fiscal 1989 budget. He also was awaiting
legislative approval of a plan to balance the fiscal 1988 budget,
which is $370 million in the red pending approval of the plan.
Aides said Dukakis hoped to sign both spending plans on Saturday, a
day before he heads to the convention.
</TEXT>
