<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-ShipAttack     07-14 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Ship Attack,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian's Conviction Opens Way For U.S. Extradition Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian believed linked to a deadly
attack on a Greek cruise ship was convicted on false passport
charges Thursday, clearing the way for a U.S. extradition request
to be heard.
   Greek authorities have said the submachine gun and hand grenade
raid on the City of Poros cruise ship, which killed nine people and
injured 98 last Monday, may have been aimed at hijacking the vessel
in an effort to gain Mohammed Rashid's release from prison.
   Rashid, 34, a self-proclaimed ``fighter'' for the Palestine
Liberation Organization, is wanted by the United States for murder,
accused of planting a bomb aboard a Pan Am jumbo jet in 1982 that
killed a Japanese teen-ager and injured 15 people.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said in Washington
on Thursday, ``We strongly believe that the most effective way to
fight terrorism in this case is to expeditiously begin extradition
proceedings against Rashid.''
   In new developments Thursday in the ship attack:
   _A 21-year-old Frenchwoman sought by Greek authorities in
connection with the attack, Isabelle Bismuth, was identified
through dental records as being among the nine people killed,
according to informed sources in Paris, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Her mother told the French press earlier her daughter was a
secretary on vacation in Greece and not a terrorist. A man shown in
a picture playing cards with Ms. Bismuth on the ship is one of
three men sought as attack suspects.
   _A Danish couple who were aboard the ship two days before it was
attacked claim to have met one of the suspected terrorists then,
the Danish newspaper B.T. reported in its Friday edition.
   The report indicated the terrorists scouted the liner on an
earlier cruise before striking. The Danish couple spoke on
condition of anonymity. The Danish man, who knows some Arabic, said
21-year-old Mohammed Zozad and two Arabic-speaking friends of
Zozad's stood out among the nearly 500 passengers, who were mainly
tourists from Northern Europe.
   In the case of Rashid, Greece says it is considering the U.S.
extradition request but that Rashid would have to serve his Greek
sentence before he could be sent to the United States.
   He began serving a seven-month jail sentence after a three-judge
panel found him guilty of entering Greece on a forged Syrian
passport on May 26.
   He appealed the sentence but presiding Judge Mihalis Margaritis
ordered his continued detention at Korydallos prison, in nearby
Piraeus.
   Now that Rashid has been tried on the Greek charge, proceedings
can begin on the U.S. extradition request. He cannot be extradited
before serving his full prison term.
   ``They are trying to involve my client in these crimes. He has
no relation to these violent crimes the Americans are accusing him
of, especially the recent one,'' Rashid's lawyer, Spyros Fitrakis,
told the court.
   ``As far as the ship attack is concerned the Americans are
trying to convince people the Palestinians did so that I would be
released. This is not true,'' Rashid testified.
   He said his forged passport was given to him by ``my PLO
superiors.''
   ``I am a soldier in the Palestine Liberation Army and a member
of the PLO,'' Rashid said.
   He was arrested by police at Athens airport May 30 on a tip-off
from the U.S. Embassy.
   ``I was passing through Greece on a secret mission,'' Rashid
told the court. He would not say where he was headed.
   The sweltering courtroom was packed with reporters and police.
Dozens of police officers cradling automatic weapons checked people
entering the courtroom.
   Police officer Matthaios Gonias testified that Rashid was
identified by his fingerprints and that the defendant had served
three years of a six-year sentence imposed in 1973 for smuggling
just under 40 pounds of hashish into Greece.
   In Baghdad, Iraq, on Wednesday, a spokesman for PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat said the group condemned the ship attack.
   On Wednesday also, in Beirut, Lebanon, a group calling itself
The Organization of the Martyrs of the Popular Revolution of
Palestine claimed responsibility for the attack. There was no way
to independently authenticate the claim by this previously unknown
group.
</TEXT>
