<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HomelessProtest     07-14 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Protest,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Advocate Scales Broadcast Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX21</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Homeless Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless advocate scaled a 767-foot
broadcast tower Thursday and vowed to remain there until the
federal government expands housing opportunities for low-income
Americans.
   Wayne Vorhees, a volunteer with the Community for Creative
Non-Violence, climbed the tower in northwest Washington and, after
waiting for winds to subside, unfurled a 50-foot banner reading
``Housing Now.''
   Two of his companions were arrested.
   John Muirhead, 24, of Clinton, N.Y., was apprehended after
abandoning his attempt to join Vorhees at the top of the tower,
which is owned by television station WFTY and used by that station,
city police and various radio stations.
   A second man, Harold Moss, was arrested after police saw him
speaking by walkie-talkie with Vorhees after Vorhees scaled the
steel communications tower.
   District of Columbia police inspector Ed Spurlock said both men
have been charged with unlawful entry. The misdemeanor charge
carries a maximum penalty of six months in jail and a $400 fine.
   The ages and hometowns for Vorhees and Moss were not immediately
available.
   Earlier in the day, CCNV leader Mitch Snyder and 36 of his
followers were arrested when they blocked traffic near the Capitol
to draw attention to the plight of the homeless. During that
protest, a ``Housing Now'' banner was draped outside the Longworth
House Office Building. All were charged with obstructing and
impeding passage on government grounds, police said.
   The dramatic tower climb was staged in an effort to focus
attention on America's current housing shortage, Moss said. ``Right
now, there's a frightening painful shortage of affordable housing,
not just in Washington, D.C. but all across America,'' Moss said
shortly before his arrest.
   ``It's not a matter of who's in the White House,'' Moss said.
``Homelessness is caused more and more by a lack of housing.''
   Moss said Vorhees has enough supplies to stay on the tower for
up to five days. Police said they're considering ways to get the
protester down, but did not reveal details.
   As Vorhees rested on a platform atop the tower, a police
helicopter circled nearby.
   Figures compiled by the Congressional Budget Office indicate
that the Department of Housing of Urban Development budget _ the
main source of federal housing assistance _ has been slashed 82
percent during the Reagan administration.
   Rental prices also are being driven up because many federally
subsidized low-income units have been demolished or abandoned in
the last eight years, with housing vouchers replacing maintenance
of these structures.
   A recent Harvard University study indicates that there are now
about 1 million more poor households than there are available
low-income housing units.
</TEXT>
