<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nicaragua-OAS     07-14 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-OAS,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tunnermann Blasts US, Wins Little Sympathy from OAS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann, faced
with a U.S. order to leave the country, accused the Reagan
administration Thursday of violating the Organization of American
States charter but he won little more than a polite hearing from
his OAS colleagues.
   Tunnermann left unclear whether he will abide by the expulsion
order, saying he will make his position clear at noon Friday, a few
hours before the deadline for his departure from U.S. territory.
   After a meeting of the OAS permanent council that lasted just
under two hours, the only expression of support Tunnermann could
claim was a statement by Mexican Ambassador Antonio de Icaza.
   Icaza, who spoke in the name of seven other governments, noted
that OAS provisions ensure that the 32 member states have the right
to attend meetings of the organization, ``independent of their
bilateral relations with the host government, underscoring the
right of all to full representation in the organization.''
   But Icaza also said that these rights are inadeqautely protected
under a 1975 agreement governing U.S. obligations as the host
country for the OAS. ``As a consequence,'' he said, ``it is
necessary to fill this legal vacuum.''
   The majority of the delegates sat impassively through the
session, apparently preferring to stay aloof from the latest
chapter in the seven-year history of acrimony between the United
States and Nicaragua.
   Much of the meeting was taken up by a heated exchange between
the U.S. and Nicaraguan delegates, with each accusing the other of
prolonging the conflict in Nicaragua.
   Tunnermann stopped short of asking for a formal endorsement of
his position, pointing out that he had requested the Thursday
meeting only to inform fellow delegates of his position.
   The Reagan administration on Tuesday ordered Tunnermann and
seven colleagues to leave the country within 72 hours, a day after
Nicaragua expelled eight American diplomats from Managua, including
U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton.
   The administration said the action was taken for retaliatory
purposes and, in the case of Tunnermann and military attache Major
Pedro Sampson, for violations of their privileges of residence in
the United States.
   The U.S. ambassador to the OAS, Richard MacCormack, told the
delegates that Tunnermann and Sampson had engaged in ``certain
activities'' which the United States found objectionable but he
declined to spell them out.
   He said the administration had deferred expelling Tunnermann and
Sampson earlier ``in order to avoid giving the Nicaragua government
a pretext for taking the kinds of actions it perpetrated this
week.''
   He added that the explusion of the American diplomats from
Managua ``removed the basis for such restraint on the part of the
United States.''
   The Reagan administration has said it expects Tunnermann and his
colleagues to comply with the expulsion order but the envoy was
non-committal when asked by reporters about his plans.
   President Reagan said Tunnermann will have a ``big surprise''
awaiting him if the envoy decides to ignore the U.S. demand.
   Tunnermann, who serves as both ambassador to the United States
and the OAS, said his government has considered taking his case
against the administration to U.S. courts.
   His main defense was that the United States has no right to
refuse accreditation to envoys sent to Washington by OAS member
states.
   ``It is a sovereign decision of our states, that the host
country must respect, to designate its representation before the
permanent council,'' he said.
</TEXT>
