<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-14 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Hot, Hazy Day for Most of the Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hot, humid conditions dominated from the Plains east to the
Atlantic Coast on Thursday, while showers and thunderstorms were
scattered from the northeast parts of the Great Lakes into the
middle Mississippi Valley.
   Chicago's temperature reached 99 degrees Thursday afternoon,
tying the record high for the date in 1976, and temperatures were
in the 80s or 90s across much of the nation. In the desert
Southwest and the high Plains of Kansas, temperatures reached about
100 degrees.
   The strongest thunderstorms developed in northern and western
New York state and across much of New England, where cooler air
from the north clashed with the warm, humid air mass over the upper
Ohio Valley.
   Thunderstorms blew down trees and power lines at Amsterdam,
N.Y., Thursday afternoon causing power outages, and strong winds
accompanying thurderstorms uprooted trees, overturned a trailer and
downed power lines at Syracuse, N.Y.
   A severe thunderstorm watch was posted for parts of New York
state, Pennsylvania, Vermont, New Hampshire, Maine, Massachusetts,
Connecticut and Rhode Island.
   Showers were scattered from southern Iowa through central
Illinois into central Indiana. Rainfall amounts ranged from a
quarter-inch to three-quarters of an inch across the region.
   Thunderstorms were widespread across the southeastern United
States, but were spotty from north-central Colorado into the
Nebraska Panhandle and across central New Mexico.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Mullan, Idaho, to 106 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz. The
low in the nation Thursday morning was 35 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   Friday's forecast called for continued heat and humidity in the
southern, central and eastern parts of the nation. Showers and
thunderstorms were expected across the upper Great Lakes region as
well as southern Georgia and Florida.
   High temperatures in the 90s were forecast across much of the
nation, and in the 70s and 80s along the California coast and from
the northwest Great Lakes region into the upper Ohio Valley through
New England.
   Highs should reach 100 to 105 degrees across the central Plains
into north-central Texas, and across the Rio Grande Valley.
Temperatures were expected to soar to 105 to 115 degrees in the
desert southwest.
</TEXT>
