<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EmbassyHostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0744 07-14 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Embassy Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0744,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Lebanese Gunman at Embassy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with newly released details of
capture, ID of gunman. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese gunman inside the Libyan
Embassy held off police for nearly 12 hours Thursday before he fell
asleep and authorities rushed him, officials said. No shots were
fired and no one was injured.
   Police identified the arrested man as El-Ibrahim Edelbi, 22. He
had pulled out a revolver Thursday morning after embassy personnel
refused to grant him a visa to travel to Libya, authorities said.
   Edelbi escaped from a prison in Goettingen on July 8 with a
Turkish inmate who has since been recaptured, authorities said.
Edelbi was serving a three-year prison term for assault and had
been at the prison for 18 months.
   Police said Edelbi told officers he had eaten nothing since he
escaped.
   ``He had become very weak since his escape and looked exhausted
during the negotiations (with authorities),'' said Ulrich Fischer,
head of the Bonn police team that captured Edelbi.
   Fischer's team watched Edelbi through a video camera that is a
normal part of security on the first floor of the Libyan Embassy.
   At about 9:15 p.m. (3:15 p.m. EDT), police noticed Edelbi had
fallen asleep inside the first-floor visitors' room, and they
rushed into the building, Fischer said.
   ``Finally, he just fell asleep from exhaustion,'' said Fischer.
``He did not offer us any resistance.''
   Police said there were no injuries among several embassy workers
who had been trapped on upper floors since the siege began early
Thursday and that no shots were fired.
   Police said they did not know where Edelbi obtained his gun.
   Edelbi was taken to a local hospital for examination, officials
said.
   Police, alerted to the situation at 10 a.m. (4 a.m. EDT),
negotiated with him by telephone and through a metal-bar door at
the building's entrance.
   ``He demanded that he not be returned to prison. He said he
wanted to go to Libya because the Libyans always help the
Lebanese,'' said Fischer.
   In the face-to-face negotiations, the gunman kept himself at a
distance of about three yards to avoid being grabbed by police
officers on the other side of the metal gate, police spokesman Hans
Georg Classen said.
   Classen said Bonn police did not know how long Edelbi had lived
in West Germany, whether he had relatives in this country, or any
other details about him other than his prison record.
   Classen said a number of embassy employees had been on floors
above the gunman, who was alone on the ground floor of the
five-story building. But he did not know how many workers had been
in the building.
   They could not leave because the gunman controlled access to
stairways and doors.
   Shortly after the standoff began, heavily armed police officers
wearing combat gear climbed through a second-story window into the
embassy, known as the Libyan People's Bureau.
   Omar K. Bukhries, head of the embassy, had given police
permission to enter the building, Classen said. He said Bukhries
was able to escape through a side door shortly after the standoff
began.
   Other police armed with automatic rifles and wearing bulletproof
vests surrounded the building.
   The embassy is on a quiet, tree-lined street in Bad Godesberg,
an area of Bonn where many embassies are located.
</TEXT>
