<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0767 07-14 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Asks Former President Carter to Mediate Between Camps</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: Dukakis' campaign, to UPDATE with
more comment from Dukakis camp; INSERTS 2 grafs after 15th graf
pvs, ``I simply, with more Jackson comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson accepted an apology Thursday from a
Michael Dukakis aide over the handling of the No. 2 spot on the
Democratic ticket and asked former President Carter to mediate
tensions between the two camps.
   Jackson sounded a conciliatory note after the call from Paul
Brountas, Dukakis' campaign chairman, who offered an apology and
detailed a series of mistakes that led to a delay in Jackson's
being told that Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen had been selected Dukakis'
running mate.
   ``We accept that explanation,'' Jackson said at a news
conference before leaving on a three-day bus caravan to the
national convention in Atlanta.
   Asked about Carter's response to his request, Jackson said, ``He
wants to serve in any way he can.''
   Dukakis' campaign manager Susan Estrich said she knew nothing
about the proposal. Later, campaign spokesman Mark Gearan, asked
whether the Dukakis forces believed a mediator was needed, said,
``Our campaigns have been talking throughout this process and we
are confident they will continue to talk and that we are going to
have a unified convention.''
   Dukakis himself did not apologize during a telephone call
Wednesday, but Jackson said he did not ask for, and would not seek,
a ``personal apology.''
   Jackson learned of Dukakis' selection of Bentsen from reporters
as he arrived in Washington Tuesday morning. He received a call
from Dukakis about an hour later and before the public announcement
that afternoon.
   Dukakis said Wednesday he tried unsuccessfully to reach Jackson
but word got out.
   Dukakis' plans for a show of unity have been clouded by
Jackson's hints that he might challenge the selection of the Texas
senator. Jackson supporters have threatened protests, and some
Dukakis backers also criticized the treatment of Jackson by the
Dukakis camp.
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., a prominent Dukakis supporter once
viewed as a possible running mate to the Massachusetts governor,
said Dukakis blundered in not notifying Jackson earlier that he
wouldn't be on the ticket.
   And New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, a prominent Democrat, said
``Dukakis is not required to anything for Jesse'' but added: ``I
think if he wants to win, he should.''
   At the news conference, Jackson insisted ``we will exercise all
our rights'' during the convention next week and said it's still an
``open question'' whether he will allow his name to be entered in
nomination for vice president.
   ``It is an open convention, we have not yet made a decision
about all the strategies we will employ,'' he said.
   Despite those statements, Jackson sent generally conciliatory
signals to the Dukakis camp, saying ``the issue for my constituency
is not about the time of a call.''
   ``I simply want the respect and responsibility,'' said Jackson,
who emphasized that he wants ``meetings of substance between now
and then about the fundamental issues.''
   Later, after his bus caravan arrived in Indianapolis, Jackson
said ``we're not going to give up on communications'' with the
Dukakis camp. He said he expected the two would meet ``at some
appropriate time.''
   ``We hope in the next three or four days that matters will be
resolved,'' he said at his news conference in Indianapolis.
   Earlier, Jackson said he has not set all of his strategies for
next week, but wants Carter to play ``a real role'' in mediating
between the two camps. He telephoned the former president Thursday
to ask his help.
   ``He understands the equation,'' said Jackson, who added that
Carter ``has earned the respect of all of us.''
   ``Then at that time, we'll look at the next step of our
challenge,'' said Jackson, who plans to meet with top advisers to
discuss convention rules and determine the best steps for next week.
   Jackson's reaction will be key at convention next week and on
Thursday he displayed both hurt feelings about his treatment during
the Bentsen selection and determination to continue talks with
Dukakis' forces.
   ``Inclusion is the watchword,'' Jackson said. ``We want
inclusion in the party at every level.
   ``As we seek to resolve the creative tensions within our party,
we are determined to set and keep a moral tone,'' that excludes
battles over personal issues, he said.
   Jackson said he hopes his forces came resume the stalled
negotiations with the Dukakis' camp on the party platform, but said
his backers ``will be debating minority planks'' at the convention.
   He said negotiations with Dukakis ``must be built based on
shared power and shared responsibility.''
   Asked about other issues he might want to settle with Dukakis,
Jackson insisted his fundamental role as a force in the party was
in question because ``at this point we're disconnected from the
process.''
   After the the stop in Indianapolis, the bus caravan will travel
to Louisville, Ky.; Nashville, Tenn., Chattanooga, Tenn. and
finally Atlanta.
</TEXT>
