<HEAD>Suspected Mother Pleads Innocent to Child Endangerment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with lawyer saying woman wants
to keep child, woman posts bail and leaves jail; custody hearing
set. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `A cleaning...'. SUBS last two grafs,
bgng `Christina Locasto...', with 4 grafs to delete now-outdated
reference to her being booked for investigation of attempted
murder, add detail on custody issue.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York City woman who allegedly
gave birth in an airliner restroom and left her newborn daughter in
a mass of blood-soaked towels pleaded innocent Thursday to a charge
of child endangerment.
   Christina Marie Locasto, 24, appeared in an orange jail jumpsuit
at her arraignment on the felony charge in San Mateo County
Municipal Court. If convicted, she could face up to six years in
prison.
   Her lawyer said Locasto, who is married and the mother of a
young daughter, regrets the incident and wants to keep the baby.
   Earlier Thursday, Locasto had been booked for investigation of
attempted murder.
   ``To prove attempted murder we have to prove beyond a reasonable
doubt an intent to kill, that by her act she intended that the
child would die,'' said Assistant District Attorney Stephen
Wagstaffe. ``But the evidence now before us does not establish
that.''
   After posting $50,000 bail in cash, a distraught-looking Locasto
left the San Mateo County Women's Correctional Facility late
Thursday afternoon, arm in arm with her husband, Louis. A
preliminary hearing was set for Aug. 9.
   Louis Locasto, 26, who was on the plane trip with her and their
3-year-old daughter, Janine, was not arrested and apparently didn't
know his wife was pregnant, San Mateo County Sheriff's Lt. Mike Dow
said.
   Detectives identified the woman through the passenger list, and
she turned herself in Thursday morning, a day after arriving in San
Francisco from Newark, N.J., said Dow.
   ``We had information she gave birth to the baby on the East
Coast before the plane took off, hid the baby ... disembarked the
aircraft and went to visit relatives,'' he said. ``Which means the
baby was beneath the sink for over six hours.''
   ``They've run tests all day yesterday and last night, and we're
waiting for the results, but the baby seems just fine,'' said Ann
Fyfe, spokeswoman for Mills Memorial Hospital in San Mateo.
   Dozens of callers offered to adopt the 8-pound, 9-ounce baby,
named Elizabeth by hospital nurses, following widespread publicity
about her birth.
   John L. Williams, an attorney for the woman, said outside the
courtroom that his client was ``very remorseful, very distraught.''
   ``I'm confident she did not plan to have the child on the
plane,'' he said.
   He would not comment further on the reasons for the incident but
said Locasto told him she wants to keep the baby. A court hearing
Monday will be held to determine whether county officials should be
given pe
DC-10 landed at San Francisco International Airport after a 5{-hour
flight.
   ``The cleaning crew heard the baby crying, and that was what led
them to the baby,'' said Rob Doughty, an airline spokesman in
Chicago.
   Except for blood on a seat, there was no trace of the mother,
who had disappeared with the other 252 passengers, detectives said.
   Flight attendants told investigators that as the crew was
preparing for takeoff, a female passenger asked to use the
bathroom. The flight was delayed for a half-hour as flight
attendants knocked on the restroom door, urging the woman to come
out so the trip could begin.
   The woman finally emerged and joined her husband and their young
child, investigators said. Flight attendants found the bathroom
splattered with blood, but sealed it off in the belief the woman
had an extreme case of diarrhea. It remained locked until after the
plane landed.
   Through the passenger list, sheriff's detectives contacted the
Locastos' relatives on the East Coast, and they contacted relatives
the couple was visiting in Los Altos, 25 miles south of San
Francisco, Dow said.
   None of Locasto's relatives were aware the 5-foot-7, 155-pound
woman was pregnant, Dow said.
   Late Wednesday night, Louis Locasto called sheriff's detectives,
beginning four hours of phone calls with investigators and the
district attorney's office, Dow said.
   Christina Locasto, accompanied by attorney Tom Nolan, turned
herself in at the Hall of Justice in Redwood City, the lieutenant
said.
   James Mayer, one of two physicians who operates the medical
clinic at San Francisco International Airport, treated the baby
before she was rushed to the hospital. He used dental floss to tie
off the umbilical cord.
   Baby Elizabeth was placed in the custody of the county
Children's Protective Services division. She will be placed in an
emergency foster home unless the mother wins custody, said Robert
McMillan, the division's head.
   There would be no problem finding a place for the newborn, he
added. ``We've had many, many calls from people who would like to
adopt the infant or provide foster care,'' he said.
