<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Election     07-14 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Election,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher's Conservatives Keep Seat in Special Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Conservative Party retained the west
London district of Kensington in polling Thursday in the first
special parliamentary election of Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's third term, but saw its winning margin sharply cut.
   Voters in the polarized district, where royal palaces and
high-rise tenements crowd into three square miles, re-elected the
Conservatives with 9,829 votes against 9,014 for the second-placed
socialist opposition Labor Party.
   This represented a winning margin for the Conservatives over
Labor of 815 votes. At the general election in June 1987, the
Conservatives' winning margin over Labor in the 48,500-voter
district was 4,500.
   Bookmakers favored the Conservatives to win. But many political
commentators considered Labor had a good chance of victory and
Bryan Gould, Labor's trade and industry spokesman, described the
Kensington result announced early Friday as a bitter disappointment
for his party.
   The campaign in Kensington, which contains thousands of highly
transient apartment-dwellers, was dull and only 51 percent of
eligible voters bothered to cast their ballots.
   The Conservatives' Dudley Fishburn, 42, an Eton- and
Harvard-educated former senior editor on the respected weekly, The
Economist, was put on the defensive during a lackluster campaign by
Thatcher plans for an unpopular new property tax.
   But Labor's Ann Holmes, 41, had to campaign against a background
of disarray in the British socialist movement over its
controversial anti-nuclear policy.
   William Goodhart, 55, of the Social and Liberal Democratic
Party, came third with 2,546 votes. Businessman John Martin, 52, of
the Social Democratic Party, came fourth with 1,190 votes.
   The Kensington poll was the first parliamentary test where
Britain's two centrist parties paid the price for an acrimonious
merger last spring of their former electoral alliance.
   Both the merged party, the Social and Liberal Democratic Party,
and the breakaway Social Democratic Party ran candidates, thus
splitting the already minority centrist vote.
   The election was caused by the death last November of
Conservative legislator Sir Brandon Rhys Williams, who represented
Kensington for 20 years.
   The district's plush southern end encompasses some of the most
beautiful parts of the British capital _ rows of elegant period
houses, Kensington Gardens and the palace where heir to the throne
Prince Charles, his aunt Princess Margaret and cousin Prince
Michael live in vast apartments.
   In north Kensington, working-class Britons and immigrants live
in shabby streets.
   At the last general election, which gave Mrs. Thatcher a third
consecutive victory, the Conservatives took 42.3 percent of the
vote, Labor 30.8 and the centrist alliance 22.5 percent.
   Since the election, she has pursued a radical program, including
a shakeup of the welfare system and education, and the new property
tax, which is aimed at undermining Labor councils but will more
than double some household tax bills.
   The Conservatives have a huge 101-seat majority in the
650-member House of Commons. The Conservatives have 375 seats,
Labor 229, the Social and Liberal Democrats 19 and the breakaway
SDP 3. The rest are held by minority regional parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
