<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     07-14 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Rebels Call Transport Ban In El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas battling the
U.S.-backed government of President Jose Napoleon Duarte announced
on Thursday a transport ban on roads and highways nationwide
beginning at midnight.
   The ban was the fourth this year by guerrillas of the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front coalition and was announced in a
broadcast over their clandestine Radio Venceremos, monitored in
this capital city.
   The rebels said it was in response to security forces' use of
tear gas and clubs Tuesday to break up a demonstration of peasants
from farming cooperatives. The armed forces claimed the
demonstrators provoked the repression by damaging vehicles and
hitting soldiers.
   In the broadcast, the guerrillas also promised to step up
sabotage of the electrical distribution system. The rebels
regularly blow up high-tension line towers and utility poles to
black out whole sectors of the country.
   The transport bans usually last three days. Previous such
prohibitions succeeded in reducing nationwide road transport by up
to 90 percent. The guerrillas stopped and burned or fired on
vehicles violating the ban.
</TEXT>
