<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Death-Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0817,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors Begin Deliberations in Trial of Three Lawmen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, `The three...', to add
that jurors end work for the night and are sequestered. Picks up
4th graf, `Garner, 34...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEMPHILL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury began deliberations Thursday in
the case of three white lawmen accused of beating a black inmate to
death.
   The three officers _ former Hemphill Police Chief Thomas Ladner,
41, and Sabine County sheriff's deputies James ``Bo'' Hyden, 35,
and Bill Horton, 58 _ have denied they delivered the blows that led
to the death of Loyal Garner Jr., a black truck driver from
Florien, La.
   The three are accused of violating Garner's civil rights. If
convicted, they face up to life in prison.
   After deliberating about six hours, the jurors were ordered
sequestered for the night and were to resume their work Friday.
   Garner, 34, died Dec. 27 at a Tyler hospital, two days after
allegedly being beaten while in the Sabine County jail in Hemphill.
   ``The issue in this case is whether Loyal Garner was beaten
unlawfully and then was left to lie in his own blood,'' prosecutor
John Hannah said in final arguments to the jury Thursday.
   Hannah accused the three of conspiring to cover up the beating
by concocting a story that Garner was a drug dealer and was
extremely drunk when he was jailed.
   ``They knew they had seriously screwed up. What they had to do
was build up a defense that the man they killed was a dope
dealer,'' he said.
   Defense attorneys in their closing arguments challenged the
credibility of some of the state's witnesses, saying many were
inmates who were in the jail at the time and had long criminal
records.
   ``The question of whether anybody had been beaten depends on
credibility,'' said John Seale, Ladner's attorney. ``Why, suddenly,
have these three leopards changed their spots and suddenly become
crooked, conniving and dirty men? These three men did not get
together and make up anything.''
   Seale also said Ladner was justified in striking Garner with a
slapstick once during a jail scuffle Christmas night.
   All three officers took the stand Wednesday as testimony in the
two-week trial ended. All denied causing Garner's death.
   If the jury convicts any of the three, the defendants have
agreed to allow State District Judge O'Neal Bacon to determine
punishment.
   The three also have been charged with murder in Garner's death,
and that trial is scheduled to begin Monday in Tyler.
</TEXT>
