<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ContraAid     07-14 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Voices Support For Contra Aid Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House on Thursday expressed support
of a $47.1 million aid package introduced in the Senate for the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels, despite some problems with the ``fine
print.''
   The outline of the package _ including $20 million in military
aid and $27.1 million in humanitarian aid through next March _ was
introduced late Wednesday by Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas.
   ``He offered it as a freestanding measure, but it will be slated
for action as an amendment to an appropriations bill,'' Dole aide
Walt Riker said Thursday.
   Under the measure, aid to the rebels opposing Nicaragua's
leftist Sandinista government would be authorized only after the
president certifies that it is necessary and after both houses of
Congress approve it.
   Asked about White House involvement in the creation of the
package, Riker said, ``We've been in consultation with them, but
we've taken the lead on it.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that the
White House was working with Congress on a new Contra aid bill and
said Dole has been ``very helpful'' in this effort.
   ``We may not agree with all the fine print in the bill, but we
think it's a very productive bill,'' Fitzwater said as he flew with
President Reagan from Washington to Marion, Ill., for a one-day
trip to see drought-ravaged farmland in the Midwest and to offer
moral support for farmers there.
   When Reagan was asked Wednesday whether he was supporting
efforts to get a new Contra aid package through Congress, he
responded, ``You bet I am.''
   Fitzwater's comments came the same day the House voted 385-18 to
condemn the Sandinista government for ``brutal suppression of basic
human rights.''
   The House action was similar to one approved by the Senate 91-4
on Wednesday, except that the Senate version threatened the
possible renewal of military aid to the Contras.
   Anger in Congress was triggered by the Sandinista government's
arrests of more than 40 people, including opposition leaders, and
the closing down of the opposition newspaper La Prensa and a Roman
Catholic radio station. In addition, Nicaragua this week expelled
eight U.S. diplomats, including Ambassador Richard Melton, an
action that prompted the Reagan administration to order the
expulsion of eight Nicaraguan diplomats, including Ambassador
Carlos Tunnermann.
   ``Obviously (Nicaraguan President Daniel) Ortega has given us a
real gift to rally support for the freedom fighters,'' Riker said.
``There's a real chance now to get Contra aid again. There's going
to be some Democratic support. We've talked to some of the
Democrats already.''
   In February, Congress rejected a $36.2 million package which
included a proposed $3.5 million for a military escrow account.
   In late March, it approved a $48 million measure providing only
humanitarian aid for Nicaragua through Sept. 30, and only $17
million of that was earmarked for the Contras.
</TEXT>
