<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Ellington Adv15   07-14 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Ellington, Adv 15,0861</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, July 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Duke Ellington Celebrated on `American Masters'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Duke Ellington was such a prolific composer and
profound influence on American music that it takes the PBS series
``American Masters'' two installments to tell his story.
   The first half of producer-director Terry Carter's vivid
portrayal, ``A Duke Named Ellington,'' airs Monday night on the
Public Broadcasting Service. The second half can be seen next
Monday, July 25.
   The documentary includes rare performance footage from Europe
never before seen in the United States and interviews with many of
the musicians who played in Ellington's band, which stayed together
for a record 47 years.
   Ellington, who died in 1974, began his career in Harlem. He says
in interview footage that there was a lot of tough competition from
the many pianists on the busy music scene, guys like Count Basie,
Willie ``The Lion'' Smith and James P. Johnson.
   ``But I'm lucky,'' Ellington says. ``Everybody liked me.''
   Suave, handsome and charismatic, Ellington was also a shrewd
businessman who entered into a productive partnership with music
publisher Irving Mills. It was Mills who was instrumental in
getting Ellington a gig at the Cotton Club. The documentary
includes tape of an announcer introducing Ellington as the
``greatest living master of jungle music.''
   Ellington's association with Mills, according to Ellington,
helped break down racial barriers in the music industry. And at a
time when blacks were being insulted by Hollywood stereotypes,
Ellington and the band appeared in their first movie in 1930,
``Check and Double Check.'' Ellington's cool, sophisticated style
gave black Americans a positive self-image.
   It seems he was as charismatic to his musicians as he was to his
fans.
   ``I consider myself privileged to sit in Duke Ellington's band
for 28 years,'' says Russell Procope. ``Any musician you talk to,
whether white, black, grizzled or gray, wanted to play with Duke
Ellington's band, believe me.''
   In 1943, Ellington hired clarinetist Jimmy Hamilton, whose
smooth, Benny Goodman-ish sound was a departure from the New
Orleans-style jazz that was prevalent among black musicians. In an
interview, Hamilton recalls his reluctance at joining Ellington's
band because he was working well enough and didn't want to go on
the road.
   He also recalls with relish how he would practice constantly to
keep up with Ellington's increasingly complex compositions.
   ``He put some music up and I'd say, `Hey, that's difficult, man,
I don't know if I can make that.' You were always trying to stay a
little ahead of him because he was going to try to get you sooner
or later.''
   Hamilton said he managed the piece quite well, and Ellington
took the same music to Goodman, who, without benefit of practice,
didn't do such a good job. Ellington came back gloating, according
to Hamilton, and said, ```Ah! I found out Benny's human!'''
   Ellington's relationship with sax player Johnny Hodges was not
so genial. According to critic Leonard Feather, Hodges' riffs would
sometimes get turned into compositions by Ellington, and Hodges
felt he was due some proceeds. When Ellington would play the piece,
said Feather, ``Johnny would start making motions with his hands,
like counting money, you know. And that went on actually on the
bandstand.''
   Part 2, which follows Ellington's later career, opens with
Ellington and the band playing the classic ``Take the `A' Train,''
which in fact was written by collaborator Billy Strayhorn.
   That number is followed by another classic, ``Mood Indigo.''
   ``I think we played that every night for 28 years,'' said
Procope. ``I never got tired of it, because every night it was like
the first time.''
   In an interview, Ellington is asked about his relationship to
``his'' people. ``THE people,'' he responds. ``That's the better
word. THE people rather than MY people. Becuase THE people are MY
people.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   SOUTHWESTERN BELL BACKS `SMITHSONIAN' _ Southwestern Bell Corp.
has signed up as sole underwriter for the public television series
``Smithsonian World'' for the 1988-89 season, scheduled to begin in
October. The program is the first public television commitment for
the corporation, based in St. Louis. Subjects will include fashion
and history, genetic research and the pressures of change at a
small prep school. The program is co-produced by WNET in Virginia
and the Smithsonian Institution. ...
   `VICE' AND `MURDER' ON USA _ The USA Network is ready to embark
on a $50 million publicity campaign to tout the cable premieres of
reruns of ``Murder, She Wrote'' and ``Miami Vice.'' The promotional
money should be even better spent than USA Network hoped when the
campaign was planned last May, now that the strike by the Writers
Guild of America has indefinitely delayed the networks' new fall
shows. Besides buying ads, the campaign includes sending splashy
multi-media publicity kits to USA affiliates and a ``Miami Vice''
contest in October with a Ferrari Testarossa the grand prize. USA
Network is available to approximately 45 million homes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, July 15</NOTE>
