<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Soviet-Estonia-Leader Adv24   07-14 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet-Estonia-Leader, Adv 24,0415</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Estonia's New Party Chief Veers from Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Soviet-Estonia, b0789</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLINN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Estonia's new Communist Party chief,
Vajno Vyalyas, is a native son attempting the delicate task of
steering his republic away from Moscow's tight grip.
   The 57-year-old descendant of Estonian fishermen and seamen took
office in June in the midst of a vigorous populist movement that is
seeking more economic, cultural and political independence from the
Kremlin.
   Such movements had been suppressed under Vyalyas' predecessor,
Karl Vaino, who is remembered by activists here for intolerance and
a poor command of the Estonian language.
   Vyalyas, a history graduate of Estonia's prestigious Tartu
University, doesn't hide his roots.
   ``I was born and raised on this land,'' he said in an interview.
``This is my homeland.''
   ``On this land worked my ancestors,'' he added. ``I myself am a
historian, and through church lists I managed to ascertain that
seven generations of them worked on the island Hiiumaa,'' an island
just off the coast.
   The brown-haired, hazel-blue-eyed Vyalyas spoke in his office in
Communist Party headquarters in Tallinn, Estonia's capital. Among
the few decorations in his office were portraits of Vladimir I.
Lenin, founder of the Soviet state, and Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev and Vyalyas both worked in the 1950s and early 1960s
in the Communist Party's youth organization, Komsomol _ Gorbachev
in his home region of Stavropol in southern Russia and at Moscow
State University, and Vyalyas in Tartu and Tallinn. Vyalyas went on
to lead the city party organization in Tallinn for 10 years before
being elected a party secretary for the republic-wide party
apparatus.
   After being passed over for the Estonian party chief's job in
1978, Vyalyas joined the Soviet diplomatic corps, serving as
ambasssador to Venezuela, Trinidad and Tobago, and Nicaragua.
   Estonian intellectuals say Vyalyas' diplomatic experience may be
helpful in winning the battle for more Estonian independence.
   Vyalyas talks about making Estonia more economically independent
of Moscow and preserving its culture and language. But he adheres
to the Soviet principle of ``internationalism,'' the mix of
national groups under one, Soviet umbrella.
   But he adds a flavoring of his own heritage to it.
   ``Islanders are always by nature big internationalists,''
Vyalyas said, chuckling. ``They were all seamen and always said,
`Any port is my home.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
