<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Bendix-Siemens     07-14 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bendix-Siemens,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Company To Purchase Majority Interest In Bendix</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Siemens AG, the billion-dollar West
German electronics and telecommunications giant, agreed in
principle Thursday to purchase a majority interest in Allied-Signal
Inc.'s Bendix Electronics Group for between $200 million and $300
million.
   The new company, Siemens-Bendix Automotive Electronics, will be
based in Southfield, Mich. and will continue under Bendix's present
management. It will concentrate on the development and application
of advanced electronic technology to the automotive industry, the
firms said.
   Siemans and Allied-Signal agreed in December to establish a
joint venture in automotive electronics. Negotiations over Bendix
intensified after that, resulting in Thursday's announcement, said
Allied-Signal spokesman Michael Ascolese.
   Terms of the sale, including the final size of the stake Siemens
will acquire, were expected to be finalized by the end of the year,
he said.
   Allied-Signal said it would use the proceeds from the sale to
reduce part of its debt.
   J. Mason Reynolds, president of Allied-Signal Automotive, said
the sale of the majority interest in Bendix will allow
Allied-Signal to focus its attention on automotive markets in which
it is an industry leader.
   Morris Township-based Allied Signal had a profit of $656
million, or $3.90 per share, on sales of $11.1 billion in 1987.
   Siemens, with headquarters in Berlin and Munich, reported
worldwide sales last year of more than $30 billion, said Martin
Weitzner, spokesman for Siemens Capital Corp., the New York-based
holding company for Siemens in the United States.
</TEXT>
