<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is promising to do all he can
to protect farmers from excessive losses during the drought that is
afflicting large areas of the nation.
   But On the eve of his inspection tour of southern Illinois
drought areas Wednesday, he cautioned, ``We mustn't bust the
budget.''
   Agriculture experts say that up to 4 inches of rain in the
flatland region won't help much of the already damaged corn crop.
But the Reagan visit, they say, is a good gesture on the
president's part and should help get federal aid for farmers who
have substantial crop loss.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Indiana farmers have sued Federal
Insurance Co., a subsidiary of Chubb Group Insurance Cos. for
allegedly reneging on policies to pay awards for lack of rain.
   Meanwhile, Iowa regulators filed misrepresentation charges
against the company on Wednesday.
   Chubb says it had far more applications than coverage it wanted
to provide, but has promised to return premiums and said it is
working with state insurance departments on the matter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security analysts say comments to investors
by an attorney for a cancer victim's widower in a landmark
cigarette liability case appear to have driven some tobacco stocks
higher.
   Philip Morris Inc. jumped $6 between July 6, the day before the
luncheon investment meeting, and Wednesday, when it closed at
$89.87{ a share. Other tobacco stocks, including RJR-Nabisco, Loews
Corp. and American Brands, also rose after declining the day before.
   The jury ordered Liggett Group Inc. to pay $400,000 in damages
to Antonio Cipollone for the death of his wife, Rose, who died of
lung cancer after 40 years of smoking.
</TEXT>
