<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     07-14 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Falls Further, But Unleaded Gasoline Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices have slumped to a 21-month low
amid growing pessimism about overproduction by OPEC members.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August-delivery price
of West Texas Intermediate crude, which fell 6 cents on Tuesday,
fell another 28 cents Wednesday to close at $14.44 per barrel.
   The last time prices for the near month WTI contract were lower
was Oct. 29, 1986, when they closed at $13.73 a barrel.
   Fears of continued overproduction by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries sent prices lower, said Andrew Lebow,
senior broker and analyst at E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc.
   ``It's the same type of scenario that's burdened the market for
the last couple of weeks,'' he said.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the August
contract for wholesale unleaded tumbled 3 cents to close at 50.48
cents a gallon.
   Gasoline futures had fared better than oil in recent weeks
because of increased demand during the summer driving season. But
profit-taking and rumors that importers were buying foreign
gasoline to ease tight supplies took their toll on gas prices
Wednesday, Lebow said.
   The near month contract for home heating oil slipped 0.51 cent
to 40.14 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
