<DOCNO> AP880714-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CBSOutlook Bjt   07-14 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS Outlook, Bjt,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Posts Profit Gain, Shuffles Broadcast Management</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY48 of July 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even as it posted a big profit gain for its
second quarter and announced some major management changes, CBS
Inc. says a scriptwriters strike is clouding the outlook for the
broadcasting business.
   CBS reported Wednesday that its second-quarter profit climbed 40
percent to a record high, citing higher interest income, improved
operating efficiency and an increase in broadcast sales despite a
sluggish advertising market.
   But Laurence A. Tisch, president and chief executive of CBS,
said in announcing the results that the business outlook for
broadcasting for the balance of the year ``is somewhat uncertain
based largely on the continuing strike by the Writers Guild of
America.''
   The 19-week strike threatens to delay the start of the fall
television season, and some network executives fear that without a
slate of new programming viewers could look elsewhere for
entertainment and reduce the audience for commercials.
   However, Tisch said CBS had found demand for advance sales of
fall television time to advertisers was ``surprisingly strong.''
   The networks have been conducting their annual ``upfront'' ad
sales for the fall season over the past 10 days, and Tisch said he
agreed with published reports that said prime time sales could
match or exceed last year's total.
   The strong earnings performance by the CBS Broadcast Group also
figured in Wednesday's announcement that Howard Stringer, the
president of CBS News, would become president of the CBS Broadcast
Group. An ABC executive, David W. Burke, was selected to head the
news division.
   Effective Aug. 1, Stringer replaces Gene F. Jankowski, 54, who
has been president of the broadcast group for 11 years and will
take the newly created post of broadcast group chairman. Stringer,
46, will report directly to Tisch.
   Burke, 52, has been with ABC News for 11 years, the last two as
executive vice president. His appointment marks the first time CBS
has gone outside the company for the head of its news division.
   Tisch said Jankowski approached him last week suggesting that
with this year's program development schedule complete and
six-month earnings at a record level, it was appropriate for ``an
orderly transition'' in management of the broadcast group. In his
new role, Jankowski said, he will scout possible station
acquisitions among other things.
   The CBS Television Network struggled during the past season,
with its prime time ratings trailing NBC and ABC for the first time
ever.
   Financial analysts suggested the changes probably were
inevitable as Tisch made his mark on the company, which he has
headed since the fall of 1986.
   ``Larry's putting his man in charge, and Gene is probably taking
the first step out the door,'' said Edward Atorino, who follows the
media business for the investment firm Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co.
   Stringer, a 23-year veteran with CBS, had headed CBS News for 22
months, steering the news division through controversial layoffs
and budget cuts while still managing to launch a news show, ``48
Hours,'' and keep three prime-time news hours on the fall schedule.
   Phil Jones, general manager of KCTV in Kansas City, Mo., and
former chairman of the CBS affiliates board, said Stringer's
performance indicates he ``will be good person to do business
with.''
   In its earnings report, CBS said it had net income of $128.7
million, or $5.01 a share, in the three months ended June 30,
compared with $92.1 million, or $3.77 a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose 4 percent to $740 million from $714 million. The 1987
figures included $19.3 million income from discontinued operations.
   For the first six months of the year, CBS earned $1.04 billion,
or $40.43 a share, up sevenfold from $140.8 million, or $5.70 a
share, a year earlier. Revenue was unchanged at $1.44 billion.
   The latest results included a gain of $866.6 million on asset
sales, while the 1987 figures include $60.2 million income from
discontinued operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Gillette-Coniston Bjt   07-14 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette-Coniston, Bjt,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says He Is Likely To Order New Vote in Proxy Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. shareholders may get another chance
to vote in the battle between the personal care products company
and the dissident investor group attempting to win seats on its
board of directors.
   A federal judge who ruled that Gillette inaccurately portrayed
the group, Coniston Partners, during a bitter proxy battle said
Wednesday he was likely to order a new shareholder vote.
   U.S. District Judge Mark L. Wolf ruled last week that Gillette
inaccurately portrayed Coniston in newspaper advertisements leading
up to the April 21 proxy vote in which shareholders rejected a
Coniston slate of four director candidates.
   Coniston had called for a new vote in briefs filed this week in
the second part of the case, being held to decide what sort of
relief Coniston deserves. Wolf tentatively set a second trial to
begin Aug 22.
   The judge said at a hearing Wednesday likely would invalidate
the proxy vote and call a new vote regardless of whether he found
that Coniston acted with ``unclean hands'' in the period leading up
to the election.
   ``I continue to believe some relief to shareholders will be
required,'' he said. ``What I found was that the essence of the
election was tainted in a material way.''
   Gillette stock closed at $40.50, up $2.25 a share on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   ``That's what we've been saying to him,'' Coniston attorney Mark
A. Michelson said of Wolf's statement. ``What the judge is saying
is he's inclined to give the relief we want, which is a new
election.''
   But Gillette spokesman David Fausch said Wolf was only
speculating on what action he may take. ``He's made no decision on
that,'' Fausch said of a new vote. ``He said that he's evolving his
theories and ideas but no decision has been made at all on remedy.''
   After a seven-day trial, Wolf ruled July 6 that several Gillette
newspaper ads during the proxy solicitation contained ``falsely
misleading'' information about Coniston. But he ruled Gillette did
not mislead shareholders when it withheld information about
potential buyers during the three-month proxy battle.
   Wolf also said he was still reviewing whether Coniston violated
full disclosure laws in U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission
filings, including the role of Swiss financier Tito Tettamanti, who
raised $5 million for strategic block investments in Gillette.
   On Wednesday, Wolf said the second phase of the case may require
more information on Tettamanti.
   ``Although he is beyond the subpoena powers of this court,
perhaps he should be invited to come,'' Wolf said. ``Why doesn't he
make one of his visits in the last week of August and we'll ask him
questions and watch the answers.''
   Gillette on April 14 filed suit seeking to block Coniston's
proxy bid on the grounds Coniston falsified SEC filings and did not
fully disclose all investors, including Tettamanti.
   A countersuit filed by Coniston five days later alleged Gillette
misprepresented Coniston in advertisements and mailings to the
company's 27,000 shareholders and failed to publicly disclose all
companies that had expressed interest in buying Gillette.
   Stockholders rejected the Coniston slate of candidates by 52
percent to 48 percent.
   Coniston controls 6.76 million Gillette shares, or about 5.8
percent of the shares outstanding. Coniston is attempting to
pressure the 12-member Gillette board to sell the company, which
likely would boost the value of the group's shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 0041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Hewlett-Apple     07-14 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hewlett-Apple,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hewlett Countersues Apple Inc. In Copyright Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. is claiming that
Apple Computer Inc. does not hold valid copyrights for visual
displays and computer images that are at the center of a legal
battle between the computer makers.
   In a countersuit filed Wednesday in response to a U.S. District
Court copyright infringement suit filed by Apple, Hewlett-Packard
alleged that Apple was engaged in unfair business practices and
antitrust violations.
   Palo Alto-based Hewlett Packard denied all of Apple's suit
allegations and asked the court to invalidate Apple's copyrights in
the case and to dismiss its suit against Hewlett-Packard.
   Cupertino-based Apple sued Hewlett-Packard and Microsoft Corp.,
of Redmond, Wash., in March, charging them with copyright
infringement in two so-called ``operating environment'' programs _
Microsoft's Windows and Hewlett-Packard's NewWave.
   The programs provide a visual ``desktop'' on the screen, on
which a computer user can view various symbols representing
documents, applications programs and places to store information.
   In April, Microsoft submitted a response to the court in San
Jose, charging that Apple violated contracts, acted in bad faith
and damaged Microsoft's relations with other companies.
   Microsoft denied that Windows infringed on Apple copyrights by
using images that too closely resembled those of Apple's popular
Macintosh computer.
   Apple's suit shook software developers and computer makers
throughout the industry because of its potential scope. Aside from
Hewlett-Packard and Microsoft, Apple also indirectly challenged its
biggest rival, International Business Machines Corp., which has
been incorporating display graphics similar to Apple's.
   Apple was seen as essentially asking the court to preserve a
technological edge it has enjoyed over its competitors, just as the
rivals were closing the gap.
   ``HP is confident the court will agree Apple's suit has no
merit,'' said Douglas C. Chance, executive vice president of HP's
Business Systems Sector.
   Apple officials could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
