<HEAD>Dollar Mixed In Calm Trading, Gold Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in calm European trading late
this morning as activity wound down ahead of Friday's release of
U.S. trade figures. Gold prices were slightly higher.
   Dealers said the market appeared to have stabilized in a narrow
range after recording further gains on statements made Wednesday by
U.S. Federal Reserve Board officials.
   Chairman Alan Greenspan indicated a tighter monetary policy and
Federal Reserve Board member Wayne Angell said the dollar's rise
was underpinned by fundamental factors.
   Dealers said the U.S. trade figures for May will be the key to
the dollar's trading range over the next week.
   The market is expecting a seasonally adjusted trade deficit
between $10 billion and $11.5 billion, larger than $9.9 billion in
April, said a dealer at a large West German bank.
   A trader in Rome said if the deficit is below $11 billion, the
dollar is likely to rise, but if it is higher, the dollar may
suffer a serious setback.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8479 West German marks, up from 1.8460; 1.5305
Swiss francs, down from 1.5313; 6.2260 French francs, down from
6.2265; 2.0843 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0835; 1,369.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,367.75; and 1.2077 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2083.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.6870 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6920 late Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.48 yen to close at 132.95 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted lower at 132.055 yen.
   Bullion dealers said gold came off its early morning highs in
quiet trading while silver, which rose as high as $7.25 a troy
ounce earlier today, also retreated slightly.
   Silver was quoted in London late this morning at a bid price of
$7.24, up from late Wednesday's $6.98.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $439.50 a troy ounce,
and at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $439.05. Both were higher than Wednesday's
late bid $437.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $439, up from $435.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.25 to close at a bid $440.53.
</TEXT>
