<HEAD>Stocks Rebound, Dollar Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rebounded today on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, and the dollar gained slightly against the Japanese yen
before the release of U.S. trade figures for May.
   The dollar opened at 132.75 yen, the day's low, and rose to
132.97 yen before closing at 132.95 yen, up 0.48 yen from
Wednesday's close.
   Dealers said the dollar moved up marginally following remarks by
U.S. Federal Reserve Board member Wayne Angell that the board
should not attempt to reverse the dollar's recent upswing.
   But they said trading remained slow with a wait-and-see attitude
prevailing before the U.S. Commerce Department announces the May
trade figures on Friday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 79.74-point
loser Wednesday, gained 63.98 points, or 0.23 percent, to close the
day's trading at 28,084.08.
   After opening higher, stock prices eased late in the morning
session but recovered on the buying of blue chip electricals and
automakers during the afternoon session.
   Traders said the market was dominated by speculative, short-term
trading ahead of the announcement of U.S. trade figures.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 2.1 billion shares,
up from Wednesday's 2.0 billion shares.
