<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SuzukiInsurance     07-14 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suzuki Insurance,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dealers Offering Samurai Insurance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio Suzuki dealers, in an attempt to restore
confidence in the company's sharply criticized Samurai model, are
offering a $1 million accidental life insurance policy free for one
year to people who buy or lease the vehicle.
   ``You can't run enough ads to erase the cloud that all of this
has put over the car,'' said Robert Reichert, president of the
Kenwood Dealer Group, on Wednesday. The sales promotion ends Aug.
31 but may be continued if buyers show renewed confidence in the
model, Reichert said.
   He said he worked with other Ohio Suzuki dealers on the plan.
``We decided that we needed something emphatic,'' he said.
   Charges by Consumers Union that the vehicle tips over too easily
caused national sales of the Samurai to drop by 70.6 percent in
June.
   American Suzuki Motor Corp., which had been selling about 6,000
a month of the vehicles from March through May, reported it sold
2,199 Samurais in June, compared to 7,479 in June 1987.
   Reichert said Suzuki dealers have considerable data to dispute
the information put out by Consumers Union, which publishes
Consumer Reports magazine. Consumers Union says Suzuki should
recall the vehicle and give car owners refunds.
   ``We felt there was very little we could do to effectively fight
the negative publicity'' other than offer a bigpromotion to show
that the Samurai is safe, Reichert said.
   The insurance program, which starts Friday, is being
underwritten by the American International group of insurance
companies.
   In a separate move, American Suzuki officials on Wednesday
disclosed to dealers plans to offer a $2,000 discount off the
Samurai's regular price for a limited time.
   Reichert said the dealers offer the insurance policy for one
year but buyers can renew after that time and pay for it themselves.
   ``It's a typical accident policy,'' said Reichert. If a person
is killed when a Samarai turns over or tips over, the policy will
pay $1 million.''
   ``But we're going to tell tham that these things are not built
to turn corners at 80 mph. Like any other car, these things can
turn over,'' Reichert said.
   Reichert said the Aug. 31 limitation was set to comply with Ohio
law that limits the time of sales promotions.
</TEXT>
