<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DefenseProbe 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Redstone Investigation Finds Overcharging On Contracts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 13, Officials at, with 2 grafs to include Morrison
Knudsen reaction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of government contractors billed the
Army for 23 hours of work at the Redstone Arsenal in Alabama even
though the job they performed took only 45 minutes, says a
congressional watchdog agency.
   And in another incident at Redstone, the contractors billed the
Pentagon for the work of 10 men to paint stripes on a parking lot
even though two of them did all the painting while the other eight
stood around, the General Accounting Office said.
   The idle workers were often told to hide from government
inspectors, a GAO witness told a house subcommittee on Wednesday.
   The incidents are part of an investigation in which the FBI and
the Army's Criminal Investigative Division are probing contracts at
the Huntsville installation, the GAO said.
   The Redstone investigations are unrelated to the investigation
into allegations that defense contractors and their consultants
bribed Pentagon officials for inside information that could have
been vital in bidding for contracts worth billions of dollars. No
charges have been filed.
   The Redstone case was revealed by David C. Williams of the GAO's
office of special investigations. He was testifying before the
Government Operations national security subcommittee.
   The Redstone case in which the 45-minute job was inflated and
the parking lot was painted involves a five-year, $250 million
contract for base support activities, including maintenance, food
service and equipment repair, Williams said.
   The contract was between the Army Missile Command and two
contractors who formed a joint venture to bid on the project. They
are the Holmes and Narver Corp. of Orange, Calif., and the
Morrison-Knudsen Corp. of Boise, Idaho.
   The investigation showed that ``to cover for falsified labor
charges, materials had to be expended and building supplies were
given away to contract workers and government employees,'' Williams
said.
   ``Materials such as paint were discarded in dumpsters and, and
other times, thrown into the Tennessee River,'' Williams.
   A review of vehicle maintenance records, looking only at oil
changes and lube jobs, showed that ``the government was overcharged
by 262 percent, or 5,000 hours, each year,'' he said.
   ``This type of charge attempted to justify the excessive costs
for that year, and created an inflated cost history for future
projected increases in the contract,'' he explained. ``In fact, the
five-year contract has increased over its original bid by more than
$100 million.''
   Officials at the Army base at Huntsville and Holmes and Narver
did not return telephoned requests for reaction to Williams'
statements.
   Vern Nelson, a spokesman for Morrison-Knudsen, said, ``We are
aware the General Accounting Office has been auditing these
operations, and we have been fully cooperating with the GAO
representatives. We have just received the GAO congressional
testimony and are reviewing the matter.''
   Williams also said that a 1987 study of 263 time-and-material
contracts to small businesses turned up some suspicious facts.
   For example, he said, 45 percent of those 263 contracts showed
that the bids were ``within 1 percent of the government's cost
estimates, suggesting that there might have been unauthorized
releases of government estimates, or that contractors themselves
prepared the government's cost estimates. Either practice
compromises the government's ability to ensure a fair and
reasonable price.''
   In yet another case, said Williams, there was ``apparent
favoritism in two contract awards'' by Army Lt. Gen. John Wall,
commander of the Army Strategic Defense Command, toward BDM
International Inc. of McLean, Va.
   In one case, Wall directed BDM to be interim contractor for a
major research initiative. In another case, according to Williams,
BDM lost out to Teledyne Brown Engineering on a $500 million
contract, but Wall ordered that 240,000 hours of support work be
shifted from Teledyne to BDM.
   Since BDM charges $15 per hour more than Teledyne, Williams
said, ``this could result in an expected increase in cost of
approximately $3.6 million.''
   Wall was investigated by the Army CID and retired in June,
Williams said. Attempts to locate him for comment were not
successful.
   James Hughes, a spokesman for BDM, said ``there was no
suggestion of wrongdoing on the part of BDM'' in the Army
investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880714-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   07-14 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Up 0.5 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-4 new to UPDATE with prime rate hikes; uppicks 2nd
graf pvs: The Commerce ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Several of the nation's major banks raised their prime lending
rate today by half a percentage point to 9.5 percent, the highest
level in more than two years.
   It was the second boost in the key lending rate this year and
signaled a new round of higher interest rates for consumers on
loans for purchases ranging from automobiles to homes.
   The increase came one day after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan warned he would use the central bank's power to tighten
credit if inflation started to accelerate.
   Separately, American consumers boosted retail sales 0.5 percent
in June by purchasing more cars and summer gear, the government
reported today, but the increase wasn't as strong as expected and
could ease concerns about inflation.
   The Commerce Department said sales increased $713 million last
month to a seasonally adjusted, but not inflation-adjusted, $132.8
billion. Much of the increase came from sales of autos, air
conditioners, barbecues and clothes.
   Analysts had been expecting a gain of about 0.8 percent. The
moderate June increase therefore may dampen anxiety in financial
markets that the economy is too strong, lessening pressure on the
Federal Reserve to tighten credit.
   The retail sales report came a day after Fed Chairman Alan
Greenspan warned he would use higher interest rates to battle any
resurgence of inflation.
   Currency investors interpreted Greenspan's comments as
supportive of the dollar, which finished mostly higher despite
reports of central bank intervention. But the stock market
discounted his warnings and the bond market was mixed.
   Delivering his midyear report to Congress on monetary policy,
Greenspan also said the Fed and other central banks would continue
to work for stable exchange rates. He said he saw no evidence that
the growth of U.S. exports has been affected by the dollar's recent
rise against other major currencies.
   Greenspan said the central bank stands ready to push interest
rates higher to stem inflation. And the risks of a new wage-price
spiral are ``sufficiently great'' that the Fed should err on the
side of squeezing credit, rather than stimulating the economy, he
said.
   Greenspan said the Fed already has made a series of small
credit-tightening steps from late March through late June, allowing
short-term interest rates to rise.
   Nevertheless, inflationary pressures _ including tight labor
markets, high factory operating rates and drought-caused increases
in grain prices _ remain and must be curbed now rather than later,
he said.
   Greenspan's pledge to continue fighting inflation gave bond
prices an early boost, but they finished mixed.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down
about 10 points at its afternoon low, closed with an 11.73 point
gain at 2,104.37. The late round of buying was attributed by
analysts to computer program trading.
   Grain and soybean futures closed sharply higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade, with most contracts up their allowable limit in
reaction to Tuesday's government report showing severe drought
damage to crops.
   Crude oil prices skidded to a 21-month low as traders grew more
pessimistic about overproduction by OPEC members. On the New York
Mercantile Exchange, the August-delivery price of West Texas
Intermediate crude fell 28 cents to close at $14.44 a barrel.
   In other economic developments Wednesday:
   _Automakers reported that buyers reacting to changing incentive
offerings pushed domestic car sales down at General Motors Corp.
and Ford Motor Co. but up at No. 3 Chrysler Corp.
   _The House passed a revamped version of the massive trade bill,
now tailored to conditions set by President Reagan when he vetoed
the original in May.
   _The U.S. appetite for foreign oil increased sharply in the
first half of the year, while domestic crude production kept
declining, an industry report showed.
</TEXT>
