<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-14 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Oats, Soybeans Open Limit-Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for corn, oats and soybeans
skyrocketed their allowable limits at the opening of today's
session on the Chicago Board of Trade in response to forecasts for
another month of drought in the Farm Belt.
   The National Weather Service predicted above-normal temperatures
and below-normal rainfall for most growing areas in both its
6-to-10 day and 30-day forecasts.
   ``Everyone's looking at the severe weather situation and right
now they're hard pressed to see anything that will turn it
around,'' said Mario Balletto, soybean analyst with Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets in New York.
   Rain is badly needed to salvage the shrinking percentage of the
corn crop that has not already been irreparably damaged by the
drought, and to prevent substantial soybean losses as that crop
enters its flowering and pod-forming stage, Balletto said.
   Corn, oat and soybean futures closed limit-up on Wednesday,
prompting the Board of Trade to expand the daily price limits by 50
percent, to 15 cents a bushel for corn and oats and 45 cents a
bushel for soybeans. Limits have been removed on the contracts for
delivery in July, pending the expiration of those contracts next
Wednesday.
   In early trading, wheat was 13 cents to 14 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.06 a bushel; corn was 11 cents
to 15 cents higher with July at $3.44{ a bushel; oats were 15 cents
to 15{ cents higher with July at $3.20 a bushel; soybeans were 45
cents to 45{ cents higher with July at $9.94 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were sharply lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to 1.02 cents lower with August at
63.30 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to 1.12 cents
lower with August at 73.15 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower
to the limit 1.50 cents higher with July at 45.20 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .90 cent to 1.63 cent higher with July at
34.60 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed sharply lower Thursday while pork futures
were mixed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
