<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Unisys-Billing     07-14 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unisys-Billing,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys Is Investigated Over Billing For Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp., which is being investigated
for allegedly fraudulent defense procurement practices, confirmed
today it may face charges for its billing for computer work done
for the U.S. Army.
   In a statement, the company said it ``has been cooperating with
the Office of the U.S. Attorney in Tucson, Ariz., in its
investigation of a contract with the Army Communications Center
based in Fort Huachuca.''
   A story in the Wall Street Journal Wednesday said the U.S.
Attorney's Office in Tucson planned to seek criminal charges
against a Unisys unit and two company officials.
   The overcharges in computer could reach as much as $10 million,
the Journal said. They stem from several years of work on the Army
Information Systems Command in Fort Huachuca, Ariz.
   However, Wren Timberlake, a spokesman at the Arizona base, said
the entire contract in question was for $9.2 million.
   Unisys said it totaled $8 million, and that the alleged
overcharges did not exceed $250,000. The company said the contract
with the Army was entered into in 1982 by Sperry Corp., which
merged with Burroughs Corp. in 1986 and became Unisys.
   ``If there were overcharges, they were significantly less than
$10 million,'' Timberlake said.
   ``I'm not certain the alleged charges involved any money at all.
The alleged administrative shortcoming involved in this case was
more the procedural irregularities in the way the government was
billed,'' he said.
   The Journal reported that Unisys had ``voluntarily disclosed the
problems at Fort Huachuca, provided additional information to the
Justice Department as the investigation progressed and pledged to
take corrective action to prevent recurrence.''
   The company has three contracts with the Army at Fort Huachuca,
totaling $70 million, Timberlake said, adding that the Army and
Unisys continue to have a ``fine relationship.''
   Unisys had $9.7 billion in revenues last year, of which 25
percent, or $2.4 billion, came from defense work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
