<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Decline</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished lower in choppy trading
Thursday on the London Stock Exchange, after being whipsawed by
British economic reports and by news that major U.S. banks raised
their prime lending rates to 9.5 percent from 9 percent.
   However, market players were reluctant to significantly change
their positions ahead of Friday's barrage of U.S. economic
indicators, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished the
day down 8 points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,863.3, its lowest level of
the day.
   Trading volume was a relatively robust 526.6 million shares, up
from Wednesday's 430.8 million shares.
   The U.S. trade report for May, producer prices for June,
industrial production data for June and business inventories for
May are due to be released Friday by the government in Washington.
In addition, the British retail price index for June is to be
reported.
   ``We've been up and down like a yo-yo today,'' one London equity
salesman said. He said the market had been doing quite well on the
spate of British economic reports released early Thursday until the
prime rate hikes at midafternoon ``knocked us down like a ton of
bricks.''
   Of particular interest to the London market was news that the
underlying annual rate of increase in British average earnings held
steady at 8.5 percent in May, following a downward revision in
April to 8.5 percent from 8.75 percent.
   That report helped eased fears about inflation, but the market
quickly became unsettled by the prime rate increase, analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
