<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 1527EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-14 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Oats, Soybeans Post Limit Gains On Drought Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forecasts for another month of drought conditions
in the Midwest drove prices for most corn, oat and soybean futures
up their allowable limits Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   But profit-taking cooled the advance in prices for near-term
delivery, and wheat futures closed lower after failing to hold new
contract highs.
   All corn, oat and soybean contracts soared their respective
limits at the opening in response to the National Weather Service's
6-to-10-day and 30-day forecasts for above-normal temperatures and
below-normal rainfall in the Farm Belt.
   Most of those contracts held their limit gains through the
close. But the July contracts, on which the limits have been
removed pending their expiration next Wednesday, closed with
relatively modest gains.
   Analysts said the pattern indicated profit-taking, perhaps
stemming from increased chances of rain in the Midwest on Friday.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 10 cents lower with July at $3.87 a
bushel; corn was 2 cents to 15 cents higher with July at $3.35{ a
bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 15 cents higher with July at $3.08 a
bushel; soybeans were 31{ cents to 45 cents higher with July at
$9.80 a bushel.
</TEXT>
