<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     07-14 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.39 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 443 money market mutual
funds rose $1.39 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise to $266.33 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday followed a revised increase of $567.5 million the
previous week, the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said.
That increase originally had been reported as $468.8 million.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 220 general purpose funds rose $814.1 million to $82.65
billion, assets of 100 broker-dealer funds rose $725.2 million to
$114.17 billion, and assets of 123 institutional funds fell $147.1
million to $69.52 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.70 percent from 6.68 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 6.64 percent from 6.58 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
unchanged at 35 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 5.77 percent as of
Wednesday from 5.76 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.12 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.21
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.15 the
previous week. Yields were 7.51 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 7.48
percent; 7.89 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 7.84 percent; and
8.28 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.26 percent.
</TEXT>
