<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Banks     07-14 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Banking, Security Pacific, Bank of New York Post 2nd-Qtr
Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Three big U.S. banking companies reported Thursday that they
were profitable in the second quarter after posting losses a year
earlier.
   The trio _ Chemical Banking Corp., Security Pacific Corp. and
Bank of New York Co. _ had sustained heavy losses in the second
quarter of 1987 from writeoffs for potential losses on loans to
developing countries.
   First City Bancorp. of Texas, meanwhile, which recently received
a $970 million federal bailout, reported net income of $17.2
million for the 72-day period immediately following its $1.6
billion reorganization.
   The restructured bank, based in Houston, said net income for the
initial period ending June 30 was 66 cents a share. Total assets as
of June 30 were $11.3 billion, loans were $6.3 billion, deposits
were $9.1 billion and shareholders' equity was $586 million.
   Chemical Banking, the nation's fourth-largest bank holding
company, said it earned $127.7 million, or $1.98 a share, compared
with a net loss of $1.1 billion in the second quarter of 1987.
   If the loan-loss provisions hadn't been made in the second
quarter of last year, New York-based Chemical would have earned
$76.4 million, or $1.21 a share, it said.
   For the first six months of the year, Chemical had net income of
$253.2 million, or $3.93 a share, compared with a net loss of $1.0
billion in the same period last year.
   The bank said its earnings in the latest quarter and six months
were due to increases in net interest income, trust fees and other
banking fees, gains from venture capital activities and higher
profits from bond trading.
   The company changed its name in late April from Chemical New
York Corp.
   Seventh-ranked Security Pacific reported a profit of $154.3
million, or $1.36 a share, compared to a net loss of $190.2 million
in the second quarter of last year.
   The 1987 second-quarter results were dragged down by a one-time
$558 million provision for bad loans to developing countries. This
year, the company has cut its non-trade developing country debts by
40 percent, said Chairman Richard J. Flamson III.
   In the latest quarter, the company posted net interest income of
$662.2 million, up from $599.1 million in the second quarter of
1987.
   For the first half of 1988, Los Angeles-based Security Pacific
had a net profit of $301.5 million, or $2.66 a share, compared with
a net loss of $73.7 million in the same period last year.
   Bank of New York, the long-time target of a hostile takeover bid
from Irving Bank Corp., said it earned $49.7 million, or $1.30 a
share, compared with a net loss of $34.9 million a year earlier.
   ``These results reflect strong growth in lending activities
accompanied with ... firm control of operating expenses,'' Chairman
J. Carter Bacot said in a statement. He said consumer lending was
especially strong during the latest quarter, rising 49 percent from
a year earlier.
   In the first six months, Bank of New York's net income totaled
$104.1 million, or $2.77 a share, up sharply from $12.4 million, or
34 cents a share, in first-half 1987.
</TEXT>
