<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Raytheon     07-14 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Raytheon,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raytheon Reports 10 Percent Increase in Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense contractor Raytheon Co. reported
a 10.4 percent increase in second-quarter earnings Thursday.
   The company said it had net income of $122.3 million, or $1.84
per share, up from $110.8 million, or $1.50 per share, for the
similar quarter a year ago. Sales were $2.04 billion, compared with
$1.92 billion during the second quarter of 1987.
   For the first six months of the year, earnings were $235.6
million, or $3.52 per share, on sales of $3.99 billion, up from
first half earnings of $212.6 million, or $2.87 per share, on sales
of $3.67 billion for 1987.
   Higher sales, improved operating performance and lower taxes all
contributed to the increase in company-wide earnings, Raytheon said.
   ``As we reported in the first quarter, Beech and Energy Services
have turned around,'' said Raytheon Chairman Thomas L. Phillips.
``As a result, all five business segments were again profitable in
the second quarter.''
   In addition, earnings per share were further improved by fewer
shares outstanding.
   This year, average shares outstanding were 66.6 million in the
second quarter and 66.9 million in the first half, compared with
73.8 million and 74 million respectively last year.
   In the second quarter, 938,700 shares were purchased, completing
the acquisition of 20 million shares previusly authorized by the
board of directors.
