<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dome-Amoco     07-14 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dome-Amoco,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Shareholder Challenge To Dome Acquisition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures are U.S.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CALGARY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled against a shareholder challenge to
Amoco Canada's $4.5 billion takeover of Dome Petroleum on Thursday,
and Amoco indicated it believed the transaction could be completed
within months.
   Justice Gregory Forsyth of Court of Queen's Bench ruled that the
acquisition was fair to all parties, and he saw no need for Amoco
to amend its buyout proposal.
   The ruling went against preferred shareholder Gordon Savage, who
headed the last of three shareholder groups _ including one headed
by Dome founder Jack Gallagher _ opposed to the transaction. The
other two bowed out about two weeks ago after accepting settlements
from Amoco.
   ``I have found...that the bid for Dome was done in a competitive
fashion and resulted in the best possible price,'' Forsyth ruled.
   Allan Sternberg, Savage's attorney, would not say whether he
will appeal the ruling. Sternberg had indicated during the fairness
hearing he would appeal any decision in favor of Dome-Amoco. He has
20 days to do so.
   Sternberg told reporters he wants to reserve comment until the
court decides who is responsible for costs in the case.
   T. Don Stacy, president of the U.S.-owned Amoco Canada, told
reporters the company was pleased with the decision, but noted
several hurdles remained before the merger could be completed.
   One issue is a $331 million loan to Dome by the Arctic Petroleum
Corp. of Japan. The consortium loaned Dome the money for Beaufort
Sea exploration and now seeks better repayment terms than Amoco is
offering.
   Asked if the consortium could still scuttle the entire deal,
Stacy said, ``Yes.'' But he said there had been progress in
resolving the matter.
   In a news release, Stacy said he hoped to close the Dome
acquisition next month.
   Bidding for Dome closed almost 15 months ago. Amoco hoped its
merger would be complete in six months, but that was before some of
the debt-ridden company's creditors and shareholders challenged the
move in court. Forsyth threw out the challenges one by one.
   The fairness hearing was the last legal obstacle to Amoco's
acquistion of Dome, which is about $5.2 billion in debt.
   Sternberg had argued that shareholders did not have complete
information when they voted 87 per cent in favor of the deal early
last month. He contended shareholders were unaware of an internal
Amoco document _ since made public _ showing the company estimated
Dome's value at up to $6 billion, and were unaware of a competing
$5.4 billion buyout offer by a group of Middle Eastern oilmen.
   Forsyth dismissed both claims, saying the competing offer was
``nothing more than a sham'' and that shareholder information
packages were prepared and distributed correctly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
