<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Reagan-Drought 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Drought, 1st Ld-Writethru,0991</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Pledges To Do `Everything We Can'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, ``Reagan, who ... with return to White House;
inserts dropped word ``percent'' in 17th graf, ``The Agriculture
... Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARION, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, lending moral support to
drought-stricken farmers while Congress mulls financial relief,
said Thursday the government must act quickly to help America cope
with the ``worst natural disaster since the Dust Bowl of the
1930s.''
   ``What I saw was not a pretty sight,'' Reagan said after walking
through sun-parched corn and soybean fields in his native Illinois.
``Stunted corn, sparse beanfields, withered plants starved for
water, struggling to push their way through.''
   He promised farmers that ``we will do everything that we can.''
At the same time, he called on Congress to ``act quickly'' on a
package of legislation aimed at making emergency federal aid
available to farmers.
   After inspecting fields on foot and by helicopter, the president
held up a portion of a corn stalk and told reporters, ``This is the
tassle, you see, but there's no silk yet.''
   Reagan, who returned to the White House in early evening, used
his tour to announce that he was dispatching Agriculture Secretary
Richard Lyng on a tour of several states hard hit by the dry spell.
   The president had planned several months ago to return to the
station that launched his radio career _ WOC in Davenport, Iowa _
and he kept that appointment Thursday, joining station executives
in marking its 65th anniversary of broadcasting.
   But if the radio station appearance presented Reagan with a
nostaligic return to his early days of radio in the 1930s, the
witnessing of the drought's effects also evoked thoughts about that
decade.
   ``From Montana to Texas, from California to Georgia, and right
here in Illinois, farmers face the worst natural disaster since the
Dust Bowl of the 1930s,'' Reagan told a group of state agriculture
officials and farmers gathered at the Du Quoin State Fairgrounds
near here.
   He voiced concern that a bipartisan farm aid program drafted by
leaders of the congressional agricultural committee might become
weighted down with special-interest amendments.
   Lawmakers earlier this week unveiled a $5.5 billion plan that
would provide payments of up to $100,000 to keep farmers on their
land despite the withering heat and lack of rain.
   ``There may be some very fine amendments that belong on the
bill,'' Reagan said, ``but also, every once in a while, it becomes
a Christmas tree, with people trying to attach things that really
have no bearing on the main purpose.''
   ``I'm calling today for Congress to act quickly on comprehensive
drought relief for all farmers, for all crops,'' he said.
   In an interview with WOC, Reagan said he is waiting for the farm
relief bill. ``I will sign it the minte it is delivered to me,'' he
said.
   The president touched on the bill again in a luncheon speech in
Davenport. ``Partisanship should be kept out of the issue of
drought relief,'' he said. ``Politics must stop at the parched
field's edge.''
   At the conclusion of his speech, the president was presented a
framed replica of a special edition of the front page of the Quad
City Times with photographs of him as a child of four in 1914, a
football star in 1927, a high-school graduate in 1928, on a
postcard in the late 1930s during his movie career, as governor of
California in 1967 and as president in 1988.
   He quipped, ``I was never as young as I am in some of those
pictures.''
   The Agriculture Department said Tuesday that the corn crop this
year may be 29 percent less than expected a few months ago, and 26
percent below last year's bumper harvest. It said sharp reductions
also are expected for 1988 wheat and soybean production.
   After landing at Williamson County Airport near here, Reagan
boarded his helicopter for a 25-minute aerial inspection of the
crop damage. The president, observed by reporters traveling in
another helicopter flying in a loose formation with Marine One,
could be seen looking out the window, occasionally gesturing toward
other passengers, as he witnessed the devastation.
   Once on the ground, he joined his farm hosts, Herman and Richard
Krone, for a walking tour of corn and soybean fields.
   Reagan, a six-footer, towered over the corn stalks, which
reached just past his waist. By this time of year, they should have
grown to eight feet.
   He then crossed a dirt road and walked through a soybean field,
which ad many gaping spots where there was nothing but soil.
   ``The situation on the ground, I'm sorry to say, is as bad as I
expected,'' the president said at the fairgrounds.
   Reagan said recent rains may have helped some, ``but it hasn't
solved the problem. And for many farmers, time has run out.''
   Noting that 1,973 counties in 38 states have qualified so far
for federal emergency agricultural disaster relief aid, he said,
``We can't make it rain, but we can help to ease the pain.''
   ``It will end. It always has in the past,'' Reagan said. ``But
the question is, when will it end and how much of the crop can be
saved.''
   ``I wanted to let you know that we will do everything that we
can,'' he said.
   Reagan, who doffed his suitcoat for the walking tour, drank iced
tea at a picnic table outside the Krones' farmhouse as he
commiserated with the father and son about the crop damage they
have suffered.
   Richard Krone, speaking just before Reagan went to the mike at
the fairgrounds, said, ``There's no one here looking for a handout.
These people here realize only so much can be done.''
</TEXT>
