<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-88 2305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SEC-PublicRecords     07-14 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SEC-Public Records,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Requests Investigation of SEC Restricting Access to
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The congressional watchdog agency was asked
Thursday to investigate complaints that the Securities and Exchange
Commission is restricting access to documents in its public
reference room.
   Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., chairman of the House Government
Operations subcommittee on government information, asked the
General Accounting Office, Congress' auditing wing, to look into
complaints about the commission's policy on how access is granted
to its records _ on paper and on microfiche _ of publicly traded
corporations.
   ``Users of the SEC reference room have charged that new access
regulations interfere with the public's right to know, threaten to
undermine investor protection, restrict the ability to gather news
about financial markets and provide de facto monopoly access to
timely financial data to a single company,'' English said in a
statement.
   Mary McCue, an SEC spokeswoman, said the agency keeps records on
paper for 30 days. After that, records are kept on microfiche.
Because over time the microfiche records have become disordered,
McCue said the agency decided last month to permit only SEC
employees to have access to those files.
   Reference room users now must fill out request forms for
microfiche and the goal is to supply it within one to four hours,
she said. There is still open access to paper records.
   However, Pat Clawson, Washington bureau chief of Radio and
Records, a weekly industry newspaper, said much longer delays of
eight hours or even several days are commonplace under the new
policy, compared with access within several minutes under the old
policy.
   ``These elongated time frames critically hamper newsgathering
activities pressured by deadlines,'' said Clawson, who is
organizing opposition to the new policy.
   The SEC actions ``represent a clear and present danger to the
public's right to know and threaten to undermine investor
protection,'' he said.
   He also charged that in many cases Bechtel Information Services,
a Gaithersburg, Md., firm which provides microfilming and copying
services under contract with the SEC, has the first access to
documents _ before the public reference room and before a press
room, which the SEC maintains for news organizations.
   Bechtel also sells copies of documents and thus competes with
about 23 other privately owned investor services which operate out
of the public reference room.
   Because Bechtel gets some documents first, ``you've got the
creation of a de facto monopoly here of the government's securities
files,'' Clawson said.
   McCue of the SEC said the Bechtel contract, which is renewable
annually, was awarded competitively and the commission reviews the
fees it charges to supply copies.
   She also blamed employees of the investor services, which
compete against one another, for misfiling and losing microfiche
files. She said the SEC has been unable to increase its reference
room staff even though the number of documents filed with the
commission and the number of people using the room have soared in
response to the boom in corporate takeovers and mergers.
   ``In an ideal world, we'd double the number of staff people we
have and double the size of the room. I'm afraid we don't live in
an ideal world,'' she said.
   Clawson, however, said the problem is ``rampant mismanagement on
the part of the SEC.''
